$40 − $24 = $16 change.","points":1},{"id":"Q33","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"area","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"A rectangle has an area of 63 square meters. If one side is 9 meters long, how long is the other side, in meters? Enter just the number.","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":7,"explanation":"Area = length × width, so 63 ÷ 9 = 7 meters.","points":1},{"id":"Q34","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"perimeter","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"What is the perimeter, in units, of this rectangle?","diagram":{"type":"rectangle","params":{"width":7,"height":3,"unit":"unit","showGrid":true,"label":"Pen"}},"options":["14 units","20 units","21 units","17 units"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Perimeter = 7 + 3 + 7 + 3 = 20 units. (Area would be 21, a common trap.)","points":1},{"id":"Q35","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"elapsed_time","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"Lunch started at 12:40 and ended at 1:15. How long did lunch last?","diagram":null,"options":["35 minutes","75 minutes","25 minutes","45 minutes"],"answer":0,"explanation":"From 12:40 to 1:00 is 20 minutes, and 1:00 to 1:15 is 15 minutes: 20 + 15 = 35 minutes.","points":1},{"id":"Q36","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"fractions","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"Which fraction is the greatest?","diagram":null,"options":["1/3","1/4","1/8","1/6"],"answer":0,"explanation":"When the top number is 1, the smaller the bottom number, the larger the fraction. 1/3 is the greatest because 3 is the smallest denominator.","points":1},{"id":"Q37","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"multiplication_facts","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Select all the expressions that equal 36.","diagram":null,"options":["3 × 12","5 × 7","6 × 6","4 × 9"],"answer":[0,2,3],"explanation":"6×6=36, 4×9=36, and 3×12=36. 5×7=35, so it is not correct.","points":1},{"id":"Q38","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"fractions","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"Select all the fractions that are equal to 1/3.","diagram":null,"options":["2/5","3/9","2/6","4/12"],"answer":[1,2,3],"explanation":"2/6, 3/9, and 4/12 each equal 1/3. 2/5 is more than 1/3.","points":1},{"id":"Q39","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"rounding","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"Select all the numbers that round to 400 when rounded to the nearest hundred.","diagram":null,"options":["438","451","352","349"],"answer":[0,2],"explanation":"352 and 438 each round to 400. 349 rounds to 300 and 451 rounds to 500.","points":1},{"id":"Q40","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"multi_step_word_problem","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"A store had 8 boxes of pencils with 9 pencils in each box. They sold 31 pencils. How many pencils are left? Enter just the number.","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":41,"explanation":"8 × 9 = 72 pencils; 72 − 31 = 41 left.","points":1}]}');
INSERT INTO "tests" ("id","grade","subject","test_type","title","time_limit_minutes","question_count","source","created_at","data") VALUES('g3-math-eog-7',3,'math','eog','Grade 3 Math — EOG Practice Test 7',120,40,'curated','2026-06-02T00:00:00.000Z','{"id":"g3-math-eog-7","grade":3,"subject":"math","testType":"eog","title":"Grade 3 Math — EOG Practice Test 7","instructions":"Read each question carefully. Choose the best answer. For gridded questions, enter just the number. For fill-in-the-blank equations, enter the number that makes the equation true.","timeLimitMinutes":120,"calculatorAllowed":false,"source":"curated","passages":[],"questions":[{"id":"Q1","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"multiplication","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"What multiplication fact does this array of dots show?","diagram":{"type":"array_dots","params":{"rows":6,"cols":5}},"options":["6 × 5 = 35","5 × 5 = 25","6 × 4 = 24","6 × 5 = 30"],"answer":3,"explanation":"There are 6 rows of 5 dots: 6 × 5 = 30.","points":1},{"id":"Q2","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"place_value","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"Which number is shown by these base-ten blocks?","diagram":{"type":"base_ten","params":{"hundreds":3,"tens":0,"ones":6}},"options":["36","360","3006","306"],"answer":3,"explanation":"3 hundreds, 0 tens, and 6 ones make 306.","points":1},{"id":"Q3","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"rounding","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"What is 84 rounded to the nearest ten?","diagram":null,"options":["100","90","80","85"],"answer":2,"explanation":"84 is closer to 80 than to 90, so it rounds to 80.","points":1},{"id":"Q4","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"fractions","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"What fraction of the circle is shaded?","diagram":{"type":"fraction_circle","params":{"parts":6,"shaded":2}},"options":["2/6","6/2","1/6","4/6"],"answer":0,"explanation":"2 of the 6 equal parts are shaded, so 2/6.","points":1},{"id":"Q5","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"time","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"What time does the clock show?","diagram":{"type":"clock","params":{"hour":4,"minute":45}},"options":["4:45","5:45","4:09","9:20"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The hour hand is almost to 5 and the minute hand points to 9, which is 45 minutes, so 4:45.","points":1},{"id":"Q6","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"subtraction","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"What is 524 − 187? Enter just the number.","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":337,"explanation":"524 − 187 = 337.","points":1},{"id":"Q7","itemType":"equation","skill":"multiplication","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"Fill in the blank to make the equation true.","template":"7 × ▢ = 63","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":9,"explanation":"63 ÷ 7 = 9.","points":1},{"id":"Q8","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"division","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"What is 42 ÷ 6?","diagram":null,"options":["6","7","8","9"],"answer":1,"explanation":"6 × 7 = 42, so 42 ÷ 6 = 7.","points":1},{"id":"Q9","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"fractions","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"Which comparison is true?","diagram":{"type":"fraction_bar","params":{"bars":[{"parts":4,"shaded":1,"label":"1/4"},{"parts":4,"shaded":3,"label":"3/4"}]}},"options":["1/4 < 3/4","1/4 = 3/4","3/4 < 1/4","1/4 > 3/4"],"answer":0,"explanation":"1/4 has fewer shaded parts than 3/4, so 1/4 < 3/4.","points":1},{"id":"Q10","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"geometry","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"How many sides does this shape have?","diagram":{"type":"shape","params":{"kind":"hexagon","sideLabels":["","","","","",""]}},"options":["5","7","6","8"],"answer":2,"explanation":"A hexagon has 6 sides.","points":1},{"id":"Q11","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"bar_graph","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"How many cans did Room 12 collect?","diagram":{"type":"bar_graph","params":{"title":"Cans Collected","xLabel":"Room","yLabel":"Cans","yMax":20,"yStep":4,"bars":[{"label":"Room 10","value":12},{"label":"Room 11","value":8},{"label":"Room 12","value":16}]}},"options":["12","8","16","20"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The bar for Room 12 reaches 16 on the scale.","points":1},{"id":"Q12","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"fractions","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"Which fraction does the point on the number line show?","diagram":{"type":"number_line","params":{"min":0,"max":1,"step":0.3333,"point":0.6667,"marks":[{"value":0,"label":"0"},{"value":1,"label":"1"}]}},"options":["1/2","2/3","1/3","3/3"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The number line is split into 3 equal parts and the point is at the second mark, which is 2/3.","points":1},{"id":"Q13","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"fractions","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"What fraction of this bar is shaded?","diagram":{"type":"fraction_bar","params":{"parts":8,"shaded":3}},"options":["3/5","8/3","5/8","3/8"],"answer":3,"explanation":"3 of the 8 equal parts are shaded, so 3/8.","points":1},{"id":"Q14","itemType":"equation","skill":"division","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"Fill in the blank to make the equation true.","template":"40 ÷ ▢ = 5","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":8,"explanation":"40 ÷ 8 = 5, so the blank is 8.","points":1},{"id":"Q15","itemType":"equation","skill":"addition","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"Fill in the blank to make the equation true.","template":"▢ + 29 = 64","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":35,"explanation":"64 − 29 = 35.","points":1},{"id":"Q16","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"multiplication","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"A box holds 6 rows of crayons with 9 crayons in each row. How many crayons are in the box? Enter just the number.","diagram":{"type":"array_dots","params":{"rows":6,"cols":9}},"options":[],"answer":54,"explanation":"6 × 9 = 54 crayons.","points":1},{"id":"Q17","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"fractions","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Which fraction is equivalent to 2/4?","diagram":{"type":"fraction_bar","params":{"bars":[{"parts":4,"shaded":2,"label":"2/4"},{"parts":2,"shaded":1,"label":"?"}]}},"options":["2/3","1/3","1/4","1/2"],"answer":3,"explanation":"2/4 covers the same amount as 1/2, so they are equivalent.","points":1},{"id":"Q18","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"elapsed_time","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Art class starts at the time shown and lasts 35 minutes. What time does it end?","diagram":{"type":"clock","params":{"hour":1,"minute":20}},"options":["1:55","1:35","2:05","1:50"],"answer":0,"explanation":"1:20 plus 35 minutes is 1:55.","points":1},{"id":"Q19","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"area","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"A poster is 7 feet long and 4 feet wide. What is its area, in square feet? Enter just the number.","diagram":{"type":"rectangle","params":{"width":7,"height":4,"unit":"ft","showGrid":true,"label":"Poster"}},"options":[],"answer":28,"explanation":"Area = 7 × 4 = 28 square feet.","points":1},{"id":"Q20","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"picture_graph","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Each star stands for 4 votes. How many votes did Blue get?","diagram":{"type":"picture_graph","params":{"title":"Class Vote","symbol":"⭐","unitValue":4,"rows":[{"label":"Red","count":5},{"label":"Blue","count":8},{"label":"Green","count":3}]}},"options":["24","32","8","12"],"answer":1,"explanation":"8 stars × 4 = 32 votes.","points":1},{"id":"Q21","itemType":"equation","skill":"subtraction","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"Fill in the blank to make the equation true.","template":"605 − ▢ = 358","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":247,"explanation":"605 − 358 = 247.","points":1},{"id":"Q22","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"geometry","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Select all the shapes that are quadrilaterals (shapes with exactly 4 sides).","diagram":{"type":"shape","params":{"kind":"rectangle","sideLabels":["","","",""]}},"options":["Rectangle","Triangle","Trapezoid","Hexagon"],"answer":[0,2],"explanation":"A trapezoid and a rectangle each have exactly 4 sides. A hexagon has 6 and a triangle has 3.","points":1},{"id":"Q23","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"fractions","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Which comparison is true?","diagram":{"type":"fraction_bar","params":{"bars":[{"parts":8,"shaded":2,"label":"2/8"},{"parts":8,"shaded":5,"label":"5/8"}]}},"options":["2/8 = 5/8","5/8 < 2/8","2/8 > 5/8","2/8 < 5/8"],"answer":3,"explanation":"With the same denominator, fewer shaded parts means less: 2/8 < 5/8.","points":1},{"id":"Q24","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"fractions","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Which fraction does the point on the number line show?","diagram":{"type":"number_line","params":{"min":0,"max":1,"step":0.1667,"point":0.8333,"marks":[{"value":0,"label":"0"},{"value":1,"label":"1"}]}},"options":["5/6","3/6","6/6","4/6"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The number line is split into 6 equal parts and the point is at the fifth mark, which is 5/6.","points":1},{"id":"Q25","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"fractions","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"There are 10 marbles in a bag. 7 of them are blue. What fraction of the marbles are blue?","diagram":null,"options":["10/7","3/10","7/3","7/10"],"answer":3,"explanation":"7 out of 10 marbles are blue, so 7/10.","points":1},{"id":"Q26","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"place_value","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"What is the value of the digit 5 in the number 458? Enter just the number.","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":50,"explanation":"The 5 is in the tens place, so its value is 50.","points":1},{"id":"Q27","itemType":"equation","skill":"multiplication","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Fill in the blank to make the equation true.","template":"▢ × 8 = 72","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":9,"explanation":"72 ÷ 8 = 9.","points":1},{"id":"Q28","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"properties","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Which expression has the same value as 8 × 4?","diagram":null,"options":["8 + 8 + 8","4 + 4 + 4","4 × 8","8 + 4"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Multiplication can be done in any order, so 4 × 8 = 8 × 4 = 32.","points":1},{"id":"Q29","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"patterns","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"In the counting pattern 6, 12, 18, 24, 30, ..., select all the numbers that belong in the pattern.","diagram":null,"options":["40","42","48","50"],"answer":[1,2],"explanation":"The pattern is multiples of 6. 42 and 48 are multiples of 6; 40 and 50 are not.","points":1},{"id":"Q30","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"mass","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"A bag of apples has a mass of 3 kilograms. A bag of oranges has a mass of 2 kilograms. What is the total mass of both bags?","diagram":null,"options":["23 kilograms","5 kilograms","6 kilograms","1 kilogram"],"answer":1,"explanation":"3 + 2 = 5 kilograms in all.","points":1},{"id":"Q31","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"liquid_volume","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"A pitcher holds 8 liters of juice. It is poured equally into 4 jars. How many liters are in each jar?","diagram":null,"options":["12 liters","2 liters","32 liters","4 liters"],"answer":1,"explanation":"8 ÷ 4 = 2 liters in each jar.","points":1},{"id":"Q32","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"multi_step_word_problem","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"A farmer planted 5 rows of corn with 8 plants in each row. Then 9 plants were eaten by deer. How many plants are left?","diagram":null,"options":["31","40","49","13"],"answer":0,"explanation":"5 × 8 = 40 plants; 40 − 9 = 31 plants left.","points":1},{"id":"Q33","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"multi_step_word_problem","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"Each book costs $6. Sam buys 4 books and pays with a $40 bill. How much change does he get back?","diagram":null,"options":["$46","$34","$16","$24"],"answer":2,"explanation":"4 × $6 = $24; $40 − $24 = $16 change.","points":1},{"id":"Q34","itemType":"equation","skill":"multiplication","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Fill in the blank to make the equation true.","template":"9 × ▢ = 63","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":7,"explanation":"63 ÷ 9 = 7.","points":1},{"id":"Q35","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"perimeter","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"What is the perimeter, in units, of this rectangle?","diagram":{"type":"rectangle","params":{"width":7,"height":3,"unit":"unit","showGrid":true,"label":"Pen"}},"options":["20 units","10 units","14 units","21 units"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Perimeter = 7 + 3 + 7 + 3 = 20 units. (Area would be 21, a common trap.)","points":1},{"id":"Q36","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"elapsed_time","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"A movie started at 2:45 and ended at 3:30. How long did the movie last?","diagram":null,"options":["85 minutes","15 minutes","45 minutes","30 minutes"],"answer":2,"explanation":"From 2:45 to 3:00 is 15 minutes, and 3:00 to 3:30 is 30 minutes: 15 + 30 = 45 minutes.","points":1},{"id":"Q37","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"fractions","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"Which fraction is the greatest?","diagram":null,"options":["1/10","1/3","1/6","1/8"],"answer":1,"explanation":"When the top number is 1, the smaller the bottom number, the larger the fraction. 1/3 is the greatest because 3 is the smallest denominator.","points":1},{"id":"Q38","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"multiplication_facts","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Select all the expressions that equal 36.","diagram":null,"options":["6 × 6","4 × 9","3 × 12","5 × 7"],"answer":[0,1,2],"explanation":"6×6=36, 4×9=36, and 3×12=36. 5×7=35, so it is not correct.","points":1},{"id":"Q39","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"fractions","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"Select all the fractions that are equal to a whole (1).","diagram":null,"options":["8/8","5/6","4/4","3/3"],"answer":[0,2,3],"explanation":"4/4, 3/3, and 8/8 each equal one whole because the top and bottom numbers are the same. 5/6 is less than one whole.","points":1},{"id":"Q40","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"multi_step_word_problem","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"A store had 8 packs of pencils with 9 pencils in each pack. They sold 35 pencils. How many pencils are left? Enter just the number.","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":37,"explanation":"8 × 9 = 72 pencils; 72 − 35 = 37 left.","points":1}]}');
INSERT INTO "tests" ("id","grade","subject","test_type","title","time_limit_minutes","question_count","source","created_at","data") VALUES('g3-math-moy-1',3,'math','moy','Grade 3 Math — Middle of Year (MOY) Test 1',90,30,'curated','2026-06-02T00:00:00.000Z','{"id":"g3-math-moy-1","grade":3,"subject":"math","testType":"moy","title":"Grade 3 Math — Middle of Year (MOY) Test 1","instructions":"Read each question carefully. Choose the best answer. For type-in questions, write only the number. For equation questions, write the number that belongs in the box.","timeLimitMinutes":90,"calculatorAllowed":false,"source":"curated","passages":[],"questions":[{"id":"Q1","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"multiplication","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"What is 7 × 8?","diagram":null,"options":["54","56","48","63"],"answer":1,"explanation":"7 groups of 8 is 56.","points":1},{"id":"Q2","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"multiplication","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"The dots below are arranged in equal rows. How many dots are there in all?","diagram":{"type":"array_dots","params":{"rows":3,"cols":6}},"options":["18","12","24","9"],"answer":0,"explanation":"3 rows of 6 is 3 × 6 = 18 dots.","points":1},{"id":"Q3","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"division","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"What is 48 ÷ 6? Type your answer.","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":8,"explanation":"48 shared into 6 equal groups is 8 in each group.","points":1},{"id":"Q4","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"multiplication","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Which multiplication fact matches the array shown below?","diagram":{"type":"array_dots","params":{"rows":6,"cols":7}},"options":["7 × 7 = 49","5 × 7 = 35","6 × 6 = 36","6 × 7 = 42"],"answer":3,"explanation":"There are 6 rows with 7 dots each, so 6 × 7 = 42.","points":1},{"id":"Q5","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"division","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"A teacher has 63 crayons. She puts them into bags of 9 crayons each. How many bags can she fill?","diagram":null,"options":["9","8","6","7"],"answer":3,"explanation":"63 ÷ 9 = 7 bags.","points":1},{"id":"Q6","itemType":"equation","skill":"multiplication","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"Fill in the blank to make the equation true.","diagram":null,"template":"9 × ▢ = 54","options":[],"answer":6,"explanation":"54 ÷ 9 = 6.","points":1},{"id":"Q7","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"multiplication_properties","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Select all the expressions that have the same value as 4 × 6.","diagram":null,"options":["4 × 5","6 + 6 + 6 + 6","4 + 6","6 × 4"],"answer":[1,3],"explanation":"4 × 6 = 24. 6 × 4 = 24 (order does not change the product) and 6 + 6 + 6 + 6 = 24 (four groups of 6). But 4 + 6 = 10 and 4 × 5 = 20, so those are not correct.","points":1},{"id":"Q8","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"division","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"A baker has 72 rolls. She packs the same number into each of 8 baskets. How many rolls are in each basket? Type your answer.","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":9,"explanation":"72 ÷ 8 = 9 rolls in each basket.","points":1},{"id":"Q9","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"two_step_word_problem","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"A library has 8 shelves with 5 books on each shelf. Then 9 more books are added. How many books are there now?","diagram":null,"options":["49","45","40","54"],"answer":0,"explanation":"First 8 × 5 = 40 books. Then 40 + 9 = 49 books.","points":1},{"id":"Q10","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"two_step_word_problem","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"Noah has 6 boxes of markers with 8 markers in each box. He gives away 7 markers. How many markers does he have left? Type your answer.","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":41,"explanation":"First 6 × 8 = 48 markers. Then 48 − 7 = 41 markers left.","points":1},{"id":"Q11","itemType":"equation","skill":"division","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Fill in the blank to make the equation true.","diagram":null,"template":"56 ÷ ▢ = 7","options":[],"answer":8,"explanation":"56 ÷ 8 = 7, so the box is 8.","points":1},{"id":"Q12","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"arithmetic_patterns","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"Look at the pattern: 5, 10, 15, 20, 25, ... The numbers increase by 5 each time. Select all the statements that are true about every number in this pattern.","diagram":null,"options":["They are all greater than 20","They are all multiples of 5","They are all odd","They all end in 0 or 5"],"answer":[1,3],"explanation":"Every multiple of 5 ends in 0 or 5 and is a multiple of 5. They are not all greater than 20 (for example 5), and they are not all odd (for example 10).","points":1},{"id":"Q13","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"fractions_number_line","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"What fraction does the point show on the number line?","diagram":{"type":"number_line","params":{"min":0,"max":1,"step":0.25,"point":0.75,"marks":[{"value":0,"label":"0"},{"value":1,"label":"1"}]}},"options":["2/4","1/4","4/4","3/4"],"answer":3,"explanation":"The number line is split into 4 equal parts. The point is on the 3rd mark, so it is 3/4.","points":1},{"id":"Q14","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"fractions_bar","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"What fraction of the bar is shaded?","diagram":{"type":"fraction_bar","params":{"parts":6,"shaded":4}},"options":["2/6","4/2","4/6","6/4"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The bar has 6 equal parts and 4 are shaded, so 4/6 is shaded.","points":1},{"id":"Q15","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"fractions_circle","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"What fraction of the circle is shaded?","diagram":{"type":"fraction_circle","params":{"parts":3,"shaded":2}},"options":["3/2","2/3","3/3","1/3"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The circle has 3 equal parts and 2 are shaded, so 2/3 is shaded.","points":1},{"id":"Q16","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"fractions_equivalent","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Which fraction is equal to 1/2?","diagram":{"type":"fraction_bar","params":{"bars":[{"parts":2,"shaded":1,"label":"A"},{"parts":4,"shaded":2,"label":"B"}]}},"options":["1/4","3/4","2/4","2/2"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Bar A shows 1/2 shaded and Bar B shows 2/4 shaded with the same amount, so 2/4 = 1/2.","points":1},{"id":"Q17","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"fractions_compare","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"Two bars are the same size. The first bar is split into 6 equal parts. The second bar is split into 3 equal parts. Which statement is true?","diagram":{"type":"fraction_bar","params":{"bars":[{"parts":6,"shaded":1,"label":"sixths"},{"parts":3,"shaded":1,"label":"thirds"}]}},"options":["1/6 is equal to 1/3","You cannot compare them","1/6 is greater than 1/3","1/6 is less than 1/3"],"answer":3,"explanation":"When a whole is split into 6 parts, each part is smaller than when it is split into 3 parts. So 1/6 is less than 1/3.","points":1},{"id":"Q18","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"fractions_whole","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Which fraction is equal to the whole number 3?","diagram":null,"options":["3/1","1/3","3/6","3/3"],"answer":0,"explanation":"3/1 means 3 wholes, because 3 ÷ 1 = 3. So 3/1 = 3.","points":1},{"id":"Q19","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"fractions_of_set","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"There are 15 stickers. One fifth (1/5) of them are gold. How many stickers are gold? Type your answer.","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":3,"explanation":"To find 1/5 of 15, divide 15 into 5 equal groups: 15 ÷ 5 = 3 gold stickers.","points":1},{"id":"Q20","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"fractions_equivalent","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"Select all the fractions that are equal to 1/3.","diagram":null,"options":["4/12","2/3","3/9","2/6"],"answer":[0,2,3],"explanation":"2/6, 3/9, and 4/12 all equal 1/3. But 2/3 is twice as much as 1/3, so it is not correct.","points":1},{"id":"Q21","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"area","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"Each square is 1 square unit. What is the area of the rectangle?","diagram":{"type":"rectangle","params":{"width":5,"height":3,"unit":"units","showGrid":true,"label":"Tile"}},"options":["15 square units","16 square units","8 square units","18 square units"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Area = length × width = 5 × 3 = 15 square units.","points":1},{"id":"Q22","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"perimeter","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"What is the perimeter of the rectangle?","diagram":{"type":"rectangle","params":{"width":8,"height":4,"unit":"cm","showGrid":false,"label":"Frame"}},"options":["20 cm","12 cm","24 cm","32 cm"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Perimeter = 8 + 4 + 8 + 4 = 24 cm.","points":1},{"id":"Q23","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"area","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"A rug is 9 feet long and 4 feet wide. What is the area of the rug in square feet? Type your answer.","diagram":{"type":"rectangle","params":{"width":9,"height":4,"unit":"ft","showGrid":false,"label":"Rug"}},"options":[],"answer":36,"explanation":"Area = 9 × 4 = 36 square feet.","points":1},{"id":"Q24","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"area_perimeter","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"A rectangle is 8 cm long and 3 cm wide. Which statement is true about its area and perimeter?","diagram":{"type":"rectangle","params":{"width":8,"height":3,"unit":"cm","showGrid":false,"label":"Strip"}},"options":["The area is 24 sq cm and the perimeter is 11 cm","The area is 24 sq cm and the perimeter is 22 cm","The area is 22 sq cm and the perimeter is 24 cm","The area and perimeter are both 24"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Area = 8 × 3 = 24 square cm. Perimeter = 8 + 3 + 8 + 3 = 22 cm.","points":1},{"id":"Q25","itemType":"equation","skill":"addition","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Fill in the blank to make the equation true.","diagram":null,"template":"▢ + 36 = 62","options":[],"answer":26,"explanation":"62 − 36 = 26, so the box is 26.","points":1},{"id":"Q26","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"time","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"What time does the clock show?","diagram":{"type":"clock","params":{"hour":3,"minute":15}},"options":["3:15","3:03","3:45","4:15"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The minute hand points to 3, which is 15 minutes. The hour hand is just past 3, so the time is 3:15.","points":1},{"id":"Q27","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"elapsed_time","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"A movie starts at 2:45 and lasts 40 minutes. What time does the movie end?","diagram":{"type":"clock","params":{"hour":2,"minute":45}},"options":["3:15","3:05","3:25","2:85"],"answer":2,"explanation":"From 2:45, add 15 minutes to reach 3:00, then 25 more minutes to reach 3:25. So the movie ends at 3:25.","points":1},{"id":"Q28","itemType":"equation","skill":"subtraction","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Fill in the blank to make the equation true.","diagram":null,"template":"84 − ▢ = 57","options":[],"answer":27,"explanation":"84 − 57 = 27, so the box is 27.","points":1},{"id":"Q29","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"bar_graph","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"The bar graph shows how many books each student read. How many books did the three students read in all?","diagram":{"type":"bar_graph","params":{"title":"Books Read","xLabel":"Student","yLabel":"Books","yMax":20,"yStep":5,"bars":[{"label":"Ava","value":10},{"label":"Ben","value":15},{"label":"Cara","value":5}]}},"options":["20","30","25","35"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Ava read 10, Ben read 15, and Cara read 5. 10 + 15 + 5 = 30 books in all.","points":1},{"id":"Q30","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"rounding","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"What is 552 rounded to the nearest hundred?","diagram":{"type":"number_line","params":{"min":500,"max":600,"step":10,"point":552,"marks":[{"value":500,"label":"500"},{"value":550,"label":"550"},{"value":600,"label":"600"}]}},"options":["550","600","500","560"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The halfway point between 500 and 600 is 550. Since 552 is just above 550, it rounds up to 600.","points":1}]}');
INSERT INTO "tests" ("id","grade","subject","test_type","title","time_limit_minutes","question_count","source","created_at","data") VALUES('g3-math-moy-2',3,'math','moy','Grade 3 Math — Middle of Year (MOY) Test 2',90,30,'curated','2026-06-02T00:00:00.000Z','{"id":"g3-math-moy-2","grade":3,"subject":"math","testType":"moy","title":"Grade 3 Math — Middle of Year (MOY) Test 2","instructions":"Read each question carefully. Choose the best answer. For type-in questions, write only the number. For fill-in-the-blank equations, write the number that makes the equation true.","timeLimitMinutes":90,"calculatorAllowed":false,"source":"curated","passages":[],"questions":[{"id":"Q1","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"multiplication","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"What is 4 × 7?","diagram":null,"options":["21","24","32","28"],"answer":3,"explanation":"4 groups of 7 is 28.","points":1},{"id":"Q2","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"multiplication","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"The dots below are arranged in equal rows. How many dots are there in all?","diagram":{"type":"array_dots","params":{"rows":6,"cols":3}},"options":["18","9","15","21"],"answer":0,"explanation":"6 rows of 3 is 6 × 3 = 18 dots.","points":1},{"id":"Q3","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"division","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"What is 45 ÷ 9?","diagram":null,"options":["7","5","6","4"],"answer":1,"explanation":"45 shared into 9 equal groups is 5 in each group.","points":1},{"id":"Q4","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"multiplication","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Which multiplication fact matches the array shown below?","diagram":{"type":"array_dots","params":{"rows":7,"cols":5}},"options":["8 × 5 = 40","6 × 5 = 30","7 × 4 = 28","7 × 5 = 35"],"answer":3,"explanation":"There are 7 rows with 5 dots each, so 7 × 5 = 35.","points":1},{"id":"Q5","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"division","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Lucas has 63 marbles. He puts them into 7 equal bags. How many marbles are in each bag? Type your answer.","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":9,"explanation":"63 ÷ 7 = 9 marbles in each bag.","points":1},{"id":"Q6","itemType":"equation","skill":"multiplication","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"Fill in the blank to make the equation true.","diagram":null,"template":"9 × ▢ = 72","options":[],"answer":8,"explanation":"72 ÷ 9 = 8.","points":1},{"id":"Q7","itemType":"equation","skill":"division","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Fill in the blank to make the equation true.","diagram":null,"template":"56 ÷ ▢ = 8","options":[],"answer":7,"explanation":"56 ÷ 7 = 8, so the blank is 7.","points":1},{"id":"Q8","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"multiplication_properties","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Select all the expressions that have the same value as 6 × 7.","diagram":null,"options":["6 + 7","6 × 6","6 + 6 + 6 + 6 + 6 + 6 + 6","7 × 6"],"answer":[2,3],"explanation":"6 × 7 = 42. 7 × 6 = 42 (order does not change the product), and 6 added 7 times = 42. But 6 × 6 = 36 and 6 + 7 = 13, so those are not correct.","points":1},{"id":"Q9","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"two_step_word_problem","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"A garden has 8 rows of carrots with 5 carrots in each row. Then 7 carrots are picked. How many carrots are left in the garden? Type your answer.","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":33,"explanation":"First 8 × 5 = 40 carrots. Then 40 − 7 = 33 carrots left.","points":1},{"id":"Q10","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"two_step_word_problem","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"Nina buys 6 boxes of crayons with 8 crayons in each box. She gives 9 crayons to her brother. How many crayons does she have left? Type your answer.","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":39,"explanation":"First 6 × 8 = 48 crayons. Then 48 − 9 = 39 crayons left.","points":1},{"id":"Q11","itemType":"equation","skill":"addition","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Fill in the blank to make the equation true.","diagram":null,"template":"▢ + 46 = 73","options":[],"answer":27,"explanation":"73 − 46 = 27, so the blank is 27.","points":1},{"id":"Q12","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"fractions_number_line","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"What fraction does the point show on the number line?","diagram":{"type":"number_line","params":{"min":0,"max":1,"step":0.25,"point":0.5,"marks":[{"value":0,"label":"0"},{"value":1,"label":"1"}]}},"options":["2/4","1/4","4/4","3/4"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The number line is split into 4 equal parts. The point is on the 2nd mark, so it is 2/4.","points":1},{"id":"Q13","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"fractions_bar","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"What fraction of the bar is shaded?","diagram":{"type":"fraction_bar","params":{"parts":4,"shaded":3}},"options":["4/3","1/4","3/4","2/4"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The bar has 4 equal parts and 3 are shaded, so 3/4 is shaded.","points":1},{"id":"Q14","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"fractions_circle","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"What fraction of the circle is shaded?","diagram":{"type":"fraction_circle","params":{"parts":6,"shaded":4}},"options":["2/6","4/4","4/6","6/4"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The circle has 6 equal parts and 4 are shaded, so 4/6 is shaded.","points":1},{"id":"Q15","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"fractions_equivalent","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Which fraction is equal to 1/4?","diagram":{"type":"fraction_bar","params":{"bars":[{"parts":4,"shaded":1,"label":"A"},{"parts":8,"shaded":2,"label":"B"}]}},"options":["2/8","3/8","1/8","2/4"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Bar A shows 1/4 shaded and Bar B shows 2/8 shaded with the same amount, so 2/8 = 1/4.","points":1},{"id":"Q16","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"fractions_compare","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"Two same-size pizzas are cut into equal slices. One is cut into 6 slices and one is cut into 8 slices. Which is true about ONE slice from each pizza?","diagram":{"type":"fraction_bar","params":{"bars":[{"parts":6,"shaded":1,"label":"1/6"},{"parts":8,"shaded":1,"label":"1/8"}]}},"options":["1/6 is bigger than 1/8","1/6 is the same as 1/8","1/6 is smaller than 1/8","You cannot tell"],"answer":0,"explanation":"When a pizza is cut into fewer slices, each slice is bigger. 6 slices are bigger than 8 slices, so 1/6 is bigger than 1/8.","points":1},{"id":"Q17","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"fractions_of_set","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"There are 20 grapes. One fourth (1/4) of them are green. How many grapes are green? Type your answer.","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":5,"explanation":"To find 1/4 of 20, divide 20 into 4 equal groups: 20 ÷ 4 = 5 green grapes.","points":1},{"id":"Q18","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"fractions_equivalent","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"Select all the fractions that are equal to one whole.","diagram":null,"options":["5/5","2/4","6/6","3/3"],"answer":[0,2,3],"explanation":"When the top number equals the bottom number, the fraction equals one whole: 3/3, 5/5, and 6/6 all equal 1. But 2/4 equals one half, so it is not correct.","points":1},{"id":"Q19","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"area","difficulty":"easy","passageId":null,"questionText":"Each square is 1 square unit. What is the area of the rectangle?","diagram":{"type":"rectangle","params":{"width":4,"height":3,"unit":"units","showGrid":true,"label":"Tile"}},"options":["12 square units","14 square units","7 square units","10 square units"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Area = length × width = 4 × 3 = 12 square units.","points":1},{"id":"Q20","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"perimeter","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"What is the perimeter of the rectangle?","diagram":{"type":"rectangle","params":{"width":8,"height":5,"unit":"cm","showGrid":false,"label":"Window"}},"options":["21 cm","26 cm","13 cm","40 cm"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Perimeter = 8 + 5 + 8 + 5 = 26 cm.","points":1},{"id":"Q21","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"area_perimeter","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"A rectangle is 10 cm long and 3 cm wide. Which statement is true about its area and perimeter?","diagram":{"type":"rectangle","params":{"width":10,"height":3,"unit":"cm","showGrid":false,"label":"Banner"}},"options":["The area is 13 sq cm and the perimeter is 30 cm","The area is 30 sq cm and the perimeter is 26 cm","The area and perimeter are both 30","The area is 26 sq cm and the perimeter is 30 cm"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Area = 10 × 3 = 30 square cm. Perimeter = 10 + 3 + 10 + 3 = 26 cm.","points":1},{"id":"Q22","itemType":"equation","skill":"subtraction","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Fill in the blank to make the equation true.","diagram":null,"template":"90 − ▢ = 58","options":[],"answer":32,"explanation":"90 − 58 = 32, so the blank is 32.","points":1},{"id":"Q23","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"elapsed_time","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"A library program starts at 3:40 and lasts 35 minutes. What time does it end?","diagram":{"type":"clock","params":{"hour":3,"minute":40}},"options":["3:75","4:05","4:35","4:15"],"answer":3,"explanation":"From 3:40, add 20 minutes to reach 4:00, then 15 more minutes to reach 4:15. So it ends at 4:15.","points":1},{"id":"Q24","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"elapsed_time","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Lunch begins at 11:35 and ends at 12:10. How many minutes long is lunch? Type your answer.","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":35,"explanation":"From 11:35 to 12:00 is 25 minutes, then 10 more minutes to 12:10 makes 35 minutes.","points":1},{"id":"Q25","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"bar_graph","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"The bar graph shows how many shells each child found. How many shells did Tara and Omar find altogether?","diagram":{"type":"bar_graph","params":{"title":"Shells Found","xLabel":"Child","yLabel":"Shells","yMax":20,"yStep":5,"bars":[{"label":"Tara","value":15},{"label":"Omar","value":10},{"label":"Kim","value":5}]}},"options":["30","5","25","20"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Tara found 15 shells and Omar found 10 shells. 15 + 10 = 25 shells altogether.","points":1},{"id":"Q26","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"picture_graph","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"Each ⚽ stands for 3 goals. How many more goals did the Tigers score than the Lions?","diagram":{"type":"picture_graph","params":{"title":"Goals Scored","symbol":"⚽","unitValue":3,"rows":[{"label":"Lions","count":4},{"label":"Tigers","count":7},{"label":"Bears","count":5}]}},"options":["12","3","21","9"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Tigers scored 7 balls = 7 × 3 = 21 goals. Lions scored 4 balls = 4 × 3 = 12 goals. 21 − 12 = 9 more goals.","points":1},{"id":"Q27","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"place_value","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"What number do the base-ten blocks show?","diagram":{"type":"base_ten","params":{"hundreds":5,"tens":3,"ones":0}},"options":["350","530","503","53"],"answer":1,"explanation":"5 hundreds, 3 tens, and 0 ones make 500 + 30 + 0 = 530.","points":1},{"id":"Q28","itemType":"equation","skill":"multiplication","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Fill in the blank to make the equation true.","diagram":null,"template":"4 × 8 = ▢ + 12","options":[],"answer":20,"explanation":"4 × 8 = 32, and 32 = 20 + 12, so the blank is 20.","points":1},{"id":"Q29","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"rounding","difficulty":"medium","passageId":null,"questionText":"Select all the numbers that round to 600 when rounded to the nearest hundred.","diagram":null,"options":["549","638","561","652"],"answer":[1,2],"explanation":"561 and 638 are between 550 and 649, so they round to 600. But 549 rounds to 500 and 652 rounds to 700, so those are not correct.","points":1},{"id":"Q30","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"rounding","difficulty":"hard","passageId":null,"questionText":"What is 352 rounded to the nearest hundred?","diagram":{"type":"number_line","params":{"min":300,"max":400,"step":10,"point":352,"marks":[{"value":300,"label":"300"},{"value":350,"label":"350"},{"value":400,"label":"400"}]}},"options":["360","350","400","300"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The halfway point between 300 and 400 is 350. Since 352 is just above 350, it rounds up to 400.","points":1}]}');
INSERT INTO "tests" ("id","grade","subject","test_type","title","time_limit_minutes","question_count","source","created_at","data") VALUES('g3-math-sample-mpz0t167',3,'math','eog','Grade 3 Math — 2025-26 Released Form',120,40,'sample','2026-06-04T04:54:45.704Z','{"id":"g3-math-sample-mpz0t167","grade":3,"subject":"math","testType":"eog","title":"Grade 3 Math — 2025-26 Released Form","instructions":"Released-form sample. Choose the best answer for each question.","timeLimitMinutes":120,"calculatorAllowed":true,"source":"sample","createdAt":"2026-06-04T04:54:45.704Z","passages":[],"questions":[{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Which circle has the same amount shaded as this figure?","options":["A","B","C","D"],"diagram":{"type":"image","params":{"src":"/sample-img/g3-math-sample-mpz0t167/Q1.png","alt":"A circle divided into four equal parts with two parts shaded."}},"skill":"fractions","id":"Q1","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":3,"explanation":"Circle D has the same amount shaded as the figure because it shows the same proportion of shading compared to the whole circle."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Savion has trouble remembering the product of 6 × 9. Which is another way for Savion to solve this multiplication problem?","options":["A  6 × 4 + 6 × 5","B  6 × 6 + 6 × 9","C  9 × 6 + 6 × 9","D  9 × 3 + 6 × 9"],"diagram":null,"skill":"multiplication strategies","id":"Q2","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"Savion can solve 6 × 9 by breaking it into smaller parts like 6 × 4 and 6 × 5, which are easier to calculate and then add together to get the same answer."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"What value for d makes this equation correct? 7 = d ÷ 3","options":["A  4","B  10","C  21","D  28"],"diagram":null,"skill":"division equations","id":"Q3","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"To find d in the equation 7 = d ÷ 3, we can multiply both sides by 3, which gives us d = 21, making the equation true."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"What is the distance between X and Y on this number line?","options":["A  1/3","B  2/3","C  3/2","D  3/1"],"diagram":{"type":"image","params":{"src":"/sample-img/g3-math-sample-mpz0t167/Q4.png","alt":"A number line from 0 to 1 with points X and Y marked."}},"skill":"number line fractions","id":"Q4","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"The distance between X and Y is 1/3 because you can count the spaces on the number line between them, and that’s how far apart they are."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"There are 32 students sitting at tables in the lunchroom. There are 2 tables that have 10 students each. The other students are sitting at an extra table. Which equation can be used to find the number of students, s, sitting at the extra table?","options":["A  2 + 10 + 32 = s","B  2 × 10 + 32 = s","C  s + 2 + 10 = 32","D  2 × 10 + s = 32"],"diagram":null,"skill":"equations","id":"Q5","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":3,"explanation":"The equation 2 × 10 + s = 32 helps us find how many students are at the extra table by adding the students at the two tables to the extra table''s students to equal the total."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Four friends drank equal shares of the fruit juice in this container. How much fruit juice did each friend get?","options":["A  6 oz","B  5 oz","C  4 oz","D  3 oz"],"diagram":{"type":"image","params":{"src":"/sample-img/g3-math-sample-mpz0t167/Q6.png","alt":"A container with markings at 10 oz and 20 oz."}},"skill":"division","id":"Q6","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"Each friend got 4 oz of juice because when you divide the total amount of juice by the number of friends, you find out how much each one gets."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"David drove on a road trip: • 198 miles on the first day, and • 134 miles on the second day. How many miles did David drive over both days, rounded to the nearest ten?","options":["A  310 miles","B  320 miles","C  330 miles","D  340 miles"],"diagram":null,"skill":"rounding","id":"Q7","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"David drove a total of 330 miles over both days because when you add 198 and 134, you get 332, and rounding that to the nearest ten gives you 330."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Sue used 42 apples to make pies. Six apples were needed to make one pie. How many pies did Sue make?","options":["A  8","B  6","C  9","D  7"],"diagram":null,"skill":"division","id":"Q8","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":3,"explanation":"Sue made 7 pies because when you divide the 42 apples by the 6 apples needed for each pie, you find out how many complete pies she could make."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"In this equation, the △ represents a number.\n\n7 × △ = 63\n\nIn which choice does the △ represent the same number?","options":["A 63 ÷ 7 = △","B 7 ÷ △ = 63","C 7 ÷ 63 = △","D △ ÷ 7 = 63"],"diagram":null,"skill":"equations","id":"Q9","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"In the equation 7 × △ = 63, △ is the same as 63 ÷ 7 because that shows how many times 7 fits into 63, which gives us the same number for △."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Matt will put all of his cards into his card book.\n\n• He has 81 baseball cards.\n• Each page of the book holds 9 cards.\n\nWhat is the fewest number of pages Matt can use to put all of his cards into the book?","options":["A 8","B 9","C 10","D 11"],"diagram":null,"skill":"division","id":"Q10","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"Matt can use 9 pages because when you divide 81 cards by 9 cards per page, you find out that he needs exactly 9 pages to hold all his cards."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Which fraction has a value of 4?","options":["A 1/4","B 1/3","C 4/4","D 16/4"],"diagram":null,"skill":"fractions","id":"Q11","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":3,"explanation":"16 divided by 4 equals 4, which means 16/4 is the same as 4. So, D) 16/4 is correct because it equals 4!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"A plane flew 336 miles on Monday and 476 miles on Tuesday. Approximately how many miles did the plane fly, rounded to the nearest hundred?","options":["A 700 miles","B 730 miles","C 800 miles","D 830 miles"],"diagram":null,"skill":"rounding","id":"Q12","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"When we add 336 and 476, we get 812. Rounding 812 to the nearest hundred gives us 800, so C) 800 miles is the right choice!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Erin and her four friends have 45 pencils. They will share them equally. How many pencils will each friend get?","options":["A 9","B 8","C 7","D 6"],"diagram":null,"skill":"division","id":"Q13","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"To share 45 pencils equally among Erin and her four friends, we divide 45 by 5 (because there are 5 people). Each person gets 9 pencils, so A) 9 is correct!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Ryan wants to paint one of his walls with red paint, white paint, and blue paint, as shown.\n\nWhat fraction of the wall will be painted blue?","options":["A 1/6","B 1/4","C 1/3","D 1/2"],"diagram":{"type":"image","params":{"src":"/sample-img/g3-math-sample-mpz0t167/Q14.png","alt":"Wall divided into sections labeled Red, White, Blue"}},"skill":"fractions","id":"Q14","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"If the wall is divided into 4 equal parts and 2 parts are shaded, that means 2 out of 4 parts are blue. This simplifies to 1/2, but since the question asks for 1/4 shaded, B) 1/4 is the right answer!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"What number makes this equation true?\n\n9 × △ = 72","options":["A 6","B 7","C 8","D 9"],"diagram":null,"skill":"equations","id":"Q15","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"To find the missing number in the equation 9 times something equals 72, we can divide 72 by 9. That gives us 8, so C) 8 is the correct answer!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"There are 40 rows of seats in a theater. There are 9 seats in each row. How many seats are in the theater?","options":["A 49 seats","B 130 seats","C 360 seats","D 380 seats"],"diagram":null,"skill":"multiplication","id":"Q16","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"To find the total number of seats in the theater, we multiply the number of rows (40) by the number of seats in each row (9). That gives us 360, so C) 360 seats is correct!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Sara will shade 2 parts of each circle below. Which circle will have 1/3 shaded?","options":["A","B","C","D"],"diagram":{"type":"image","params":{"src":"/sample-img/g3-math-sample-mpz0t167/Q17.png","alt":"Four circles divided into parts"}},"skill":"fractions","id":"Q17","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":3,"explanation":"If Sara shades 2 parts of a circle and we want to know which circle has 1/3 shaded, we need to look for a circle divided into 3 equal parts. D) is the one that has 1/3 shaded!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Melvin planted 24 flowers in 4 equal rows. Which number sentence finds out how many plants, p, are in each row?","options":["A 24 ÷ 4 = p","B 4 ÷ p = 24","C 24 × 4 = p","D p × 24 = 4"],"diagram":null,"skill":"equations","id":"Q18","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"To find out how many plants are in each row, we need to divide the total number of flowers (24) by the number of rows (4). So, A) 24 ÷ 4 = p is the right choice!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Which model is 1/4 shaded?","options":["A","B","C","D"],"diagram":{"type":"image","params":{"src":"/sample-img/g3-math-sample-mpz0t167/Q19.png","alt":"Four rectangular grids with different shaded areas"}},"skill":"fractions","id":"Q19","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"We need to find a model that shows 1 out of 4 equal parts shaded. C) is the model that shows exactly that, so it is correct!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Adam has 49 cards and James has 28 cards. How many more cards are needed for them to have 111 cards altogether?","options":["A 34 cards","B 36 cards","C 44 cards","D 46 cards"],"diagram":null,"skill":"addition","id":"Q20","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"To find out how many more cards Adam and James need to reach 111 cards, we first add their cards together (49 + 28 = 77) and then subtract that from 111, which gives us 34. So, A) 34 cards is the right answer!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"A multiplication chart is shown. Which statement is always true and is illustrated by the shaded portion of the chart?","options":["A The product of two even numbers is divisible by 6.","B The product of two odd numbers is odd.","C The product of an even number and an odd number is odd.","D The product of two odd numbers is divisible by 5."],"diagram":{"type":"image","params":{"src":"/sample-img/g3-math-sample-mpz0t167/Q21.png","alt":"Multiplication chart with shaded portion."}},"skill":"multiplication properties","id":"Q21","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"When you multiply two odd numbers, like 3 and 5, the result is always odd, like 15. This is true for any odd numbers, so option B is correct!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"There are 7 parking spaces in each row of a parking lot. There are 8 rows. A total of 39 parking spaces are full. How many parking spaces are empty?","options":["A 10","B 13","C 15","D 17"],"diagram":null,"skill":"subtraction and multiplication","id":"Q22","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":3,"explanation":"First, we find the total number of parking spaces by multiplying 7 spaces per row by 8 rows, which gives us 56 spaces. If 39 are full, we subtract that from 56, leaving us with 17 empty spaces, so option D is right!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"A rectangular bedroom is 12 feet long and 10 feet wide. What is the perimeter of the bedroom?","options":["A 22 feet","B 44 feet","C 100 feet","D 120 feet"],"diagram":null,"skill":"perimeter of rectangles","id":"Q23","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"To find the perimeter of a rectangle, we add all the sides together. For a rectangle that is 12 feet long and 10 feet wide, the perimeter is 12 + 10 + 12 + 10, which equals 44 feet, making option B correct!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"This bar graph shows the number of people who attended a school play. How many fewer people attended on Sunday than on Saturday?","options":["A 30","B 40","C 50","D 130"],"diagram":{"type":"image","params":{"src":"/sample-img/g3-math-sample-mpz0t167/Q24.png","alt":"Bar graph showing school play attendance."}},"skill":"bar graph interpretation","id":"Q24","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"To find out how many fewer people attended on Sunday than Saturday, we look at the numbers on the graph. If 100 people came on Saturday and 50 on Sunday, we subtract 50 from 100, which gives us 50 fewer people, so option C is right!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Four students were trying to find the area of this rectangle. Whose strategies would find the correct area of the rectangle?","options":["A Kendra’s and Jason’s","B Jason’s and Ali’s","C Ali’s and Melvin’s","D Kendra’s and Melvin’s"],"diagram":{"type":"image","params":{"src":"/sample-img/g3-math-sample-mpz0t167/Q25.png","alt":"Rectangle with grid."}},"skill":"area of rectangles","id":"Q25","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"Jason and Ali both used the correct method to find the area of the rectangle. They multiplied the length by the width, which is the right way to find area, so option B is correct!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Which fraction is represented by the distance from H to J?","options":["A 1/3","B 2/6","C 3/6","D 3/3"],"diagram":{"type":"image","params":{"src":"/sample-img/g3-math-sample-mpz0t167/Q26.png","alt":"Number line from 0 to 1 with points H and J."}},"skill":"fractions on a number line","id":"Q26","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"The distance from H to J represents the fraction of the whole. If there are 6 equal parts and 3 of them are counted, that means it is 3 out of 6, or 3/6, so option C is correct!"},{"itemType":"numeric_entry","questionText":"Which fraction model shows 1/3 shaded?","options":[],"diagram":{"type":"image","params":{"src":"/sample-img/g3-math-sample-mpz0t167/Q27.png","alt":"Four fraction models with different shadings."}},"skill":"fraction models","id":"Q27","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":"D","explanation":"The model that shows 1/3 shaded must have 1 out of 3 equal parts filled in. Option D shows exactly that, so it is the correct choice!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"A pentagon has sides with equal lengths. The perimeter of the pentagon is 35 units. How long is each side?","options":["A 6 units","B 7 units","C 8 units","D 9 units"],"diagram":null,"skill":"perimeter","id":"Q28","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"A pentagon has 5 equal sides, and if the total perimeter is 35 units, we divide that by 5 to find the length of each side, which is 7 units, so option B is correct!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"The fourth- and fifth-grade classes at an elementary school made $674 altogether at a school yard sale. The fifth-grade classes made $391. How much money did the fourth-grade classes make?","options":["A $1,065","B $965","C $323","D $283"],"diagram":null,"skill":"subtraction","id":"Q29","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":3,"explanation":"To find out how much money the fourth-grade classes made, we subtract the fifth-grade amount from the total. So, $674 - $391 equals $283, making option D the right answer!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Which statement is true about these shapes?","options":["A Both shapes have four vertices.","B Both shapes have four equal sides.","C Both shapes have slanted lines.","D Both shapes have two sets of parallel lines."],"diagram":{"type":"image","params":{"src":"/sample-img/g3-math-sample-mpz0t167/Q30.png","alt":"two quadrilateral shapes"}},"skill":"geometry","id":"Q30","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"Both shapes have four corners, which we call vertices. Since they both have four vertices, option A is the correct statement!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Mike runs 4 miles a day. How many days will it take him to run 20 miles?","options":["A 4","B 5","C 16","D 24"],"diagram":null,"skill":"division","id":"Q31","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"To find out how many days it takes Mike to run 20 miles, we divide 20 by 4 because he runs 4 miles each day. So, 20 divided by 4 equals 5 days!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"An art teacher had 18 feet of string. She gave the string to 9 students to share equally. How many feet of string did each student get?","options":["A 2","B 3","C 27","D 36"],"diagram":null,"skill":"division","id":"Q32","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"The teacher had 18 feet of string and shared it with 9 students equally. When we divide 18 by 9, each student gets 2 feet of string."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"A fraction of this figure is shaded. Which choice is a fraction that is less than the shaded fraction of the figure?","options":["A 2/3","B 2/8","C 2/2","D 2/4"],"diagram":{"type":"image","params":{"src":"/sample-img/g3-math-sample-mpz0t167/Q33.png","alt":"hexagon divided into six triangles, three shaded"}},"skill":"fractions","id":"Q33","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"The fraction 2/8 is less than the shaded fraction because it shows a smaller part of a whole compared to the other options. It’s like having fewer slices of pizza!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"A rectangular garden is shown. What is the area of the garden?","options":["A 17 square feet","B 34 square feet","C 72 square feet","D 81 square feet"],"diagram":{"type":"image","params":{"src":"/sample-img/g3-math-sample-mpz0t167/Q34.png","alt":"rectangle labeled 8 feet by 9 feet"}},"skill":"area","id":"Q34","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"To find the area of the rectangular garden, we multiply the length by the width. If the area is 72 square feet, it means the garden is big enough to fit that many squares inside it!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"On which number line does n have a value of 2/6 ?","options":["A","B","C","D"],"diagram":{"type":"image","params":{"src":"/sample-img/g3-math-sample-mpz0t167/Q35.png","alt":"four number lines with different positions for n"}},"skill":"fractions","id":"Q35","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"The number line that shows n as 2/6 is A because it correctly represents that fraction in the right spot on the line."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Victoria has a refrigerator with 2 rectangular doors that are the same size. What is the total area of both doors if one door is 5 feet tall and 2 feet wide?","options":["A 7 square feet","B 10 square feet","C 14 square feet","D 20 square feet"],"diagram":null,"skill":"area","id":"Q36","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":3,"explanation":"Each door of the refrigerator is 5 feet tall and 2 feet wide, so we find the area of one door by multiplying 5 by 2, which is 10 square feet. Since there are two doors, we double that to get 20 square feet!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Which choice will make the diagram shown true?","options":["A","B","C","D"],"diagram":{"type":"image","params":{"src":"/sample-img/g3-math-sample-mpz0t167/Q37.png","alt":"two circles divided into equal parts, one shaded more than the other"}},"skill":"fractions","id":"Q37","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"The choice that makes the diagram true is A because it fits perfectly with what the diagram is showing, just like a puzzle piece!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Which fraction is represented by point M on this number line?","options":["A 1/3","B 3/4","C 7/9","D 6/4"],"diagram":{"type":"image","params":{"src":"/sample-img/g3-math-sample-mpz0t167/Q38.png","alt":"Number line with point M"}},"skill":"fractions on a number line","id":"Q38","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"Point M on the number line represents the fraction 3/4 because it is located three-quarters of the way between 0 and 1, showing a larger part of the whole."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Joel hiked for 45 minutes. He finished hiking at the time shown. At what time did Joel begin hiking?","options":["A 5:10 p.m.","B 5:45 p.m.","C 6:10 p.m.","D 6:40 p.m."],"diagram":{"type":"image","params":{"src":"/sample-img/g3-math-sample-mpz0t167/Q39.png","alt":"Clock showing 6:55"}},"skill":"elapsed time","id":"Q39","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"If Joel hiked for 45 minutes and finished at a certain time, we can subtract 45 minutes from that time to find when he started. So, he began hiking at 5:10 p.m.!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"A farmer put 8 large boxes of apples into a truck. There are 80 apples in each box. How many apples did the farmer put into the truck altogether?","options":["A 72","B 88","C 640","D 720"],"diagram":null,"skill":"multiplication","id":"Q40","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"The farmer put 8 boxes of apples in the truck, and since each box has 80 apples, we multiply 8 by 80 to find the total, which is 640 apples altogether!"}]}');
INSERT INTO "tests" ("id","grade","subject","test_type","title","time_limit_minutes","question_count","source","created_at","data") VALUES('g3-read-boy-1',3,'reading','boy','Grade 3 Reading — Beginning of Grade (BOG) Test 1',90,32,'curated','2026-06-02T00:00:00.000Z','{"id":"g3-read-boy-1","grade":3,"subject":"reading","testType":"boy","title":"Grade 3 Reading — Beginning of Grade (BOG) Test 1","instructions":"Read each selection carefully. Then choose the best answer for each question. Some questions ask you to select more than one answer.","timeLimitMinutes":90,"calculatorAllowed":false,"source":"curated","passages":[{"id":"P1","title":"The New Bike","genre":"fiction","lexile":"480L","text":"Part 1\n\nSam wanted to ride a bike more than anything. His older sister, Lena, could ride down the whole block without falling. Sam still used training wheels. Every time he watched Lena zoom past, his cheeks turned warm.\n\n\"I will never learn,\" Sam said one morning. He kicked a small rock across the driveway.\n\nLena sat down next to him. \"I fell a hundred times before I could ride,\" she said. \"Falling is how you learn. Do you want me to help you?\"\n\nSam nodded slowly. He was not sure he believed her, but he wanted to try.\n\nPart 2\n\nLena took off Sam''s training wheels with a wrench. Then she held the back of the seat. \"I have you,\" she said. \"Just push the pedals and look straight ahead.\"\n\nSam pushed. The bike wobbled. He pushed again, and the bike rolled forward. Lena jogged behind him, keeping her hand on the seat.\n\nThen Sam felt something change. The seat felt light. He looked back and saw Lena standing far behind him, smiling and waving. She had let go, and he was riding all by himself!\n\nSam was so surprised that he forgot to steer. The bike tipped, and he landed softly in the grass. But he was laughing.\n\n\"You did it!\" Lena shouted, running to him. \"You rode by yourself!\"\n\nSam stood up and brushed the grass off his knees. His cheeks were warm again, but this time it was from pride. \"Let''s go again,\" he said. \"I want to ride all the way down the block.\""},{"id":"P2","title":"Animals That Glow","genre":"informational","lexile":"560L","text":"Part 1\n\nHave you ever seen a tiny light blink in the dark on a summer night? That light may come from a firefly. Some animals can make their own light. This special light is called bioluminescence. It does not feel hot like a lamp. Instead, it is a cool light that the animal makes inside its body.\n\nFireflies are not the only animals that glow. Deep in the ocean, where sunlight cannot reach, many sea creatures make light too. The water there is dark and cold. Glowing helps these animals live in a world without sunlight.\n\nPart 2\n\nWhy would an animal make light? Animals glow for different reasons. A firefly flashes its light to send a message to other fireflies. The flashes help fireflies find a mate in the dark.\n\nSome fish use light in a clever way. The anglerfish has a glowing part that hangs in front of its mouth, like a tiny fishing pole. Smaller fish swim toward the light because they are curious. When they get close, the anglerfish catches them. The glowing light helps the anglerfish find food.\n\nOther sea animals use light to stay safe. When a tiny shrimp is in danger, it can squirt out a cloud of glowing liquid. The bright cloud surprises the hungry animal chasing it. While the predator is confused, the shrimp swims away and hides.\n\nMaking light is a useful tool. It helps animals talk to one another, find a meal, and escape from danger. The next time you see a firefly blink, remember that it is sending a tiny message in the dark."},{"id":"P3","title":"George Washington Carver and the Peanut","genre":"informational","lexile":"600L","text":"Part 1\n\nGeorge Washington Carver was a scientist who loved plants. He was born long ago, when life was very hard for many people. As a child, George was so curious about growing things that neighbors called him \"the plant doctor.\" He would visit sick plants and find ways to help them grow strong again.\n\nWhen George grew up, he taught at a school in Alabama. There he saw a big problem. Many farmers in the South grew only cotton. Growing the same crop year after year took all the goodness out of the soil. The tired soil could no longer grow healthy cotton, and the farmers were poor and worried.\n\nPart 2\n\nGeorge had an idea. He told the farmers to plant peanuts instead of cotton for a while. Peanuts put goodness back into the soil. The next year, the soil would be rich again, and the cotton would grow better.\n\nThe farmers tried his idea, and it worked. But soon there was a new problem. The farmers had grown so many peanuts that they could not sell them all. Boxes of peanuts sat unused.\n\nGeorge went to work in his laboratory. He studied the peanut and found hundreds of new ways to use it. He showed people how to make soap, glue, ink, and even a kind of milk from peanuts. Because of his work, peanuts became useful and valuable.\n\nGeorge Washington Carver helped farmers in two ways. He helped the soil become healthy, and he helped people find new uses for their crops. He spent his life solving problems with the plants he loved."},{"id":"P4","title":"The Garden in Spring","genre":"poetry","lexile":"450L","text":"Part 1\n\nThe garden wakes when winter ends,\nand soft green shoots push through.\nThe sleepy seeds I planted deep\nhave heard the springtime, too.\n\nThe robin hops from branch to branch\nand sings a cheerful tune.\nThe sun climbs higher every day\nand warms the earth by noon.\n\nPart 2\n\nI water rows of little plants\nand pull the weeds away.\nI watch them stretch and reach for light\na little more each day.\n\nThe peas climb up their wooden poles,\nthe carrots hide below.\nWith sun and rain and gentle care,\nmy garden starts to grow.\n\nSo I will wait and tend it well,\nthrough every sunny hour.\nFor seeds that wait beneath the ground\nwill someday be a flower."}],"questions":[{"id":"Q1","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P1","questionText":"At the beginning of the story, what does Sam want to do more than anything?","diagram":null,"options":["Win a race against Lena","Fix his sister''s bike","Ride a bike like his sister","Plant a garden"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The first sentence says Sam wanted to ride a bike more than anything.","points":1},{"id":"Q2","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P1","questionText":"According to the story, what does Lena do to Sam''s bike before he rides it?","diagram":null,"options":["She puts air in the tires.","She adds a basket to the front.","She paints the bike a new color.","She takes off the training wheels."],"answer":3,"explanation":"In Part 2, Lena took off Sam''s training wheels with a wrench.","points":1},{"id":"Q3","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Which word BEST describes Lena in this story?","diagram":null,"options":["Shy","Helpful","Selfish","Angry"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Lena offers to help Sam, holds his seat, and cheers for him, which shows she is helpful.","points":1},{"id":"Q4","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Read this sentence from Part 1: \"Every time he watched Lena zoom past, his cheeks turned warm.\" What does the word \"zoom\" mean here?","diagram":null,"options":["Turn around slowly","Fall down hard","Stop and rest","Move by quickly"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Lena could ride the whole block, so \"zoom past\" means she moved by quickly.","points":1},{"id":"Q5","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What happens right AFTER Sam feels the seat become light?","diagram":null,"options":["He looks back and sees that Lena let go.","He decides he will never learn.","He puts the training wheels back on.","He kicks a rock across the driveway."],"answer":0,"explanation":"After the seat felt light, Sam looked back and saw Lena standing far behind him because she had let go.","points":1},{"id":"Q6","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"At the end, the story says Sam''s \"cheeks were warm again, but this time it was from pride.\" Why are his cheeks warm for a different reason now?","diagram":null,"options":["He is angry because Lena let go too soon.","He is cold because he sat in the wet grass.","He is embarrassed because he fell in the grass.","He is proud because he rode the bike by himself."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Earlier his cheeks turned warm from embarrassment, but now they are warm from pride because he rode by himself.","points":1},{"id":"Q7","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What is the main lesson, or theme, of this story?","diagram":null,"options":["Bikes are safer with training wheels on them.","Older sisters always ride faster than younger brothers.","It is better to give up than to keep trying.","Trying and falling can help you learn something new."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Lena says falling is how you learn, and Sam learns to ride after wobbling and tipping over, showing the theme that trying and falling help you learn.","points":1},{"id":"Q8","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What does Sam want to do at the very end of the story?","diagram":null,"options":["Ride all the way down the block","Put the training wheels back on","Go inside and rest","Watch Lena ride instead"],"answer":0,"explanation":"At the end Sam says, \"I want to ride all the way down the block.\"","points":1},{"id":"Q9","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"bioluminescence\" as it is used in Part 1?","diagram":null,"options":["A summer night when fireflies sleep","A cool light that an animal makes inside its body","A deep part of the ocean with no fish","A hot lamp that people turn on at night"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 1 says bioluminescence is a cool light that the animal makes inside its body.","points":1},{"id":"Q10","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P2","questionText":"According to the text, why does a firefly flash its light?","diagram":null,"options":["To send a message to other fireflies","To help people see in the dark","To dry the water off its wings","To keep itself warm at night"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Part 2 says a firefly flashes its light to send a message to other fireflies.","points":1},{"id":"Q11","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"How does the anglerfish use its glowing light?","diagram":null,"options":["To scare away larger fish that chase it","To warm the cold ocean water around it","To light up the path back to its nest","To attract smaller fish so it can catch them"],"answer":3,"explanation":"The text says smaller fish swim toward the light, and when they get close, the anglerfish catches them.","points":1},{"id":"Q12","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.2","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What is the main idea of this text?","diagram":null,"options":["Fireflies are the only animals that can glow at night.","Some animals make their own light, and it helps them in different ways.","The ocean is too dark and cold for any animal to live in.","People should catch fireflies to use as lamps."],"answer":1,"explanation":"The whole text explains that some animals make light and how that light helps them, which is the main idea.","points":1},{"id":"Q13","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What does a tiny shrimp do when it is in danger?","diagram":null,"options":["It swims toward a bigger, brighter light.","It hangs a glowing pole in front of its mouth.","It squirts out a cloud of glowing liquid.","It flashes its light to call for help."],"answer":2,"explanation":"The text says when a shrimp is in danger, it can squirt out a cloud of glowing liquid to surprise the animal chasing it.","points":1},{"id":"Q14","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"How does the author connect the ideas in the paragraphs of Part 2?","diagram":null,"options":["By comparing the ocean to a summer night","By showing what happens before and after sunset","By giving different reasons that animals glow","By telling the steps to catch a firefly in order"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Each paragraph in Part 2 gives a different reason animals glow: to send messages, to find food, and to stay safe.","points":1},{"id":"Q15","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Which sentence from the text BEST supports the idea that glowing helps animals stay safe?","diagram":null,"options":["\"The glowing light helps the anglerfish find food.\"","\"While the predator is confused, the shrimp swims away and hides.\"","\"The flashes help fireflies find a mate in the dark.\"","\"It does not feel hot like a lamp.\""],"answer":1,"explanation":"The shrimp escaping while the predator is confused best shows how glowing keeps an animal safe.","points":1},{"id":"Q16","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Select the two reasons the text gives for why animals make light.","diagram":null,"options":["To turn off the sunlight in the deep sea","To send messages, like the firefly does","To make the ocean water warmer","To find food, like the anglerfish does"],"answer":[1,3],"explanation":"The text says animals glow to find food (the anglerfish) and to send messages (the firefly). It does not say glowing warms the water or turns off sunlight.","points":1},{"id":"Q17","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What did neighbors call George Washington Carver when he was a child?","diagram":null,"options":["\"The peanut seller\"","\"The cotton farmer\"","\"The plant doctor\"","\"The school teacher\""],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 1 says neighbors called George \"the plant doctor\" because he was so curious about growing things.","points":1},{"id":"Q18","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"According to the text, why was the soil in the South tired and poor?","diagram":null,"options":["The farmers planted peanuts every year.","No one watered the fields in the summer.","Too much rain washed the soil away.","Farmers grew only cotton year after year."],"answer":3,"explanation":"The text says growing the same crop, cotton, year after year took all the goodness out of the soil.","points":1},{"id":"Q19","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"In Part 2, the text says peanuts became \"valuable.\" What does \"valuable\" mean?","diagram":null,"options":["Very hard to grow","Easy to throw away","Worth a lot and useful","Small and round"],"answer":2,"explanation":"After George found hundreds of uses for peanuts, they became worth a lot and useful, which is what \"valuable\" means.","points":1},{"id":"Q20","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What did George tell the farmers to do to help the tired soil?","diagram":null,"options":["Stop farming and sell their land","Plant peanuts instead of cotton for a while","Add more cotton to the fields","Water the soil with peanut milk"],"answer":1,"explanation":"George told the farmers to plant peanuts instead of cotton because peanuts put goodness back into the soil.","points":1},{"id":"Q21","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the connection between the farmers growing too many peanuts and George working in his laboratory?","diagram":null,"options":["The farmers worked in the laboratory with George.","The new problem led George to find new uses for peanuts.","George grew the extra peanuts in his laboratory.","George studied cotton instead of peanuts."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Because the farmers grew more peanuts than they could sell, George went to his laboratory and found hundreds of new uses for them, showing cause and effect.","points":1},{"id":"Q22","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the main idea of this text?","diagram":null,"options":["Farmers should always sell their crops in boxes.","Cotton is the most important crop in the South.","Peanuts are the easiest plants for children to grow.","George Washington Carver used his love of plants to solve problems for farmers."],"answer":3,"explanation":"The text describes how George solved the soil problem and the unused-peanut problem, showing he used his love of plants to help farmers.","points":1},{"id":"Q23","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"Which sentence from the text BEST supports the idea that George helped farmers in more than one way?","diagram":null,"options":["\"He helped the soil become healthy, and he helped people find new uses for their crops.\"","\"Boxes of peanuts sat unused.\"","\"He was born long ago, when life was very hard for many people.\"","\"When George grew up, he taught at a school in Alabama.\""],"answer":0,"explanation":"This sentence directly states the two ways George helped farmers: healthy soil and new uses for crops.","points":1},{"id":"Q24","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.2","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is one product the text says people learned to make from peanuts?","diagram":null,"options":["Soap","Wood","Cotton","Snow"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The text says George showed people how to make soap, glue, ink, and even a kind of milk from peanuts.","points":1},{"id":"Q25","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P4","questionText":"In the poem, what wakes up when winter ends?","diagram":null,"options":["The garden","The snow","The moon","The wind"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The first line says, \"The garden wakes when winter ends.\"","points":1},{"id":"Q26","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P4","questionText":"According to the poem, what does the speaker do to take care of the little plants?","diagram":null,"options":["Carries them inside the house","Waters them and pulls the weeds","Cuts them down and dries them","Covers them with snow"],"answer":1,"explanation":"In Part 2 the speaker says, \"I water rows of little plants / and pull the weeds away.\"","points":1},{"id":"Q27","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"Read these lines: \"The peas climb up their wooden poles, / the carrots hide below.\" What does it mean that the carrots \"hide below\"?","diagram":null,"options":["The carrots climb the wooden poles too.","The carrots run away from the garden.","The carrots grow under the ground.","The carrots are scared of the peas."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Carrots grow under the ground, so saying they \"hide below\" means they grow below the soil.","points":1},{"id":"Q28","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"L.3.5.a","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"Read this line from the poem: \"The sleepy seeds I planted deep / have heard the springtime, too.\" What does the poet mean by calling the seeds \"sleepy\"?","diagram":null,"options":["The seeds were planted by a sleeping person.","The seeds are too tired to ever grow.","The seeds have been resting and are now starting to grow.","The seeds make a soft sound at night."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Calling the seeds \"sleepy\" and saying they \"heard the springtime\" shows the seeds were resting and are now waking up to grow.","points":1},{"id":"Q29","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"What is the main message of the poem?","diagram":null,"options":["With care and patience, a garden will grow over time.","Winter is the best season for planting seeds.","Robins keep the garden from growing.","Gardens grow best when no one takes care of them."],"answer":0,"explanation":"The speaker waters, weeds, and waits, and the poem ends saying the seeds will someday be a flower, showing that care and patience help a garden grow.","points":1},{"id":"Q30","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.5","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"How is the poem organized?","diagram":null,"options":["It follows the garden as it grows from seeds to plants.","It lists the names of every flower in the world.","It tells about one single rainy day.","It compares two different gardens."],"answer":0,"explanation":"The poem moves from the garden waking and seeds sprouting to plants growing and finally becoming a flower, following the garden as it grows.","points":1},{"id":"Q31","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"Select the two things the poem says the speaker watches happen in the garden.","diagram":null,"options":["The garden fills with snow.","The plants stretch and reach for light.","The wooden poles grow taller.","The robin hops and sings."],"answer":[1,3],"explanation":"The poem says the robin hops from branch to branch and sings, and that the speaker watches the plants stretch and reach for light. The garden does not fill with snow, and the poles do not grow.","points":1},{"id":"Q32","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.9","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"Use both parts of this text to answer this question. How are Part 1 and Part 2 of the poem alike?","diagram":null,"options":["Both parts tell about a robin building a nest.","Both parts show the garden coming to life in spring.","Both parts list reasons not to plant a garden.","Both parts describe a cold and snowy winter day."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 1 shows the garden waking and seeds sprouting, and Part 2 shows the plants growing with care; both parts show the garden coming to life in spring.","points":1}]}');
INSERT INTO "tests" ("id","grade","subject","test_type","title","time_limit_minutes","question_count","source","created_at","data") VALUES('g3-read-eog-1',3,'reading','eog','Grade 3 Reading — EOG Practice Test 1',120,40,'curated','2026-06-02T00:00:00.000Z','{"id":"g3-read-eog-1","grade":3,"subject":"reading","testType":"eog","title":"Grade 3 Reading — EOG Practice Test 1","instructions":"Read each selection. Some selections have two parts. Read each question carefully and choose the best answer. For questions that say \"Select all that apply,\" mark every correct answer.","timeLimitMinutes":120,"calculatorAllowed":false,"source":"curated","passages":[{"id":"P1","title":"The Lopsided Pot","genre":"fiction","lexile":"560L","text":"Part 1\n\nNina sat at the spinning wheel in her grandmother''s pottery shop. All her cousins could make smooth, round bowls. Their pots stood in a neat row on the shelf, shining like new moons. Nina''s pots always leaned to one side.\n\n\"Mine is lopsided again,\" Nina groaned, pushing the wet clay away. \"I will never be good at this.\"\n\nGrandmother wiped her hands on her apron and came to sit beside her. \"When I was your age,\" she said softly, \"my pots leaned more than yours do now. A pot is not ruined because it leans. Sometimes a lean is the start of something new.\"\n\nNina did not believe her. She watched her cousin Theo lift a perfect, even pot from the wheel. Everyone clapped. Nina hid her crooked pot behind a sack of dry clay where no one could see it.\n\nPart 2\n\nThe next week, a flood of rain swept through the village. Water rushed into the shop and knocked the neat row of round pots to the floor. They cracked and broke into pieces. When the family came back, the shelf was bare.\n\nThen Grandmother reached behind the sack of dry clay. She pulled out Nina''s lopsided pot, dry and whole. The lean had let the pot rest against the wall, so it had not rolled off the shelf and shattered.\n\n\"This crooked little pot is the only one that lasted,\" Grandmother said, holding it up to the light. The cousins gathered around to look. Theo smiled at Nina. \"Show me how you made it lean like that,\" he said.\n\nNina laughed. She no longer wished her pot looked like everyone else''s. For the first time, she was glad it was her own."},{"id":"P2","title":"The Smallest Helper","genre":"fiction","lexile":"530L","text":"Part 1\n\nIn the warm grass of the meadow lived a colony of ants. Every ant had a job. The big ants carried heavy seeds. The fast ants ran messages from one tunnel to the next. But Pip was the smallest ant of all, and no job seemed to fit her.\n\n\"You are too little to carry a seed,\" said a big ant.\n\n\"You are too slow to run a message,\" said a fast ant.\n\nPip felt useless. She wandered to the far edge of the meadow, where the other ants rarely went. There she found a thin crack in the dry earth, and from it came the cool smell of water.\n\nPart 2\n\nThat summer, the meadow grew dry as dust. The stream the ants drank from shrank to a trickle and then to nothing. The big ants and the fast ants searched everywhere, but they were too large to squeeze into the narrow places where water might hide.\n\nPip remembered the crack at the edge of the meadow. She slipped easily through the tiny gap, down into the cool dark, and there she found a hidden pool of clean water. She hurried back and led the others to the spot.\n\nOne by one, the bigger ants tried to follow her down, but only Pip was small enough to fit. So Pip carried water up, drop by drop, until the whole colony had enough to drink.\n\n\"Being small,\" said the oldest ant, \"turned out to be exactly the right size.\" Pip glowed with pride. She had a job after all, and it was a job only she could do."},{"id":"P3","title":"The Journey of a Raindrop","genre":"informational","lexile":"600L","text":"Part 1\n\nHave you ever wondered where rain comes from, or where it goes after it falls? Water is always moving in a great loop called the water cycle. The same water has been traveling around our planet for millions of years.\n\nThe journey begins with the sun. The sun heats the water in oceans, lakes, and rivers. When water gets warm enough, it turns into a gas called water vapor and rises into the air. This step is called evaporation. You cannot see water vapor, but it is all around you.\n\nHigh in the sky, the air is cold. The cold air cools the water vapor and turns it back into tiny drops of water. Millions of these tiny drops gather together to form clouds. This step is called condensation.\n\nPart 2\n\nClouds drift across the sky, pushed by the wind. Inside a cloud, the tiny water drops bump into one another and join. Slowly the drops grow heavier and heavier. When they become too heavy to float, they fall to the earth as rain, snow, or hail. This step is called precipitation.\n\nOnce the water reaches the ground, its journey is still not over. Some water soaks deep into the soil. Some flows downhill into streams and rivers, which carry it back to the ocean. Then the sun warms the water again, and the whole cycle starts over.\n\nThe water cycle never stops, and it never wastes a single drop. The rain that splashes on your window today may have fallen on a forest long ago, or even on the dinosaurs millions of years before that."},{"id":"P4","title":"The Lighthouse Keeper of Long Ago","genre":"informational","lexile":"620L","text":"Part 1\n\nLong before bright electric lights and computers, ships at sea faced great danger near the shore. Hidden rocks and shallow water could crack a ship''s wooden hull and sink it. To keep sailors safe, people built tall towers called lighthouses along the coast. At the top of each tower burned a strong light to warn ships away from danger.\n\nBut a lighthouse light did not shine by itself. A person called a lighthouse keeper had to care for it. The keeper lived in a small house beside the tower, often far from any town. Every evening at sunset, the keeper climbed a long, winding staircase to light the lamp. The lamp burned oil, so the keeper carried heavy buckets of oil up the stairs again and again.\n\nPart 2\n\nThe keeper''s work was never done. The glass around the light had to be cleaned each day, because smoke and salt would dim its glow. If the light grew weak, a ship might not see the warning in time.\n\nDuring storms, the keeper''s job became the hardest of all. Wind shook the tower and rain pounded the windows, yet the keeper stayed awake all night to keep the flame burning. Sailors out on the dark water trusted that light to guide them home. Many keepers said they could not sleep until the sun rose and the danger passed.\n\nToday, machines run most lighthouses, and keepers are no longer needed. But long ago, the steady glow of a lighthouse was the work of one brave person climbing the stairs, night after night, so that strangers at sea would be safe."},{"id":"P5","title":"The Garden After Rain","genre":"poetry","lexile":"480L","text":"Part 1\n\nThe storm has packed its bags and gone,\nthe gray clouds rolled away.\nThe garden lifts its dripping head\nto greet the washed-bright day.\n\nEach leaf is wearing little jewels\nthat sparkle, shake, and slide.\nA spider mends her broken web\nwith patience and with pride.\n\nPart 2\n\nThe worms come up to taste the air,\nthe robins hop and sing.\nThe puddles hold a piece of sky,\na small and shining thing.\n\nSo do not frown when raindrops fall\nand hide the sun from view—\nfor every storm that comes to pass\nleaves something fresh and new."}],"questions":[{"id":"Q1","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P1","questionText":"According to the text, why does Nina hide her pot behind the sack of dry clay?","diagram":null,"options":["She wants to keep it safe from the coming flood.","She thinks it is the best pot in the whole shop.","She does not want anyone to see that it is crooked.","She is saving it as a gift for her grandmother."],"answer":2,"explanation":"In Part 1 Nina hides her crooked pot \"where no one could see it,\" because she is ashamed it is lopsided. She does not yet know a flood is coming.","points":1},{"id":"Q2","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Which word BEST describes how Nina feels at the beginning of the story?","diagram":null,"options":["Bored","Frightened","Cheerful","Discouraged"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Nina groans, pushes the clay away, and says she will never be good at pottery, showing she feels discouraged.","points":1},{"id":"Q3","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"lopsided\" in paragraph 1 of Part 1?","diagram":null,"options":["Leaning more to one side than the other","Very large and heavy","Smooth and perfectly round","Painted in bright colors"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The text contrasts the cousins'' \"smooth, round bowls\" with Nina''s pots, which \"always leaned to one side,\" so lopsided means leaning to one side.","points":1},{"id":"Q4","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What happens to the neat row of round pots during the flood?","diagram":null,"options":["They fall to the floor and break into pieces.","They are sold quickly before the rain comes.","They float safely on top of the water.","Grandmother carries them out of the shop."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Part 2 says the water \"knocked the neat row of round pots to the floor\" and \"they cracked and broke into pieces.\"","points":1},{"id":"Q5","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Why does Nina''s lopsided pot survive the flood when the others do not?","diagram":null,"options":["It was too heavy for the rushing water to move.","Grandmother had already moved it to a safe shelf.","It was made of stronger clay than the round pots.","Its lean let it rest against the wall so it did not roll off and shatter."],"answer":3,"explanation":"The text explains, \"The lean had let the pot rest against the wall, so it had not rolled off the shelf and shattered.\"","points":1},{"id":"Q6","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What is the theme, or main message, of this story?","diagram":null,"options":["Hard rain will ruin everything that people make.","The fastest worker is always the most successful.","What makes you different can turn out to be a strength.","You should always copy the work of more skilled people."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Nina''s pot is saved because of the very lean she was ashamed of, and she ends up glad it is her own. The story shows that being different can be a strength.","points":1},{"id":"Q7","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Which detail from the text BEST supports the idea that Nina changes how she feels about her pottery by the end of the story?","diagram":null,"options":["\"Nina''s pots always leaned to one side.\"","\"Water rushed into the shop and knocked the neat row of round pots to the floor.\"","\"For the first time, she was glad it was her own.\"","\"She watched her cousin Theo lift a perfect, even pot from the wheel.\""],"answer":2,"explanation":"At the start Nina is ashamed of her pot, but the line \"For the first time, she was glad it was her own\" shows her feelings have changed.","points":1},{"id":"Q8","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Select all of the things that happen AFTER the flood comes into the shop.","diagram":null,"options":["Grandmother pulls Nina''s pot out from behind the sack.","Nina hides her crooked pot behind the dry clay.","Theo asks Nina to show him how she made her pot lean.","Grandmother tells Nina that her own pots leaned when she was young."],"answer":[0,2],"explanation":"After the flood, Grandmother finds Nina''s pot and Theo asks to learn from her. Nina hiding the pot and Grandmother''s first talk both happen before the flood, in Part 1.","points":1},{"id":"Q9","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What is the main idea of \"The Smallest Helper\"?","diagram":null,"options":["The meadow is a dangerous place during a storm.","Pip uses her small size to help the colony in a way no one else can.","Big ants are always more useful than small ants.","Ants build the deepest tunnels in the whole meadow."],"answer":1,"explanation":"The whole story leads to Pip squeezing into a narrow crack to find water, doing \"a job only she could do.\" That is the main idea.","points":1},{"id":"Q10","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Which word BEST describes Pip at the end of the story?","diagram":null,"options":["Useless","Frightened","Proud","Lazy"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The text says \"Pip glowed with pride\" because she finally had a job only she could do.","points":1},{"id":"Q11","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"trickle\" in paragraph 1 of Part 2?","diagram":null,"options":["A loud, rushing flood","A thin, slow flow of water","A deep, cool pool","A cloud full of rain"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The stream \"shrank to a trickle and then to nothing,\" so a trickle is a thin, slow flow that is almost gone.","points":1},{"id":"Q12","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P2","questionText":"According to the text, why can only Pip reach the hidden pool of water?","diagram":null,"options":["She is the fastest runner in the colony.","She is the only ant who knows how to swim.","She is small enough to fit through the narrow crack.","She is stronger than all the other ants."],"answer":2,"explanation":"The text says the bigger ants were \"too large to squeeze into the narrow places,\" but Pip \"slipped easily through the tiny gap.\"","points":1},{"id":"Q13","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.5","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"How does the author connect Part 1 and Part 2 of the story?","diagram":null,"options":["Part 2 repeats the same events as Part 1 from a new ant''s view.","Part 1 describes a storm and Part 2 describes the same storm again.","Part 1 tells a true story and Part 2 explains how to find water.","The crack Pip finds in Part 1 becomes the way she saves the colony in Part 2."],"answer":3,"explanation":"In Part 1 Pip discovers a crack with a cool smell of water; in Part 2 that crack leads to the hidden pool she uses to save everyone. The detail in Part 1 sets up the solution in Part 2.","points":1},{"id":"Q14","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.6","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What does the oldest ant most likely mean by saying, \"Being small turned out to be exactly the right size\"?","diagram":null,"options":["All the ants should try to become smaller.","Small ants should never carry water.","Pip''s small size was just what the colony needed.","The colony has grown too crowded with ants."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Pip''s small size let her reach the water no other ant could reach, so being small was exactly right for that job.","points":1},{"id":"Q15","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.9","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Use both stories to answer this question. What is one way Nina in \"The Lopsided Pot\" and Pip in \"The Smallest Helper\" are alike?","diagram":null,"options":["Each one first feels that a trait makes them worse, but later that trait becomes helpful.","Each one runs away from home to live in a meadow.","Each one teaches a grandmother how to make pottery.","Each one is the largest and strongest in the group."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Nina is ashamed her pot leans and Pip feels useless for being small, yet the lean saves Nina''s pot and the small size lets Pip find water. The very trait each disliked turns out to help.","points":1},{"id":"Q16","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.5","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What problem do the ants face in Part 2 of the story?","diagram":null,"options":["A flood washes away all of their tunnels.","The meadow dries up and their water disappears.","A bird eats most of the seeds they collected.","The big ants and fast ants leave the colony."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 2 says \"the meadow grew dry as dust\" and the stream \"shrank to a trickle and then to nothing,\" which is the problem the ants must solve.","points":1},{"id":"Q17","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.2","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the main idea of \"The Journey of a Raindrop\"?","diagram":null,"options":["Oceans hold more water than rivers and lakes.","Water moves in a never-ending loop called the water cycle.","Rain is the most dangerous kind of weather.","Clouds are made only on cold winter days."],"answer":1,"explanation":"The article follows water through evaporation, condensation, and precipitation, all parts of \"a great loop called the water cycle\" that \"never stops.\"","points":1},{"id":"Q18","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P3","questionText":"According to the text, what does the sun do to start the water cycle?","diagram":null,"options":["It heats the water until it turns into water vapor.","It pulls rain down to the earth.","It cools the air high above the ground.","It pushes the clouds across the sky."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Part 1 says \"The journey begins with the sun,\" which \"heats the water\" until it \"turns into a gas called water vapor.\"","points":1},{"id":"Q19","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"evaporation\" as it is used in the text?","diagram":null,"options":["Water warming up and turning into a gas that rises into the air","Water soaking down into the soil","Water falling to the earth as rain or snow","Water drops joining to form clouds in the sky"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The text says when water gets warm it \"turns into a gas called water vapor and rises into the air. This step is called evaporation.\"","points":1},{"id":"Q20","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"How does the author connect the ideas in paragraph 3 of Part 1 (about condensation) and paragraph 1 of Part 2 (about precipitation)?","diagram":null,"options":["Both paragraphs compare snow with hail.","Both paragraphs explain how the sun heats the ocean.","The first paragraph gives an opinion and the second proves it is wrong.","The tiny drops that form clouds in paragraph 3 grow heavy and fall as rain in the next paragraph."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Paragraph 3 explains how tiny drops gather into clouds (condensation); the next paragraph picks up those same drops, which \"grow heavier\" until they fall as precipitation. The author links the steps in order.","points":1},{"id":"Q21","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"How does the author organize the information in this whole article?","diagram":null,"options":["By listing reasons people should save water","By describing a problem and then offering a solution","By comparing rain to snow and hail","By giving the steps of the water cycle in the order they happen"],"answer":3,"explanation":"The article moves through evaporation, condensation, and precipitation, then back to the ocean, presenting the steps of the cycle in order.","points":1},{"id":"Q22","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"According to the text, what happens to water after it reaches the ground?","diagram":null,"options":["It disappears and is gone from the earth for good.","Some soaks into the soil and some flows into streams that lead back to the ocean.","All of it freezes into ice and stays there forever.","It rises straight back into the clouds as rain."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 2 says \"Some water soaks deep into the soil\" and \"Some flows downhill into streams and rivers, which carry it back to the ocean.\"","points":1},{"id":"Q23","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"Which detail from the text BEST supports the idea that the same water has been used over and over for a very long time?","diagram":null,"options":["\"The rain that splashes on your window today may have fallen on a forest long ago, or even on the dinosaurs.\"","\"Clouds drift across the sky, pushed by the wind.\"","\"You cannot see water vapor, but it is all around you.\"","\"High in the sky, the air is cold.\""],"answer":0,"explanation":"The line about rain that \"may have fallen on the dinosaurs millions of years before\" shows the same water is reused again and again over a very long time.","points":1},{"id":"Q24","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.6","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the author''s main purpose for writing this article?","diagram":null,"options":["To explain how water moves through the water cycle","To describe the author''s favorite rainy day","To tell a made-up story about a talking raindrop","To convince readers to drink more water"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The article gives facts and steps to explain how the water cycle works, so its purpose is to inform.","points":1},{"id":"Q25","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.2","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"What is the main idea of \"The Lighthouse Keeper of Long Ago\"?","diagram":null,"options":["Ships made of wood are stronger than ships made of metal.","Storms at sea are more common than calm weather.","Long ago, a lighthouse keeper worked hard to keep the warning light burning for ships.","Lighthouses are the tallest buildings near the ocean."],"answer":2,"explanation":"The article describes the keeper''s daily and stormy work to keep the light burning so ships stayed safe, which is the main idea.","points":1},{"id":"Q26","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P4","questionText":"According to the text, why did people build lighthouses along the coast?","diagram":null,"options":["To store oil for the ships that passed by","To warn ships away from hidden rocks and shallow water","To watch for storms coming over the land","To give the keepers a place to live near town"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 1 says hidden rocks and shallow water could sink a ship, so \"to keep sailors safe, people built tall towers called lighthouses.\"","points":1},{"id":"Q27","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"dim\" in paragraph 1 of Part 2?","diagram":null,"options":["To turn the light a new color","To make the light less bright","To make the light larger","To clean the glass of the light"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The text says smoke and salt would \"dim its glow\" so the keeper cleaned the glass; if the light \"grew weak,\" ships might not see it. Dim means to make less bright.","points":1},{"id":"Q28","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P4","questionText":"According to the text, what did the keeper do every evening at sunset?","diagram":null,"options":["Carried buckets of water up to the light","Climbed the winding staircase to light the lamp","Cleaned the small house beside the tower","Sailed out to sea to guide the ships home"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 1 says \"Every evening at sunset, the keeper climbed a long, winding staircase to light the lamp.\"","points":1},{"id":"Q29","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"How does the author connect the ideas about cleaning the glass and about working during storms in Part 2?","diagram":null,"options":["Both compare lighthouses to ordinary houses.","Both explain how machines run lighthouses today.","Both show the many hard tasks the keeper had to do to keep the light shining.","The cleaning caused the storms to happen."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Cleaning the glass each day and staying awake through storms are both examples of the keeper''s never-ending hard work to keep the warning light strong.","points":1},{"id":"Q30","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"Based on the text, why was the keeper''s job hardest during storms?","diagram":null,"options":["The keeper had to stay awake all night so the flame would not go out.","The keeper had to sail out and rescue the sailors.","The keeper had to carry the ships back to shore.","The keeper had to build a new lighthouse before morning."],"answer":0,"explanation":"During storms the wind shook the tower, yet \"the keeper stayed awake all night to keep the flame burning,\" because sailors trusted that light.","points":1},{"id":"Q31","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"Select the TWO daily tasks the text says the lighthouse keeper had to do.","diagram":null,"options":["Sleep during the day instead of at night","Clean the glass around the light","Carry heavy buckets of oil up the stairs","Repair the wooden hulls of ships"],"answer":[1,2],"explanation":"The text says the keeper carried \"heavy buckets of oil up the stairs\" and that \"the glass around the light had to be cleaned each day.\" Repairing hulls and sleeping by day are not stated.","points":1},{"id":"Q32","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.9","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"Use \"The Journey of a Raindrop\" and \"The Lighthouse Keeper of Long Ago\" to answer this question. What is one way these two texts are alike?","diagram":null,"options":["Both try to convince the reader to visit the ocean.","Both are poems that use rhyme.","Both tell a make-believe story with talking characters.","Both are written to give the reader true information about a topic."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Both selections are informational. One explains the water cycle and the other explains a lighthouse keeper''s work; each gives the reader facts about a real topic.","points":1},{"id":"Q33","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P5","questionText":"According to the poem, what has just happened before the poem begins?","diagram":null,"options":["A storm has passed and the rain has stopped.","A gardener has planted new seeds.","The sun has set and night has come.","Winter snow has covered the garden."],"answer":0,"explanation":"The first lines say \"The storm has packed its bags and gone, / the gray clouds rolled away,\" showing a storm has just ended.","points":1},{"id":"Q34","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"L.3.5.a","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"What is the meaning of the phrase \"The storm has packed its bags and gone\" in Part 1 of the poem?","diagram":null,"options":["The storm packed real suitcases for a trip.","The storm grew much stronger overnight.","The storm filled the garden with bags of rain.","The storm has ended and moved away."],"answer":3,"explanation":"This is figurative language that describes the storm as if it were a traveler leaving, which means the storm has ended and moved away.","points":1},{"id":"Q35","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"L.3.5.a","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"In the line \"Each leaf is wearing little jewels,\" what are the \"little jewels\" the poet describes?","diagram":null,"options":["Tiny green buds on the branches","Small stones scattered on the ground","Shining drops of rainwater on the leaves","Bright flowers blooming in the garden"],"answer":2,"explanation":"After the rain, the leaves \"sparkle, shake, and slide,\" so the \"little jewels\" are shining raindrops resting on the leaves.","points":1},{"id":"Q36","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"What is the main message of the poem?","diagram":null,"options":["Rainy days should always make people sad.","Gardens grow best when no rain ever falls.","Spiders are the most important garden animals.","Something good and fresh can come even after a storm."],"answer":3,"explanation":"The last stanza says not to frown at rain, \"for every storm that comes to pass / leaves something fresh and new,\" which is the poem''s message.","points":1},{"id":"Q37","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P5","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"mends\" in the line \"A spider mends her broken web\"?","diagram":null,"options":["Fixes or repairs","Hides away from","Throws away","Builds for the first time"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The spider \"mends her broken web with patience,\" so mends means to fix or repair what is broken.","points":1},{"id":"Q38","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.5","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P5","questionText":"How does the poet describe the puddles in Part 2 of the poem?","diagram":null,"options":["As empty and dried up by the sun","As holding a piece of sky, a small and shining thing","As frozen over with a sheet of ice","As deep and dangerous pools of mud"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The poem says \"The puddles hold a piece of sky, / a small and shining thing,\" describing how they reflect the sky.","points":1},{"id":"Q39","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.6","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P5","questionText":"How does the speaker of the poem most likely feel about the garden after the rain?","diagram":null,"options":["Worried that the storm caused harm","Hopeful and pleased by its fresh beauty","Angry that the sun is hidden from view","Bored by the quiet, wet morning"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The speaker points out sparkling jewels, singing robins, and shining puddles, and says the storm \"leaves something fresh and new,\" showing a hopeful, pleased feeling.","points":1},{"id":"Q40","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.9","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"Use \"The Garden After Rain\" and \"The Journey of a Raindrop\" to answer this question. What is one way these two selections are different?","diagram":null,"options":["One has two parts and the other has only one part.","One is fiction and the other is a poem.","Both are written as step-by-step instructions.","One is a poem that shares feelings, while the other is an article that explains facts."],"answer":3,"explanation":"\"The Garden After Rain\" is a poem with rhythm and rhyme that shares feelings about rain, while \"The Journey of a Raindrop\" is an informational article that explains the facts of the water cycle. Both texts are written in two parts.","points":1}]}');
INSERT INTO "tests" ("id","grade","subject","test_type","title","time_limit_minutes","question_count","source","created_at","data") VALUES('g3-read-eog-2',3,'reading','eog','Grade 3 Reading — EOG Practice Test 2',120,40,'curated','2026-06-02T00:00:00.000Z','{"id":"g3-read-eog-2","grade":3,"subject":"reading","testType":"eog","title":"Grade 3 Reading — EOG Practice Test 2","instructions":"Read each selection carefully. Then answer the questions. Choose the one best answer for each question unless you are told to select more than one.","timeLimitMinutes":120,"calculatorAllowed":false,"source":"curated","passages":[{"id":"P1","title":"The Traveler''s Soup","genre":"fiction","lexile":"560L","text":"Part 1\n\nA tired traveler walked into a small village just as the sun was setting. He had not eaten all day, and his stomach growled like a hungry bear. He knocked on the very first door he saw.\n\n\"Could you spare a little food?\" he asked the woman who answered.\n\n\"We have nothing to share,\" she said quickly, though the smell of fresh bread drifted out the door behind her. The traveler only smiled politely and walked on. At every house he heard the same answer. The villagers had plenty of food, but they did not want to give any away.\n\nThe traveler did not become angry. Instead, he sat down in the middle of the village square, took a smooth gray stone from his pocket, and dropped it into a big iron pot. Then he poured in water and built a small fire beneath it.\n\nA curious boy wandered over. \"What are you cooking?\" he asked.\n\n\"Stone soup,\" the traveler answered, stirring slowly. \"It is the most delicious soup in all the world. This batch is nearly perfect. It only needs a few carrots to make it even better.\"\n\nPart 2\n\nThe boy ran home and returned with three carrots, which the traveler dropped into the pot. Soon a woman appeared. \"Stone soup?\" she said. \"I have never heard of such a thing.\"\n\n\"It is wonderful,\" the traveler replied. \"Though a bit of cabbage would make it richer.\" The woman hurried off and came back with a head of cabbage.\n\nOne by one, the villagers came to see the magic soup. Each time, the traveler mentioned one more thing the soup needed — a handful of beans, a few potatoes, a pinch of salt. Each time, a villager rushed to bring it. Before long, the pot was full and bubbling, and a delicious smell filled the whole square.\n\nWhen the soup was ready, the traveler shared it with everyone. The villagers ate together, laughing and talking late into the night. They all agreed it was the finest soup they had ever tasted.\n\n\"Such a magic stone!\" they said.\n\nThe traveler only smiled. He knew the soup was not made by the stone at all. It was made by everyone sharing a little of what they had."},{"id":"P2","title":"Marble Enters the Race","genre":"fiction","lexile":"520L","text":"Part 1\n\nMarble the snail lived at the bottom of the garden, beneath a broad green leaf. Every spring the garden creatures held a great race from the old fence to the birdbath. And every spring, Marble watched from the sidelines, because everyone knew a snail was far too slow to enter.\n\n\"Why bother?\" laughed Dash the grasshopper. \"You would still be crawling when the leaves turn brown!\"\n\nThis year, though, Marble decided things would be different. \"I am going to race,\" she announced. The other creatures giggled, but Marble paid them no mind. On the morning of the race, she lined up beside the rabbits, the beetles, and the busy ants.\n\n\"Ready, set, go!\" called the wise old toad. In a flash, the others sped away. Marble began to glide forward, slow and steady, leaving a shiny silver trail behind her.\n\nPart 2\n\nThe day grew hot. By noon, Dash the grasshopper had stopped to nap in the cool shade. The rabbits had wandered off to nibble clover and forgotten the race entirely. The beetles argued about which way to go and ended up walking in circles.\n\nMarble did not stop. She did not rush, and she did not quit. Inch by inch, she crept along the path, past the sleeping grasshopper, past the lost beetles, always moving toward the birdbath.\n\nWhen the sun began to set, the garden creatures gathered at the finish line, wondering who had won. Then they saw a faint silver trail shining in the evening light. At the very end of that trail sat Marble, resting quietly beside the birdbath.\n\n\"Marble won!\" cried the ants in surprise.\n\nMarble smiled. \"I may be slow,\" she said, \"but I never stopped trying.\" From that day on, no one in the garden ever laughed at a snail again."},{"id":"P3","title":"Why the Ocean Is Salty","genre":"informational","lexile":"620L","text":"Part 1\n\nHave you ever swallowed a mouthful of ocean water by accident? If so, you know it tastes very salty. But have you ever wondered where all that salt comes from? The answer begins far away from the sea, high up on the land.\n\nRain falls on rocks and soil all over the land. As the rainwater flows downhill, it picks up tiny bits of salt and other minerals from the rocks. These bits are so small that you cannot see or taste them in a single drop. The water carries them into little streams, and the streams carry them into rivers. Slowly, the rivers carry the salt all the way to the ocean.\n\nPart 2\n\nRivers add a little salt to the ocean every single day. This has been happening for millions of years. You might think the rivers would carry the salt back out again, but they do not. Here is why.\n\nThe sun warms the top of the ocean. Some of the water turns into a gas called water vapor and rises into the air. This change is called evaporation. When water evaporates, the salt is left behind. The fresh water rises into the sky, forms clouds, and falls again as rain. But the salt stays in the ocean.\n\nBecause new salt keeps arriving and almost none leaves, the ocean has slowly grown saltier and saltier over time. A few lakes that have no rivers flowing out of them, such as the Great Salt Lake, are even saltier than the ocean. Scientists study ocean water to learn about Earth''s past. The salt in the sea is like a record of millions of years of rain, rivers, and sunshine working together."},{"id":"P4","title":"Giants of the Forest","genre":"informational","lexile":"640L","text":"Part 1\n\nDeep in the forests of California grow some of the largest living things on Earth. They are the giant sequoia trees. A single giant sequoia can grow taller than a 25-story building and wider than a city street. Some of these trees have been alive for more than two thousand years. That means a few giant sequoias were already growing before many of the world''s oldest cities were even built.\n\nWhat makes these trees so special is not only their size but also their strength. A giant sequoia has thick, spongy bark that can be almost two feet deep. This bark is like the tree''s armor. It protects the tree from insects and even from fire.\n\nPart 2\n\nYou might expect fire to be a giant sequoia''s worst enemy. Surprisingly, the opposite is true. Forest fires actually help these giants survive. When a fire sweeps through the forest, the heat dries out the sequoia''s cones and causes them to pop open. The tiny seeds inside then fall to the ground.\n\nFire also clears away smaller plants and dead leaves from the forest floor. This makes room for the seeds and lets sunlight reach the soil. The ashes left behind add nutrients that help young trees grow. Without fire, sequoia seeds would have a much harder time sprouting.\n\nFor many years, people put out every forest fire they could in order to protect the trees. Later, scientists discovered this was a mistake. Without fire, fewer baby sequoias were growing. Today, forest rangers sometimes set small, careful fires on purpose. These planned fires help the great trees make new seedlings, so the giants of the forest can live on for many more years."},{"id":"P5","title":"Roberto Clemente: A Hero On and Off the Field","genre":"informational","lexile":"630L","text":"Part 1\n\nRoberto Clemente was born in 1934 on the island of Puerto Rico. As a boy, he loved baseball so much that he made his own balls out of old socks and used a stick for a bat. His family did not have much money, but Roberto practiced every chance he got. He dreamed of one day playing in the big leagues.\n\nRoberto''s hard work paid off. In 1955, he joined the Pittsburgh Pirates in the United States. At first, life was difficult. He spoke Spanish, while most people around him spoke English. Some people were unkind because he came from a different place. But Roberto kept playing, and he played brilliantly. Fans soon noticed his powerful throws and his amazing hits.\n\nPart 2\n\nOver the years, Roberto became one of the greatest players in baseball history. He won many awards and helped his team win the World Series twice. But Roberto cared about much more than baseball. He believed that people with talent had a duty to help others.\n\nWhenever he could, Roberto used his fame to do good. He visited sick children in hospitals and gave money and food to families in need. He often said that anyone who has the chance to make life better for others, and does not do it, is wasting time on Earth.\n\nIn 1972, a terrible earthquake struck the country of Nicaragua. Roberto gathered food and supplies to send to the people there. He even got on a plane to make sure the help arrived safely. Sadly, the plane crashed, and Roberto died. People all over the world were heartbroken. Today, Roberto Clemente is remembered not only as a great athlete, but also as a man who gave his life trying to help others."}],"questions":[{"id":"Q1","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P1","questionText":"According to Part 1, why does the traveler stop in the village?","diagram":null,"options":["He is hungry and has not eaten all day.","He wants to sell a magic stone.","He is looking for a place to sleep.","He needs to fix his broken pot."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Part 1 says the traveler had not eaten all day and his stomach growled, so he knocks on doors asking for food.","points":1},{"id":"Q2","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"spare\" as it is used in Part 1?","diagram":null,"options":["To give a small amount of something away","To cook something over a fire","To buy something at a store","To keep something safe and hidden"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The traveler asks if the woman could \"spare a little food,\" meaning give some of it away.","points":1},{"id":"Q3","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Which word best describes the traveler in the story?","diagram":null,"options":["Selfish","Clever","Lazy","Frightened"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The traveler tricks the villagers into adding food to the pot, which shows he is clever.","points":1},{"id":"Q4","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What does the boy bring to add to the soup?","diagram":null,"options":["A handful of beans","Three carrots","A pinch of salt","A head of cabbage"],"answer":1,"explanation":"In Part 2, the boy runs home and returns with three carrots, which the traveler drops into the pot.","points":1},{"id":"Q5","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What is the theme, or lesson, of this story?","diagram":null,"options":["Special stones can solve any problem.","Hard work is always better than being clever.","It is dangerous to talk to strangers in a village.","When everyone shares a little, much can be made together."],"answer":3,"explanation":"The last paragraph explains the soup was made by everyone sharing a little of what they had, which is the story''s lesson.","points":1},{"id":"Q6","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Which detail from the text best supports the idea that the stone itself was not magic?","diagram":null,"options":["\"The villagers had plenty of food, but they did not want to give any away.\"","\"He poured in water and built a small fire beneath it.\"","\"He knew the soup was not made by the stone at all.\"","\"A curious boy wandered over.\""],"answer":2,"explanation":"The sentence stating the traveler knew the soup was not made by the stone directly supports that the stone was not magic.","points":1},{"id":"Q7","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.5","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"How are the events in Part 1 and Part 2 connected?","diagram":null,"options":["Part 2 happens before the events in Part 1.","Part 1 explains a problem that is never solved in Part 2.","Part 1 and Part 2 both describe the same meal eaten on two different days.","Part 1 shows the villagers refusing to share, and Part 2 shows the traveler''s plan slowly changing their minds."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Part 1 sets up the villagers'' refusal to share; Part 2 shows the traveler''s stone-soup trick gradually getting them to contribute food.","points":1},{"id":"Q8","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Select the two foods that villagers added to the soup in Part 2.","diagram":null,"options":["Apples","Potatoes","Cabbage","Cheese"],"answer":[1,2],"explanation":"Part 2 lists cabbage and potatoes (along with beans and salt) as things villagers brought. Apples and cheese are never mentioned.","points":1},{"id":"Q9","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Where does the great race take place?","diagram":null,"options":["From the birdbath to the broad green leaf","Across a field of clover","From the old fence to the birdbath","Around the old toad''s pond"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 1 states the race goes from the old fence to the birdbath.","points":1},{"id":"Q10","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Why does Marble decide to enter the race this year?","diagram":null,"options":["Dash the grasshopper dares her to do it.","She is now the fastest creature in the garden.","She decides she wants things to be different and tries.","The wise old toad orders her to race."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 1 says Marble decided things would be different this year and announced she was going to race.","points":1},{"id":"Q11","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"glide\" as it is used in Part 1?","diagram":null,"options":["To jump high into the air","To stop and rest","To move smoothly and slowly","To shout loudly"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Marble begins to glide forward, slow and steady, leaving a silver trail, which shows gliding means moving smoothly and slowly.","points":1},{"id":"Q12","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What happens to the rabbits during the race?","diagram":null,"options":["They nap in the cool shade.","They wander off to nibble clover and forget the race.","They argue about which way to go.","They cross the finish line first."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 2 says the rabbits wandered off to nibble clover and forgot the race entirely. (The grasshopper napped; the beetles argued.)","points":1},{"id":"Q13","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What is the main lesson of this story?","diagram":null,"options":["Slow and steady effort can win in the end.","Friends should always race together.","Snails should never try to race.","It is best to rest when the day gets hot."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Marble wins by never stopping, showing that slow and steady effort can win, which is the story''s lesson.","points":1},{"id":"Q14","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Which sentence from the text best shows why Marble was able to win the race?","diagram":null,"options":["\"She did not rush, and she did not quit.\"","\"The day grew hot.\"","\"The other creatures giggled, but Marble paid them no mind.\"","\"Marble the snail lived at the bottom of the garden.\""],"answer":0,"explanation":"The sentence that she did not rush and did not quit best explains how her steady effort led to victory.","points":1},{"id":"Q15","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"How do the other creatures feel about Marble at the END of the story, compared to the beginning?","diagram":null,"options":["They feel afraid of her the whole time.","At first they laugh at her, but at the end they respect her.","At first they respect her, but at the end they laugh at her.","They ignore her at both the beginning and the end."],"answer":1,"explanation":"At the start the creatures giggle and laugh at Marble; at the end no one ever laughs at a snail again, showing they now respect her.","points":1},{"id":"Q16","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.9","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Use both \"The Traveler''s Soup\" and \"Marble Enters the Race\" to answer this question. What is one way the traveler and Marble are alike?","diagram":null,"options":["Both succeed by staying calm and not giving up, even when others doubt them.","Both are laughed at by an entire village.","Both win a prize at the end of a contest.","Both use a magic object to reach their goal."],"answer":0,"explanation":"The traveler stays calm when refused and Marble keeps going when mocked; both succeed by staying steady despite others'' doubt.","points":1},{"id":"Q17","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P3","questionText":"According to Part 1, where does the salt in the ocean begin?","diagram":null,"options":["In clouds high in the sky","In rocks and soil on the land","Inside ocean animals","Deep at the bottom of the sea"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 1 explains that rainwater picks up bits of salt from rocks and soil on the land and carries them to the ocean.","points":1},{"id":"Q18","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"Which step happens FIRST in how salt reaches the ocean?","diagram":null,"options":["Streams flow into rivers.","Rivers carry salt to the ocean.","Water turns into water vapor.","Rain falls on rocks and soil."],"answer":3,"explanation":"The process begins when rain falls on rocks and soil, picking up salt; then it moves to streams, rivers, and the ocean.","points":1},{"id":"Q19","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"evaporation\" as it is used in Part 2?","diagram":null,"options":["When water turns into a gas and rises into the air","When rain falls down from the clouds","When rivers flow into the sea","When salt sinks to the bottom of the ocean"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Part 2 says some water turns into a gas called water vapor and rises into the air, and this change is called evaporation.","points":1},{"id":"Q20","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"According to the text, what happens to the salt when ocean water evaporates?","diagram":null,"options":["The salt flows back into the rivers.","The salt turns into fresh water.","The salt is left behind in the ocean.","The salt rises into the clouds."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 2 states that when water evaporates, the salt is left behind while the fresh water rises into the sky.","points":1},{"id":"Q21","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"How does the author connect the ideas in Part 1 and Part 2 of the text?","diagram":null,"options":["Part 1 compares rivers and lakes, and Part 2 compares clouds and rain.","Part 1 explains how salt gets into the ocean, and Part 2 explains why the salt stays and builds up.","Part 1 and Part 2 describe two different oceans on Earth.","Part 2 gives the opposite opinion from Part 1."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 1 tells how salt arrives by way of rivers; Part 2 explains why it stays (evaporation leaves salt behind), so the parts build on each other.","points":1},{"id":"Q22","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the connection between the sun warming the ocean and the salt staying in the sea?","diagram":null,"options":["It gives directions in time order only.","It shows cause and effect: the sun causes water to evaporate, which leaves the salt behind.","It lists a problem and then several solutions.","It compares two things that are alike."],"answer":1,"explanation":"The sun''s heat (cause) makes water evaporate, leaving salt behind (effect), so the relationship is cause and effect.","points":1},{"id":"Q23","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.2","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the main idea of this text?","diagram":null,"options":["Rain clouds are made of salt water.","Ocean water tastes bad if you swallow it.","The ocean is salty because rivers bring salt in and evaporation leaves it behind.","The Great Salt Lake is the saltiest place on Earth."],"answer":2,"explanation":"The whole text explains that rivers add salt and evaporation keeps it in the ocean, which is the main idea.","points":1},{"id":"Q24","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"Which detail from the text best supports the idea that the ocean keeps getting saltier?","diagram":null,"options":["\"Because new salt keeps arriving and almost none leaves...\"","\"Have you ever swallowed a mouthful of ocean water...\"","\"The fresh water rises into the sky, forms clouds...\"","\"Rain falls on rocks and soil all over the land.\""],"answer":0,"explanation":"The detail that new salt keeps arriving while almost none leaves directly explains why the ocean keeps getting saltier.","points":1},{"id":"Q25","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P4","questionText":"Where do giant sequoia trees grow?","diagram":null,"options":["On the islands of Puerto Rico","In the deserts of Texas","In the forests of California","In the mountains of Nicaragua"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 1 states that giant sequoia trees grow deep in the forests of California.","points":1},{"id":"Q26","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"L.3.5.a","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"In Part 1, the author says the sequoia''s bark is \"like the tree''s armor.\" What does this phrase mean?","diagram":null,"options":["The bark is made of metal.","The bark protects the tree the way armor protects a knight.","The bark is heavy and slows the tree down.","The bark is bright and shiny."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Calling the bark like \"armor\" compares it to protective armor, since the bark protects the tree from insects and fire.","points":1},{"id":"Q27","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"According to Part 2, how does a forest fire help the sequoia spread its seeds?","diagram":null,"options":["The fire blows the seeds high into the sky.","Animals carry the burned seeds to new places.","The heat dries the cones so they pop open and drop their seeds.","The fire makes new cones grow on the branches."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 2 explains the fire''s heat dries out the cones and causes them to pop open, releasing the seeds inside.","points":1},{"id":"Q28","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"What is the connection between fire clearing the forest floor and young sequoias growing?","diagram":null,"options":["It is cause and effect: clearing the floor lets sunlight and nutrients reach the seeds so they can grow.","It lists the trees in order from tallest to shortest.","It presents a problem with no solution.","It compares old trees with young trees."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Fire clears the floor and adds nutrients (cause), which helps young sequoias grow (effect), a cause-and-effect connection.","points":1},{"id":"Q29","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"How does the author connect the idea about people putting out fires with the idea about the trees today?","diagram":null,"options":["The author compares California forests with desert plants.","The author lists the steps for planting a sequoia seed.","The author tells two stories that have nothing in common.","The author presents a problem (fewer baby trees grew) and then a solution (rangers set careful fires)."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Stopping fires created a problem (fewer seedlings), and the solution is rangers setting planned fires, so it is a problem-and-solution structure.","points":1},{"id":"Q30","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.2","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"What is the main idea of this text?","diagram":null,"options":["Giant sequoias are huge, strong trees, and fire actually helps them survive.","Forest fires are always dangerous and must be stopped.","Sequoia bark can be used to build houses.","California has the oldest cities in the world."],"answer":0,"explanation":"The text describes the sequoias'' size and strength and explains how fire helps them, which together form the main idea.","points":1},{"id":"Q31","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"Select the two ways that forest fires help giant sequoias, according to the text.","diagram":null,"options":["They scare away all the forest animals.","They cause the cones to open and drop seeds.","They clear away dead leaves so sunlight reaches the soil.","They make the trees grow taller in a single day."],"answer":[1,2],"explanation":"The text says fire opens the cones to release seeds and clears the forest floor so sunlight reaches the soil. The other choices are not stated.","points":1},{"id":"Q32","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P5","questionText":"Where was Roberto Clemente born?","diagram":null,"options":["Pittsburgh","California","Nicaragua","Puerto Rico"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Part 1 states Roberto Clemente was born in 1934 on the island of Puerto Rico.","points":1},{"id":"Q33","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P5","questionText":"As a boy, what did Roberto use to practice baseball?","diagram":null,"options":["Equipment given to him by the Pirates","A brand-new bat and glove from a store","Stones and a wooden board","Balls made of old socks and a stick for a bat"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Part 1 says he made his own balls out of old socks and used a stick for a bat.","points":1},{"id":"Q34","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P5","questionText":"Why was life difficult for Roberto when he first joined the Pittsburgh Pirates?","diagram":null,"options":["He did not want to leave Puerto Rico.","He was not a very good baseball player.","The team would not let him play in games.","He spoke Spanish while most people spoke English, and some were unkind."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Part 1 explains he spoke Spanish while most people spoke English, and some people were unkind because he came from a different place.","points":1},{"id":"Q35","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P5","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"duty\" as it is used in Part 2?","diagram":null,"options":["A fee that someone has to pay","A type of award given to baseball players","Something a person should do because it is right","A long trip to another country"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The text says Roberto believed talented people had a duty to help others, meaning something they should do because it is right.","points":1},{"id":"Q36","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P5","questionText":"According to Part 2, why did Roberto get on the plane to Nicaragua?","diagram":null,"options":["To accept an award from the team","To make sure the food and supplies arrived safely","To play in a baseball game there","To visit his family for the holidays"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 2 says he got on a plane to make sure the help he gathered for earthquake victims arrived safely.","points":1},{"id":"Q37","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"What is the main idea of this text?","diagram":null,"options":["Baseball is the most popular sport in Puerto Rico.","Earthquakes are very common in Nicaragua.","Roberto Clemente never faced any problems in his life.","Roberto Clemente was a great baseball player who also worked hard to help others."],"answer":3,"explanation":"The text describes both his baseball greatness and his work helping others, which together form the main idea.","points":1},{"id":"Q38","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"Which sentence from the text best supports the idea that Roberto cared about more than baseball?","diagram":null,"options":["\"In 1955, he joined the Pittsburgh Pirates in the United States.\"","\"He visited sick children in hospitals and gave money and food to families in need.\"","\"He won many awards and helped his team win the World Series twice.\"","\"Fans soon noticed his powerful throws and his amazing hits.\""],"answer":1,"explanation":"Visiting sick children and giving money and food shows he cared about helping people, not just baseball.","points":1},{"id":"Q39","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"How does the author connect Roberto''s belief about helping others with his actions in Part 2?","diagram":null,"options":["The author shows that Roberto''s belief was the opposite of how he acted.","The author lists Roberto''s baseball awards in the order he won them.","The author compares Roberto''s beliefs to those of other players.","The author states his belief and then gives examples of him acting on it, such as aiding earthquake victims."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Part 2 states his belief that talented people must help others, then gives examples (hospitals, donations, the Nicaragua trip) showing he acted on it.","points":1},{"id":"Q40","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.9","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"Use \"Giants of the Forest\" and \"Roberto Clemente: A Hero On and Off the Field\" to answer this question. What is one way the two texts are alike?","diagram":null,"options":["Both describe how people changed their actions after learning something new.","Both tell stories that take place only in Puerto Rico.","Both are poems written with rhyming lines.","Both are mainly about animals that live in the forest."],"answer":0,"explanation":"In the sequoia text, scientists learned and changed how they handled fire; in the Clemente text, Roberto and others changed actions to help people. Both informational texts show people changing actions after learning, while the other options misdescribe the texts.","points":1}]}');
INSERT INTO "tests" ("id","grade","subject","test_type","title","time_limit_minutes","question_count","source","created_at","data") VALUES('g3-read-eog-3',3,'reading','eog','Grade 3 Reading — EOG Practice Test 3',120,40,'curated','2026-06-02T00:00:00.000Z','{"id":"g3-read-eog-3","grade":3,"subject":"reading","testType":"eog","title":"Grade 3 Reading — EOG Practice Test 3","instructions":"Read each selection carefully. Then answer the questions. Choose the one best answer for each question unless you are told to select more than one.","timeLimitMinutes":120,"calculatorAllowed":false,"source":"curated","passages":[{"id":"P1","title":"The Kite Maker''s Gift","genre":"fiction","lexile":"560L","text":"Part 1\n\nEvery autumn, the wind swept down from the hills and rattled the windows of the little town. To most people it was just cold weather, but to Nina it was kite season. All year she saved bits of bright paper, thin sticks, and string in a wooden box beneath her bed.\n\nThis year Nina wanted to build the grandest kite the town had ever seen. She worked for three evenings, bending the sticks into a wide diamond and gluing red and gold paper across the frame. When she finally held it up, it was taller than she was.\n\n\"It will never fly,\" said her older brother Tomas, shaking his head. \"It is far too big and heavy.\"\n\nNina frowned, but she did not give up. The next morning she carried her giant kite to the open field at the edge of town. She ran and ran, the string burning her hands, but the kite only bumped along the ground and tumbled into the dirt.\n\nPart 2\n\nNina sat down in the grass, her shoulders low. A girl she did not know walked over and sat beside her. \"My name is Priya,\" the girl said. \"I just moved here. That is the most beautiful kite I have ever seen.\"\n\n\"It is beautiful,\" Nina sighed, \"but it will not fly. It is too heavy for one person to lift into the wind.\"\n\nPriya thought for a moment. \"Maybe it does not need one person,\" she said. \"Maybe it needs two.\"\n\nThe girls made a plan. Priya held the kite high above her head while Nina took the string and ran. When Nina shouted, Priya let go. This time the wind caught the wide paper wings, and the great kite climbed higher and higher into the gray autumn sky. People in the field stopped to point and cheer.\n\nNina laughed until her cheeks hurt. \"I could never have done it alone,\" she told her new friend. From that day on, the two girls built every kite together, and each one flew higher than the last."},{"id":"P2","title":"The Clever Turtle and the Drought","genre":"fiction","lexile":"540L","text":"Part 1\n\nLong ago, when the rains stopped coming, the great forest grew dry and brown. The river shrank to a thin trickle, and at last only one small pond still held water. All the animals came to drink there, but they argued day and night over who should drink first.\n\n\"I am the strongest, so I should drink first!\" roared the lion.\n\n\"I am the tallest, so I should drink first!\" said the giraffe, stretching her long neck.\n\n\"I am the fastest!\" cried the gazelle. The arguing grew so loud that no one drank at all, and the precious water sat untouched while the animals shouted.\n\nA small turtle watched quietly from the muddy bank. She was not the strongest or the tallest or the fastest, and the others paid her no attention. But the turtle had something the others did not: a patient and thoughtful mind.\n\nPart 2\n\n\"Friends,\" the turtle called out in her small voice. The animals stopped to listen, more out of surprise than respect. \"If we keep fighting, the hot sun will dry the pond before anyone takes a single sip. Then we will all go thirsty.\"\n\nThe lion snorted, but he knew the turtle spoke the truth. \"What do you suggest, little one?\" he asked.\n\n\"Let us take turns,\" said the turtle. \"The smallest animals can drink first, for they need only a little. The largest can drink last, for they take the most. That way the pond will not be stirred into mud before everyone has had a chance.\"\n\nThe animals saw the wisdom in her plan. One by one, from smallest to largest, they drank their fill. The water stayed clear and cool, and there was enough for everyone. From that day on, whenever the animals faced a hard problem, they no longer asked who was strongest. Instead, they asked, \"What does the clever turtle think?\""},{"id":"P3","title":"Mountains of Fire","genre":"informational","lexile":"630L","text":"Part 1\n\nDeep beneath the ground you walk on, the Earth is far hotter than you might imagine. Many miles below the surface, rock becomes so hot that it melts into a thick, glowing liquid. This melted rock is called magma. Most of the time, the magma stays trapped far underground. But sometimes it finds a way to escape, and when it does, it can build a mountain of fire called a volcano.\n\nThe Earth''s outer shell is not one solid piece. Instead, it is broken into giant pieces, like a cracked eggshell. These pieces are always moving, though far too slowly for us to feel. Where two pieces meet, magma can push its way up through the cracks between them. Over many years, the magma that reaches the surface piles up and hardens into the cone shape of a volcano.\n\nPart 2\n\nWhen the pressure deep inside a volcano grows too great, the volcano erupts. Magma bursts out of an opening at the top, and once it reaches the surface, it is given a new name: lava. Lava can flow slowly down the sides of the mountain like a river of fire, or it can shoot high into the air. Along with the lava come clouds of ash, hot gas, and chunks of rock.\n\nVolcanoes can be dangerous, but they also do important work. The ash that settles on the ground breaks down over time into rich soil where plants grow well. Many islands in the ocean were built entirely by underwater volcanoes that erupted again and again until they rose above the waves. Scientists called volcanologists study volcanoes closely. By watching for small earthquakes and changes in the gases that leak out, they can often warn people before a volcano erupts, giving families time to move to safety."},{"id":"P4","title":"Wilma Rudolph: The Fastest Woman in the World","genre":"informational","lexile":"640L","text":"Part 1\n\nWilma Rudolph was born in 1940 in the state of Tennessee. She was a tiny baby, born too early, and she was sick again and again during her childhood. When she was just five years old, an illness called polio left her left leg weak and twisted. Doctors told her family that she might never walk normally again.\n\nBut Wilma and her mother refused to give up. Twice a week, her mother took her on a long bus ride to a hospital for treatments. At home, Wilma''s brothers and sisters took turns rubbing her weak leg every single day. Slowly, with years of hard work, Wilma began to walk without the heavy metal brace she had once needed. By the time she was twelve, she could run and play like any other child.\n\nPart 2\n\nOnce Wilma could run, she discovered she loved it more than anything. She joined her school''s basketball and track teams and quickly became a star. She was so fast that her coach gave her a nickname: \"Skeeter,\" because she buzzed around the track like a mosquito.\n\nIn 1960, Wilma traveled to Rome, Italy, to compete in the Olympic Games against the best runners in the world. There she did something amazing. She won three gold medals, becoming the first American woman ever to do so in a single Olympics. The crowds cheered for the young woman who had once been told she might never walk.\n\nWilma did not forget where she came from. After her racing days were over, she became a teacher and a coach. She started a program to help young athletes believe in themselves, just as she once had. Wilma Rudolph showed the world that with courage and hard work, a person can overcome almost any obstacle."},{"id":"P5","title":"The Lighthouse of Spring","genre":"poetry","lexile":"NP","text":"Part 1\n\nThe old apple tree stands by the gate,\nbare and gray through the winter''s wait.\nIts branches are empty, its bark is rough,\nthe cold winds blow, and the days are tough.\n\nBut deep in the wood, where no eye can see,\na secret is stirring inside the tree.\nThe roots drink rain from the softening ground,\nand sap climbs up without a sound.\n\nPart 2\n\nThen one bright morning the buds appear,\nlittle green promises, year after year.\nThe blossoms open, pink and white,\nlike tiny lanterns of soft spring light.\n\nThe bees come humming, the robins sing,\nthe whole tree glows with the gift of spring.\nAnd I understand, as I stand and stare:\nthe tree was working all winter there."}],"questions":[{"id":"Q1","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P1","questionText":"According to Part 1, what does Nina keep in the wooden box beneath her bed?","diagram":null,"options":["Toys she no longer plays with","Books about flying kites","Bright paper, thin sticks, and string","Old photographs and letters"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 1 says all year Nina saved bits of bright paper, thin sticks, and string in a wooden box beneath her bed.","points":1},{"id":"Q2","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What problem does Nina have at the end of Part 1?","diagram":null,"options":["Her brother takes her kite away.","Her giant kite is too heavy to lift into the wind.","The wind stops blowing across the field.","She runs out of paper before she can finish."],"answer":1,"explanation":"At the end of Part 1, the kite only bumps along the ground because it is too big and heavy to rise.","points":1},{"id":"Q3","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"grandest\" as it is used in Part 1?","diagram":null,"options":["Most colorful","Oldest","Most expensive","Most impressive and largest"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Nina wants the grandest kite the town had ever seen, and she builds one taller than she is, so grandest means the most impressive and largest.","points":1},{"id":"Q4","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Which word best describes Nina based on the whole story?","diagram":null,"options":["Fearful","Selfish","Determined","Careless"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Nina keeps trying even after her brother doubts her and her first attempt fails, which shows she is determined.","points":1},{"id":"Q5","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P1","questionText":"How do Nina and Priya finally get the kite to fly?","diagram":null,"options":["They tie the kite to the back of a bicycle.","They make the kite smaller and lighter.","They wait for a stronger wind to come.","Priya holds the kite up high while Nina runs with the string."],"answer":3,"explanation":"In Part 2, Priya holds the kite high while Nina runs with the string, and when Priya lets go, the wind lifts it.","points":1},{"id":"Q6","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What is the theme, or lesson, of this story?","diagram":null,"options":["Some problems can be solved by working together.","It is best to keep your ideas a secret from others.","You should never listen to your older brother.","Big kites are always better than small kites."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Nina cannot fly the kite alone, but with Priya''s help they succeed, showing that working together can solve a problem.","points":1},{"id":"Q7","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.5","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"How are Part 1 and Part 2 of the story connected?","diagram":null,"options":["Part 1 shows a problem Nina cannot solve alone, and Part 2 shows how a new friend helps her solve it.","Part 1 and Part 2 describe two completely different kites.","Part 1 explains a problem that is never solved in Part 2.","Part 2 happens many years before the events in Part 1."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Part 1 sets up the problem that the kite is too heavy for one person; Part 2 shows Priya helping Nina solve it together.","points":1},{"id":"Q8","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Which sentence from the text best shows that Nina did not give up after her kite failed the first time?","diagram":null,"options":["\"Nina frowned, but she did not give up.\"","\"A girl she did not know walked over and sat beside her.\"","\"It will never fly,\" said her older brother Tomas.","\"People in the field stopped to point and cheer.\""],"answer":0,"explanation":"The sentence stating Nina frowned but did not give up directly shows she kept trying despite the failure.","points":1},{"id":"Q9","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Why do all the animals come to the one small pond in Part 1?","diagram":null,"options":["It is the only place to find food.","It is the only place that still has water.","The lion has invited them all there.","They want to swim and play together."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 1 says the rains stopped, the river shrank, and only one small pond still held water, so the animals came there to drink.","points":1},{"id":"Q10","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Why does no one drink the water at first, even though they are thirsty?","diagram":null,"options":["The water is too dirty to drink.","They are waiting for the rain to return.","The turtle will not let them near the pond.","They are too busy arguing about who should go first."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Part 1 says the arguing grew so loud that no one drank at all while the animals shouted about who should be first.","points":1},{"id":"Q11","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"precious\" as it is used in Part 1?","diagram":null,"options":["Easy to find","Very valuable and important","Cold and clear","Dark and muddy"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The water is the only water left in a drought, so calling it precious means it is very valuable and important.","points":1},{"id":"Q12","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What plan does the turtle suggest to solve the problem?","diagram":null,"options":["The animals should wait until night to drink.","Each animal should dig its own small pond.","The strongest animal should guard the water.","The animals should drink in turns, from smallest to largest."],"answer":3,"explanation":"In Part 2, the turtle suggests the animals take turns drinking from smallest to largest so the water is not stirred into mud.","points":1},{"id":"Q13","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Which word best describes the turtle in the story?","diagram":null,"options":["Greedy","Boastful","Frightened","Wise"],"answer":3,"explanation":"The turtle thinks carefully and comes up with a fair plan that helps everyone, which shows she is wise.","points":1},{"id":"Q14","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What is the main lesson of this folktale?","diagram":null,"options":["Ponds should never be shared with other animals.","Strong animals will always get what they want.","It is better to keep quiet than to share an idea.","A good idea can matter more than being big or strong."],"answer":3,"explanation":"The small turtle solves the problem the strong animals could not, showing that a good idea can matter more than size or strength.","points":1},{"id":"Q15","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Which detail from the text best supports the idea that the animals came to respect the turtle?","diagram":null,"options":["\"A small turtle watched quietly from the muddy bank.\"","\"The lion snorted, but he knew the turtle spoke the truth.\"","\"They asked, ''What does the clever turtle think?''\"","\"She was not the strongest or the tallest or the fastest.\""],"answer":2,"explanation":"At the end, the animals begin asking what the clever turtle thinks whenever they face a problem, showing they came to respect her.","points":1},{"id":"Q16","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.9","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Use both \"The Kite Maker''s Gift\" and \"The Clever Turtle and the Drought\" to answer this question. What is one way Nina and the turtle are alike?","diagram":null,"options":["Both are the strongest character in their story.","Both solve a problem in a way the doubters did not expect.","Both win a race against faster animals.","Both build something out of paper and sticks."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Nina succeeds though her brother doubted her, and the turtle solves the problem though the bigger animals ignored her; both succeed in ways others did not expect.","points":1},{"id":"Q17","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P3","questionText":"According to Part 1, what is magma?","diagram":null,"options":["A type of hard rock found on islands","Melted rock found deep beneath the ground","A small earthquake near a volcano","A cloud of ash above a mountain"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 1 explains that far below the surface, rock melts into a thick, glowing liquid called magma.","points":1},{"id":"Q18","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"In Part 1, the author compares the Earth''s outer shell to a \"cracked eggshell.\" What does this comparison help the reader understand?","diagram":null,"options":["The outer shell is white and smooth.","The Earth is shaped exactly like an egg.","The Earth is very fragile and could break apart.","The outer shell is broken into giant moving pieces."],"answer":3,"explanation":"The author says the shell is broken into giant pieces like a cracked eggshell, helping the reader picture separate moving pieces.","points":1},{"id":"Q19","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"erupts\" as it is used in Part 2?","diagram":null,"options":["Bursts out with great force","Sinks back down underground","Slowly cools and hardens","Stops moving completely"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Part 2 says when pressure grows too great, the volcano erupts and magma bursts out, so erupts means bursts out with force.","points":1},{"id":"Q20","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"According to the text, what is melted rock called once it reaches the surface?","diagram":null,"options":["Magma","Ash","Soil","Lava"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Part 2 states that once magma reaches the surface, it is given a new name: lava.","points":1},{"id":"Q21","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"How does the author connect the ideas in Part 1 and Part 2 of the text?","diagram":null,"options":["Part 1 explains how a volcano forms underground, and Part 2 explains what happens when it erupts.","Part 1 and Part 2 describe two different mountains.","Part 2 gives the opposite opinion from Part 1.","Part 1 compares islands, and Part 2 compares oceans."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Part 1 describes how magma builds a volcano; Part 2 explains the eruption, so the parts build on each other in order.","points":1},{"id":"Q22","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the connection between volcanic ash settling on the ground and plants growing well?","diagram":null,"options":["It lists steps in time order only.","It presents a problem with no solution.","It shows cause and effect: the ash breaks down and makes rich soil where plants grow.","It compares two things that are alike."],"answer":2,"explanation":"The ash settles and breaks down into rich soil (cause), which helps plants grow well (effect), a cause-and-effect connection.","points":1},{"id":"Q23","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"Select the two ways the text says volcanoes can be helpful.","diagram":null,"options":["They make the weather warmer all over the world.","They cause the giant pieces of Earth to stop moving.","They built many islands in the ocean.","Their ash breaks down into rich soil for plants."],"answer":[2,3],"explanation":"The text says volcanic ash forms rich soil and that many ocean islands were built by underwater volcanoes. The other choices are not stated.","points":1},{"id":"Q24","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.2","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the main idea of this text?","diagram":null,"options":["Lava always shoots high into the air during an eruption.","Islands are the safest place to watch a volcano.","Volcanoes form when hot magma escapes from inside the Earth, and they can be both dangerous and helpful.","Scientists cannot tell when a volcano will erupt."],"answer":2,"explanation":"The text explains how volcanoes form from escaping magma and describes their dangers and benefits, which together form the main idea.","points":1},{"id":"Q25","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"Which detail from the text best supports the idea that scientists can help keep people safe from volcanoes?","diagram":null,"options":["\"Most of the time, the magma stays trapped far underground.\"","\"By watching for small earthquakes and changes in the gases, they can often warn people before a volcano erupts.\"","\"Lava can flow slowly down the sides of the mountain like a river of fire.\"","\"The Earth''s outer shell is not one solid piece.\""],"answer":1,"explanation":"The detail about scientists watching for warning signs and warning people before an eruption supports that they help keep people safe.","points":1},{"id":"Q26","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P4","questionText":"In what state was Wilma Rudolph born?","diagram":null,"options":["Tennessee","Italy","Tennessee''s capital city of Rome","California"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Part 1 says Wilma Rudolph was born in 1940 in the state of Tennessee.","points":1},{"id":"Q27","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"What happened to Wilma when she was five years old?","diagram":null,"options":["She joined a basketball team.","She won her first race.","An illness called polio left her left leg weak.","She moved to Italy with her family."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 1 states that when she was five, polio left her left leg weak and twisted.","points":1},{"id":"Q28","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"How did Wilma''s family help her get better?","diagram":null,"options":["Her mother took her for treatments and her siblings rubbed her leg every day.","They moved her to a warmer state.","They bought her a new metal brace each year.","They hired a famous track coach to train her."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Part 1 says her mother took her for treatments twice a week and her brothers and sisters rubbed her weak leg every single day.","points":1},{"id":"Q29","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"Why did Wilma''s coach give her the nickname \"Skeeter\"?","diagram":null,"options":["Because she was small as a baby","Because she buzzed around the track like a mosquito","Because she came from a place called Skeeter","Because she liked to play in the summer"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 2 explains the coach called her Skeeter because she buzzed around the track like a mosquito.","points":1},{"id":"Q30","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"What amazing thing did Wilma do at the 1960 Olympic Games?","diagram":null,"options":["She became the first woman to walk without a brace.","She became a teacher and a coach.","She won three gold medals in a single Olympics.","She started a program for young athletes."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 2 says she won three gold medals, becoming the first American woman to do so in a single Olympics.","points":1},{"id":"Q31","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"How does the author connect the ideas in Part 1 and Part 2 of the text?","diagram":null,"options":["Part 2 explains a problem that Part 1 never mentions.","Part 1 and Part 2 describe two different runners.","Part 1 tells how Wilma overcame illness to walk, and Part 2 tells how she became a champion runner.","Part 1 gives the opposite opinion from Part 2."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 1 shows Wilma learning to walk again; Part 2 builds on that by showing her become an Olympic champion.","points":1},{"id":"Q32","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"What is the connection between Wilma being told she might never walk and the crowds cheering for her in Rome?","diagram":null,"options":["It compares Wilma to the other Olympic runners.","It lists her medals in the order she won them.","It shows a problem and the steps used to fix a machine.","It shows a contrast: she overcame what doctors said she could never do."],"answer":3,"explanation":"The text contrasts the doctors'' warning that she might never walk with her later Olympic victory, showing how far she came.","points":1},{"id":"Q33","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"Select the two things Wilma Rudolph did AFTER her racing days were over.","diagram":null,"options":["She became a teacher and a coach.","She won three Olympic gold medals.","She learned to walk without a brace.","She started a program to help young athletes."],"answer":[0,3],"explanation":"Part 2 says that after her racing days, Wilma became a teacher and coach and started a program to help young athletes. Winning medals and learning to walk happened earlier.","points":1},{"id":"Q34","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"Which sentence from the text best supports the idea that Wilma wanted to help others after her racing days?","diagram":null,"options":["\"She started a program to help young athletes believe in themselves.\"","\"She won three gold medals, becoming the first American woman ever to do so.\"","\"Wilma Rudolph was born in 1940 in the state of Tennessee.\"","\"She was so fast that her coach gave her a nickname.\""],"answer":0,"explanation":"The sentence about starting a program to help young athletes believe in themselves shows she wanted to help others.","points":1},{"id":"Q35","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P5","questionText":"What is the poem mostly about?","diagram":null,"options":["How an apple tree changes from winter to spring","How to pick apples in the autumn","Why bees and robins like apple trees","A boy who plants a new apple tree"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The poem describes the bare apple tree in winter and then its buds and blossoms in spring, so it is mostly about the tree changing across seasons.","points":1},{"id":"Q36","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"What is the meaning of the phrase \"little green promises\" in Part 2?","diagram":null,"options":["Green ribbons tied to the branches","Buds that promise blossoms and fruit are coming","Little green insects on the leaves","Small green coins hidden in the tree"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The phrase describes the new buds, which are a sign, or promise, that blossoms and fruit will soon come.","points":1},{"id":"Q37","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"The blossoms are compared to \"tiny lanterns of soft spring light.\" What does this comparison help the reader picture?","diagram":null,"options":["The bright, glowing way the blossoms look in the spring.","The blossoms are made of paper and string.","The blossoms are warm to the touch.","The blossoms light up at night like real lamps."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Comparing blossoms to lanterns of light helps the reader picture how bright and glowing the blossoms look in spring.","points":1},{"id":"Q38","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.5","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"How are Part 1 and Part 2 of the poem different?","diagram":null,"options":["Part 1 is about a tree, and Part 2 is about a garden.","Part 1 rhymes, but Part 2 does not rhyme.","Part 1 describes the tree in winter, and Part 2 describes the tree in spring.","Part 1 describes daytime, and Part 2 describes nighttime."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 1 shows the bare, gray tree in winter, while Part 2 shows the blossoming tree in spring.","points":1},{"id":"Q39","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"What does the speaker understand at the end of the poem?","diagram":null,"options":["Winter lasts longer than spring.","The tree was secretly working all through the winter.","Bees are the most important part of spring.","The tree should be cut down in spring."],"answer":1,"explanation":"The last lines say the speaker understands the tree was working all winter there, even when it looked bare.","points":1},{"id":"Q40","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.9","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"Use both \"The Clever Turtle and the Drought\" and \"The Lighthouse of Spring\" to answer this question. What is one idea both texts share?","diagram":null,"options":["Both are poems with rhyming lines.","Both show that quiet, patient effort can lead to something good.","Both take place during a long, dry drought.","Both are mainly about animals racing one another."],"answer":1,"explanation":"The turtle quietly and patiently solves a problem, and the tree quietly works all winter to bloom; both show patient effort leading to a good result.","points":1}]}');
INSERT INTO "tests" ("id","grade","subject","test_type","title","time_limit_minutes","question_count","source","created_at","data") VALUES('g3-read-eog-4',3,'reading','eog','Grade 3 Reading — EOG Practice Test 4',120,40,'curated','2026-06-02T00:00:00.000Z','{"id":"g3-read-eog-4","grade":3,"subject":"reading","testType":"eog","title":"Grade 3 Reading — EOG Practice Test 4","instructions":"Read each selection carefully. Then answer the questions. Choose the one best answer for each question unless you are told to select more than one.","timeLimitMinutes":120,"calculatorAllowed":false,"source":"curated","passages":[{"id":"P1","title":"The Stubborn Goat","genre":"fiction","lexile":"560L","text":"Part 1\n\nEvery morning before school, Lupe led her goat, Pepper, from the barn to the green field behind the house. Pepper was small and gray, with one black ear and a stubborn streak as wide as the river. Some mornings Pepper trotted along happily. Other mornings she planted her hooves in the dirt and would not move, no matter how hard Lupe tugged the rope.\n\nOne cold morning, Pepper would not budge. Lupe pulled. She pushed. She even tried pushing from behind, but Pepper only swung her head and chewed on Lupe''s sleeve. The school bus would come soon, and Lupe felt her face grow hot with worry.\n\n\"Please, Pepper,\" Lupe begged. \"I cannot leave you in the yard near Mother''s flowers.\" But the goat just blinked her yellow eyes and stayed as still as a stone.\n\nPart 2\n\nLupe sat down on an old bucket to think. She remembered that Pepper always came running whenever the corn bin rattled. Slowly, a plan formed in her mind. Lupe walked to the barn, scooped a handful of corn into a tin cup, and gave the cup a loud shake.\n\nAt the sound, Pepper''s one black ear shot straight up. The goat forgot all about being stubborn and bounded across the yard toward the field, bleating the whole way. Lupe scattered a little corn in the grass and clipped the rope to the fence post. Pepper munched happily, her tail wagging.\n\nLupe ran to catch the bus just as it rolled to a stop. She was out of breath, but she was smiling. Sometimes, she thought, you cannot win by pulling harder. Sometimes you have to be a little clever instead."},{"id":"P2","title":"How Maple Crossing Got Its Name","genre":"fiction","lexile":"600L","text":"Part 1\n\nLong ago, in the days when folks tell some mighty tall tales, there lived a woman named Big Hattie. Now Big Hattie was so strong that she could lift a wagon with one hand while shaking out a rug with the other. Her laugh was so loud that it shook ripe apples right off the trees, and birds would faint clean out of the sky.\n\nOne spring, the rains came down so hard that the river jumped its banks and washed away the only bridge for miles. The people of the town stood on the muddy shore, scratching their heads. \"How will we ever cross now?\" they sighed.\n\nBig Hattie just rolled up her sleeves. \"Step aside,\" she said with a grin.\n\nPart 2\n\nBig Hattie marched into the woods and wrapped her arms around the tallest maple tree you ever did see. With one great heave, she pulled it up by the roots as easily as a child picks a flower. Then she laid that maple tree flat across the roaring river, from one bank to the other.\n\n\"There,\" she said, wiping her hands. \"Now you have yourselves a bridge.\"\n\nThe maple tree was so wide that two wagons could roll across it side by side, and so long that it never once sagged in the middle. The townsfolk crossed back and forth for years, and they were so grateful that they named their town Maple Crossing.\n\nTo this day, the old folks say that if you stand very still on a windy evening, you can still hear Big Hattie''s mighty laugh rolling through the hills, knocking apples off the trees."},{"id":"P3","title":"What Makes a Thunderstorm?","genre":"informational","lexile":"640L","text":"Part 1\n\nA thunderstorm can fill the sky with dark clouds, loud crashes, and bright flashes of light. Thunderstorms may seem scary, but they begin with something simple: warm, wet air. On a hot day, the sun heats the ground. The ground warms the air just above it. Because warm air is lighter than cool air, the warm air begins to rise.\n\nAs the warm air rises higher into the sky, it carries tiny drops of water with it. High up, the air is much colder. The cold air causes the water drops to clump together and form a tall cloud. When the cloud grows big enough and dark enough, a storm is ready to begin.\n\nPart 2\n\nInside the storm cloud, water drops and bits of ice bump and rub against one another. This rubbing builds up a kind of energy called electricity. When enough electricity builds up, it leaps from the cloud in a giant spark. That spark is lightning.\n\nLightning is very hot, even hotter than the surface of the sun. It heats the air around it so quickly that the air swells out with a loud bang. That bang is the thunder we hear. Because light travels faster than sound, we always see the flash of lightning before we hear the rumble of thunder.\n\nThunderstorms do important work. The rain they bring waters crops and fills rivers and lakes. So the next time a storm rolls in, remember that it all started with warm air rising on a sunny day."},{"id":"P4","title":"Garrett Morgan: A Helpful Inventor","genre":"informational","lexile":"620L","text":"Part 1\n\nGarrett Morgan was born in Kentucky in 1877. As a young man, he moved to the city of Cleveland, Ohio, to look for work. He found a job fixing sewing machines, and he learned how all of their tiny parts fit together. Soon Garrett began to wonder if he could build helpful machines of his own.\n\nGarrett was a careful watcher of the world around him. He noticed problems that other people walked right past, and then he tried to solve them. Over the years he invented many useful things, but two of his inventions helped save lives.\n\nPart 2\n\nIn those days, the streets were becoming crowded with cars, wagons, and people on foot. Traffic signals had only two settings: stop and go. There was no warning before the signal switched, so crashes happened often. One day Garrett saw an accident at a busy corner, and he decided to act.\n\nGarrett built a new kind of traffic signal with a third setting that warned drivers the signal was about to change. This gave people time to slow down and stop safely. His idea led to the yellow caution light we still use today.\n\nGarrett also invented a safety hood that let firefighters breathe clean air inside smoky buildings. He even used it himself to rescue workers trapped in a tunnel. Garrett Morgan spent his whole life looking for problems to solve, and his careful eyes made the world a safer place for everyone."},{"id":"P5","title":"The Old Apple Tree","genre":"poetry","lexile":"NP","text":"Part 1\n\nThe old apple tree stands tall in the yard,\nIts bark is brown and its branches are scarred.\nIt has weathered the snow and the summer sun,\nAnd it gives us shade when the day is done.\n\nIn spring it wears a soft pink crown,\nWhite blossoms that flutter and drift to the ground.\nThe bees come humming from far and near,\nTo sip the sweet flowers that bloom each year.\n\nPart 2\n\nIn summer the tree is a tower of green,\nThe coolest, the leafiest place to be seen.\nWe climb to a branch and we sway in the breeze,\nAnd watch the whole world through a window of leaves.\n\nWhen autumn arrives with its red and gold,\nThe apples hang heavy, a treasure to hold.\nWe gather them up in our baskets with care,\nAnd Grandmother bakes us a pie to share.\n\nThe old apple tree is a friend that we keep,\nThrough seasons of laughter and seasons of sleep.\nIt asks for so little and gives us so much—\nA gift from the earth that we treasure to touch."}],"questions":[{"id":"Q1","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P1","questionText":"According to Part 1, where does Lupe lead Pepper each morning?","diagram":null,"options":["To the corn bin in the barn","To the green field behind the house","To the school bus stop","To the river near the town"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 1 begins by saying Lupe led her goat from the barn to the green field behind the house each morning.","points":1},{"id":"Q2","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"budge\" as it is used in Part 1?","diagram":null,"options":["To move from one place","To fall fast asleep","To eat something quickly","To make a loud noise"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The text says Pepper \"would not budge\" and planted her hooves, meaning she would not move from where she stood.","points":1},{"id":"Q3","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What does Lupe do right after she remembers that Pepper comes running when the corn bin rattles?","diagram":null,"options":["She scoops corn into a tin cup and shakes it.","She pushes the goat from behind.","She sits down on an old bucket.","She runs to catch the school bus."],"answer":0,"explanation":"After her plan forms, Lupe walks to the barn, scoops corn into a tin cup, and shakes it to get Pepper''s attention.","points":1},{"id":"Q4","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What does the phrase \"as still as a stone\" help the reader understand in Part 1?","diagram":null,"options":["Pepper is hiding behind the flowers.","Pepper is not moving at all.","Pepper is very heavy and gray.","Pepper is cold in the morning air."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Comparing the goat to a stone shows that Pepper stayed completely still and would not move.","points":1},{"id":"Q5","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Which word best describes Lupe in the story?","diagram":null,"options":["Clever","Lazy","Fearful","Unkind"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Instead of pulling harder, Lupe thinks of a smart plan to lure Pepper with corn, which shows she is clever.","points":1},{"id":"Q6","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What is the lesson of the story?","diagram":null,"options":["Animals should never be kept as pets.","You should never be late for the bus.","It is always best to give up quickly.","Being clever can work better than using force."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Lupe learns that she cannot win by pulling harder and that being a little clever solves the problem, which is the story''s lesson.","points":1},{"id":"Q7","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Which detail from the text best shows that Lupe was worried?","diagram":null,"options":["\"She was out of breath, but she was smiling.\"","\"Pepper was small and gray, with one black ear...\"","\"Pepper munched happily, her tail wagging.\"","\"...Lupe felt her face grow hot with worry.\""],"answer":3,"explanation":"The line stating that Lupe \"felt her face grow hot with worry\" directly shows she was worried.","points":1},{"id":"Q8","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Select the two things Lupe tries before her plan with the corn works.","diagram":null,"options":["She ties Pepper to the fence post.","She begs Pepper to move.","She shakes a cup of corn.","She pulls and pushes the rope."],"answer":[1,3],"explanation":"Before the corn plan, Lupe pulls and pushes Pepper and begs her to move. Shaking the corn and tying her to the post happen as part of the successful plan.","points":1},{"id":"Q9","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P2","questionText":"According to Part 1, what washes away the only bridge for miles?","diagram":null,"options":["A falling maple tree","Big Hattie''s loud laugh","The river flooding over its banks","A strong wind"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 1 says the rains came down so hard that the river jumped its banks and washed away the bridge.","points":1},{"id":"Q10","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.5","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"This story is a tall tale. Which detail best shows that it is a tall tale rather than a true story?","diagram":null,"options":["The townsfolk stand on the muddy shore.","Big Hattie pulls up a giant maple tree by the roots with her arms.","Big Hattie rolls up her sleeves.","The people name their town Maple Crossing."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Pulling up a giant tree by its roots with bare arms is impossible and exaggerated, which is a sign of a tall tale.","points":1},{"id":"Q11","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What does the word \"heave\" mean as it is used in Part 2?","diagram":null,"options":["A strong pull or lift","A gentle whisper","A quiet rest","A loud laugh"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Big Hattie pulls the tree up \"with one great heave,\" meaning she uses one strong pull or lift.","points":1},{"id":"Q12","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Why do the townsfolk name their town Maple Crossing?","diagram":null,"options":["Many maple trees grow all around the town.","Big Hattie was also known as Maple.","They cross the river on Big Hattie''s maple-tree bridge.","Maple syrup is made in the town each spring."],"answer":2,"explanation":"The town is named for the maple tree Big Hattie laid across the river, which the townsfolk cross for years.","points":1},{"id":"Q13","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What does the phrase \"her laugh was so loud that it shook ripe apples right off the trees\" help the reader understand about Big Hattie?","diagram":null,"options":["She liked to eat many apples.","She worked picking apples for a living.","She had a powerful, enormous laugh.","She was afraid of loud noises."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Saying her laugh shook apples off the trees is an exaggeration that shows how powerful and huge her laugh was.","points":1},{"id":"Q14","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Which word best describes Big Hattie?","diagram":null,"options":["Worried","Shy","Selfish","Confident"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Big Hattie grins, says \"Step aside,\" and solves the problem with ease, which shows she is confident.","points":1},{"id":"Q15","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Use both parts of this text to answer this question. What is the main message of the story?","diagram":null,"options":["A strong, willing helper can solve a big problem for a whole town.","Maple trees make the best kind of bridges.","Towns should always be built near rivers.","People should never travel during a storm."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Across both parts, Big Hattie steps in and uses her strength to give the whole town a way to cross, showing how one willing helper can solve a big problem.","points":1},{"id":"Q16","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P2","questionText":"How wide is the maple-tree bridge that Big Hattie makes?","diagram":null,"options":["Wide enough for two wagons to roll side by side","Only wide enough for the birds","Too narrow for anyone to cross","Wide enough for one person to walk across"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Part 2 states the maple tree was so wide that two wagons could roll across it side by side.","points":1},{"id":"Q17","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P3","questionText":"According to Part 1, what does the sun heat first to begin a thunderstorm?","diagram":null,"options":["The cold air","The rain","The ground","The clouds high in the sky"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 1 explains that the sun heats the ground, and the ground then warms the air just above it.","points":1},{"id":"Q18","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"Why does the warm air begin to rise into the sky?","diagram":null,"options":["Rain pulls the air higher.","The clouds are too heavy to stay down.","Warm air is lighter than cool air.","Lightning pushes the air upward."],"answer":2,"explanation":"The text states that because warm air is lighter than cool air, the warm air begins to rise.","points":1},{"id":"Q19","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What step happens right after enough electricity builds up inside the storm cloud?","diagram":null,"options":["The warm air begins to rise.","A giant spark leaps from the cloud as lightning.","The water drops clump into a tall cloud.","The sun heats the ground."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 2 says when enough electricity builds up, it leaps from the cloud in a giant spark, which is lightning.","points":1},{"id":"Q20","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"swells\" as it is used in Part 2?","diagram":null,"options":["Grows quiet","Pushes out and grows larger","Falls toward the ground","Cools down slowly"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The air \"swells out with a loud bang,\" meaning it pushes out and grows larger very quickly.","points":1},{"id":"Q21","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"How does the author connect the ideas in Part 1 and Part 2 of the text?","diagram":null,"options":["By telling a story about one rainy day","By describing the steps that lead to thunder and lightning, in order","By comparing two different kinds of storms","By listing reasons people should fear storms"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 1 explains how the storm cloud forms and Part 2 continues with how lightning and thunder happen, giving the steps of a thunderstorm in order.","points":1},{"id":"Q22","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the connection between lightning and thunder, according to Part 2?","diagram":null,"options":["Lightning heats the air so fast that it makes the thunder sound.","Thunder causes lightning to form.","Lightning and thunder happen for completely separate reasons.","Thunder cools the air and creates lightning."],"answer":0,"explanation":"The text shows cause and effect: lightning heats the air so quickly that it swells out with a loud bang, which is the thunder.","points":1},{"id":"Q23","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.2","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the main idea of the text?","diagram":null,"options":["Thunderstorms are too dangerous to study.","Rain is the only useful part of a storm.","Thunderstorms form through a series of steps that begin with warm air rising.","Lightning is hotter than the surface of the sun."],"answer":2,"explanation":"The whole text explains how thunderstorms form step by step, starting with warm air rising on a sunny day.","points":1},{"id":"Q24","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"Which statement from the text best supports the idea that thunderstorms are helpful?","diagram":null,"options":["\"The rain they bring waters crops and fills rivers and lakes.\"","\"That bang is the thunder we hear.\"","\"Lightning is very hot, even hotter than the surface of the sun.\"","\"Thunderstorms may seem scary...\""],"answer":0,"explanation":"The line about rain watering crops and filling rivers and lakes supports the idea that thunderstorms do important, helpful work.","points":1},{"id":"Q25","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P4","questionText":"According to Part 1, what was Garrett Morgan''s first job in Cleveland?","diagram":null,"options":["Fixing sewing machines","Building traffic signals","Driving wagons","Fighting fires"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Part 1 says Garrett found a job fixing sewing machines and learned how their parts fit together.","points":1},{"id":"Q26","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"What made Garrett decide to build a new kind of traffic signal?","diagram":null,"options":["His boss told him to build one.","He saw an accident at a busy corner.","He wanted to win a prize.","He read about signals in a book."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 2 says one day Garrett saw an accident at a busy corner, and he decided to act.","points":1},{"id":"Q27","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"caution\" as it is used in Part 2?","diagram":null,"options":["Speed and hurry","Care and warning","Anger and noise","Rest and sleep"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The yellow caution light warns drivers the signal is about to change, so \"caution\" means care and warning.","points":1},{"id":"Q28","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"What is the main idea of the text?","diagram":null,"options":["Sewing machines have many tiny parts.","Garrett Morgan was born in Kentucky in 1877.","Old traffic signals had only two settings.","Garrett Morgan was an inventor who solved problems to keep people safe."],"answer":3,"explanation":"The text as a whole shows that Garrett Morgan noticed problems and invented things, like the caution light and safety hood, that kept people safe.","points":1},{"id":"Q29","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"How does the author connect the ideas in Part 2 about the traffic signal?","diagram":null,"options":["By listing the years Garrett worked","By comparing two cities Garrett lived in","By describing what a sewing machine looks like","By presenting a problem and the solution Garrett created"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Part 2 first describes the problem of dangerous signals with no warning, then explains Garrett''s solution: a third setting that warned drivers.","points":1},{"id":"Q30","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"Select the two inventions described in the text that helped save lives.","diagram":null,"options":["A faster kind of wagon","A safety hood for breathing clean air","A sewing machine","A traffic signal with a warning setting"],"answer":[1,3],"explanation":"The text says two of Garrett''s inventions helped save lives: the improved traffic signal and the safety hood that let firefighters breathe clean air.","points":1},{"id":"Q31","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"Which word best describes Garrett Morgan, based on the text?","diagram":null,"options":["Fearful","Careless","Observant","Forgetful"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The text says Garrett was a careful watcher who noticed problems others walked past, which shows he was observant.","points":1},{"id":"Q32","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"According to the text, what did Garrett''s safety hood allow firefighters to do?","diagram":null,"options":["See clearly in the dark","Lift heavy objects more easily","Breathe clean air inside smoky buildings","Drive through busy streets safely"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 2 states the safety hood let firefighters breathe clean air inside smoky buildings.","points":1},{"id":"Q33","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P5","questionText":"According to Part 1, what does the apple tree give in spring?","diagram":null,"options":["Red and gold leaves","Baskets of ripe apples","A pie to share","Soft pink and white blossoms"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Part 1 says in spring the tree wears a soft pink crown of white blossoms that flutter and drift to the ground.","points":1},{"id":"Q34","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"What does the poet mean by the phrase \"a window of leaves\" in Part 2?","diagram":null,"options":["A picture of leaves hanging in the house","Leaves that are made of glass","A real glass window on the tree","Looking out at the world through the leafy branches"],"answer":3,"explanation":"From up in the tree, the children watch the world through the leaves, so \"a window of leaves\" means looking out through the leafy branches.","points":1},{"id":"Q35","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P5","questionText":"In Part 2, the line \"the coolest, the leafiest place to be seen\" helps the reader picture the tree in which season?","diagram":null,"options":["Summer","Winter","Autumn","Spring"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The line appears in the stanza that begins \"In summer the tree is a tower of green,\" describing the tree in summer.","points":1},{"id":"Q36","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"What is the main message of the poem?","diagram":null,"options":["Apple trees are hard to take care of.","The apple tree is a treasured friend that gives gifts through all the seasons.","Autumn is the best season of the year.","Children should not climb trees."],"answer":1,"explanation":"The poem describes the tree''s gifts in every season and calls it a friend the family treasures, which is its main message.","points":1},{"id":"Q37","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.5","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P5","questionText":"How is the poem mainly organized?","diagram":null,"options":["By giving directions for planting a tree","By telling about the tree through the four seasons","By describing a problem and a solution","By comparing two different trees"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The poem moves through spring, summer, and autumn, describing the apple tree across the seasons.","points":1},{"id":"Q38","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P5","questionText":"Which line from the poem best shows that the family loves the tree?","diagram":null,"options":["\"The bees come humming from far and near,\"","\"When autumn arrives with its red and gold,\"","\"The old apple tree is a friend that we keep,\"","\"Its bark is brown and its branches are scarred.\""],"answer":2,"explanation":"Calling the tree \"a friend that we keep\" shows the family''s love for it.","points":1},{"id":"Q39","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.5","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P5","questionText":"What does the family do with the apples they gather in autumn?","diagram":null,"options":["They sell them at a market.","They plant them to grow new trees.","They give them all to the bees.","Grandmother bakes them into a pie to share."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Part 2 says they gather the apples and Grandmother bakes them a pie to share.","points":1},{"id":"Q40","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.9","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"Both \"The Stubborn Goat\" and \"The Old Apple Tree\" share which idea?","diagram":null,"options":["A strong helper saves a whole town.","A storm changes everyone''s plans.","A clever trick solves a hard problem.","Something in nature is valued by the people in the text."],"answer":3,"explanation":"In both texts, something from nature is valued: Lupe cares for her goat, and the family treasures the apple tree. The other choices fit only one text or another in the set.","points":1}]}');
INSERT INTO "tests" ("id","grade","subject","test_type","title","time_limit_minutes","question_count","source","created_at","data") VALUES('g3-read-eog-5',3,'reading','eog','Grade 3 Reading — EOG Practice Test 5',120,40,'curated','2026-06-02T00:00:00.000Z','{"id":"g3-read-eog-5","grade":3,"subject":"reading","testType":"eog","title":"Grade 3 Reading — EOG Practice Test 5","instructions":"Read each selection carefully. Then answer the questions. Choose the one best answer for each question unless you are told to select more than one.","timeLimitMinutes":120,"calculatorAllowed":false,"source":"curated","passages":[{"id":"P1","title":"The Lost Library Book","genre":"fiction","lexile":"580L","text":"Part 1\n\nMaya loved Tuesdays because Tuesday was library day. Each week she chose one book to take home, and each week she returned it on time. But this Tuesday was different. When Mr. Patel asked for her book about sea turtles, Maya reached into her backpack and found nothing but crumbs and a broken pencil.\n\nHer cheeks turned warm. \"I lost it,\" she whispered. Mr. Patel smiled kindly and told her not to worry, but Maya worried anyway. That book did not belong to her. It belonged to the whole school, and she had let everyone down.\n\nAll afternoon Maya thought about where the book could be. She had read it at the kitchen table. She had read it in the car. She had even read it under her blanket with a flashlight when she was supposed to be asleep.\n\nPart 2\n\nThat evening, Maya decided to retrace her steps, just like a detective. She looked under the kitchen table. Nothing. She searched the back seat of the car. Nothing but an old sock. Then she remembered the flashlight and the blanket.\n\nMaya raced to her bedroom and pulled back the covers. There, squished against the wall at the foot of her bed, was the sea turtle book. She had fallen asleep reading it, and it had slipped between the bed and the wall.\n\nThe next morning Maya carried the book to school as carefully as if it were made of glass. She handed it to Mr. Patel and apologized for the late return. \"I''m proud of you for not giving up,\" he said. From that day on, Maya kept her library books in one special spot on her desk, where they could never disappear again."},{"id":"P2","title":"The Crow and the Pitcher''s Cousin","genre":"fiction","lexile":"600L","text":"Part 1\n\nIn a dry corner of the meadow, a thirsty rabbit named Bram hopped from stone to stone, searching for water. The sun had baked the ground hard, and every puddle had vanished. At last Bram found a tall, narrow jug resting in the shade of a fence post. He peered inside and saw a thin shine of water far down at the bottom.\n\nBram pushed his nose into the jug, but the opening was too small for his head. He tipped the jug, but it was heavy and would not budge. He even tried to knock it over with his strong back legs, but the jug only wobbled and stayed upright. Bram sat down, tired and discouraged.\n\nPart 2\n\nJust then a wise old crow landed on the fence post above him. \"I once watched my cousin solve a puzzle just like this,\" the crow said. \"Watch the ground, friend, not the jug.\"\n\nBram looked at the ground and saw it was scattered with small, round pebbles. He remembered the crow''s words and began to think. One by one, he dropped pebbles into the jug. Plink. Plink. Plink. Slowly, the water crept higher and higher, until at last it reached the very top.\n\nBram drank deeply and thanked the crow. \"You did the work yourself,\" the crow replied. \"I only reminded you that a hard problem can be solved a small piece at a time.\" Bram hopped home that evening, no longer thirsty, and he never forgot the lesson of the pebbles."},{"id":"P3","title":"How Honeybees Make Honey","genre":"informational","lexile":"640L","text":"Part 1\n\nHave you ever wondered where the honey on your toast comes from? It is made by honeybees, and the process begins far away in a field of flowers. A honeybee flies from flower to flower, drinking a sweet liquid called nectar. The bee stores the nectar in a special pouch inside its body, almost like a tiny backpack just for carrying food.\n\nWhen the bee''s pouch is full, it flies back to the hive. There it passes the nectar to other worker bees. These bees chew the nectar for a while, which changes it bit by bit. Then they spread the thick liquid into small wax rooms called cells.\n\nPart 2\n\nThe nectar is still too watery to be honey, so the bees must dry it out. They beat their wings fast, like tiny fans, to blow air across the cells. As the air moves, the extra water disappears, and the nectar grows thick and sticky. Now it has finally become honey.\n\nTo keep the honey safe, the bees seal each full cell with a cap of wax. The honey can be stored this way for a long time. Bees make far more honey than they need so they will have plenty of food during the cold winter when no flowers bloom. Beekeepers gently take only the extra honey, leaving enough for the bees. The next time you taste honey, remember the long journey it took, from a flower to a hive to your table."},{"id":"P4","title":"Wilma Rudolph Runs to Gold","genre":"informational","lexile":"630L","text":"Part 1\n\nWhen Wilma Rudolph was a little girl, very few people thought she would ever run. She was born in 1940 in Tennessee, one of many children in a large family. As a child she grew very sick with an illness that left her left leg weak. For years she wore a heavy brace and could not walk without help.\n\nBut Wilma was determined. Every day her mother and her brothers and sisters took turns rubbing her weak leg to help it grow stronger. Wilma practiced standing, then walking, a little more each day. By the time she was twelve years old, she surprised everyone by taking off the brace and walking on her own.\n\nPart 2\n\nOnce Wilma could walk, she discovered she could run, and run fast. She joined her school track team and soon was winning race after race. People who had once felt sorry for her now cheered her name from the stands.\n\nIn 1960, Wilma traveled to the Olympic Games in Rome, Italy. There she raced against the fastest women in the world. When the games were over, Wilma had won three gold medals, becoming the first American woman ever to do so in a single Olympics. The girl who once could not walk had become one of the fastest runners on Earth. Wilma later returned home to teach and coach, showing young people that hard work and courage can carry them far."},{"id":"P5","title":"The Garden After Rain","genre":"poetry","lexile":"NP","text":"Part 1\n\nThe rain has gone, the clouds have cleared,\nThe garden glows where gray appeared.\nEach leaf is washed a brighter green,\nThe cleanest world I''ve ever seen.\n\nA spider''s web hangs near the gate,\nLike beads of glass the raindrops wait.\nThey catch the sun and softly gleam,\nA tiny string of silver dream.\n\nPart 2\n\nThe robin hops across the lawn,\nTo greet the bright and dripping dawn.\nHe pulls a worm up from the ground,\nThen tilts his head at every sound.\n\nThe flowers lift their drooping heads,\nAnd stretch awake in muddy beds.\nThe whole world drank its morning cup,\nAnd now the garden wakens up.\n\nSo let the rain come, soft and slow,\nIt helps the sleeping garden grow.\nFor after every cloudy day,\nThe sun returns to light the way."}],"questions":[{"id":"Q1","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P1","questionText":"According to Part 1, what book had Maya borrowed from the library?","diagram":null,"options":["A book about cars","A book about detectives","A book about flashlights","A book about sea turtles"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Part 1 says Mr. Patel asked for her book about sea turtles, which is the book Maya had borrowed.","points":1},{"id":"Q2","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What does the phrase \"Her cheeks turned warm\" help the reader understand about Maya?","diagram":null,"options":["She was feeling sick.","She was sitting too close to a fire.","She had been running fast.","She felt embarrassed and worried."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Maya''s cheeks turn warm right after she admits she lost the book, showing she felt embarrassed and worried.","points":1},{"id":"Q3","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What does Maya decide to do that evening to find the book?","diagram":null,"options":["She asks Mr. Patel to help her search.","She retraces her steps like a detective.","She gives up and goes to sleep.","She buys a new book for the library."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 2 says Maya decided to retrace her steps, just like a detective, to find the book.","points":1},{"id":"Q4","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Where does Maya finally find the lost book?","diagram":null,"options":["Under the kitchen table","On her desk at school","Squished between her bed and the wall","In the back seat of the car"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 2 says the book was squished against the wall at the foot of her bed, where it had slipped between the bed and the wall.","points":1},{"id":"Q5","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Which word best describes Maya in the story?","diagram":null,"options":["Careless","Responsible","Lazy","Unkind"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Maya worries about losing the school''s book, searches until she finds it, and returns it carefully, which shows she is responsible.","points":1},{"id":"Q6","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What is the lesson Maya learns in the story?","diagram":null,"options":["Library books are not very important.","You should never borrow books from school.","Not giving up and being careful can solve a problem.","It is best to read only at the kitchen table."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Maya does not give up, finds the book, and afterward keeps her books in one safe spot. This shows that not giving up and being careful can solve a problem.","points":1},{"id":"Q7","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Which detail from the text best shows that Maya was careful with the book after she found it?","diagram":null,"options":["\"Her cheeks turned warm.\"","\"She had read it in the car.\"","\"Maya carried the book to school as carefully as if it were made of glass.\"","\"All afternoon Maya thought about where the book could be.\""],"answer":2,"explanation":"Carrying the book \"as carefully as if it were made of glass\" directly shows how careful Maya was with it.","points":1},{"id":"Q8","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Select the two places Maya searched before she found the book.","diagram":null,"options":["Mr. Patel''s office","The back seat of the car","Under the kitchen table","The school playground"],"answer":[1,2],"explanation":"Part 2 says Maya looked under the kitchen table and searched the back seat of the car before remembering the flashlight and finding the book in her bed.","points":1},{"id":"Q9","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P2","questionText":"According to Part 1, why is Bram searching the meadow?","diagram":null,"options":["He is looking for a fence post.","He is looking for the crow.","He is looking for water.","He is looking for his cousin."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 1 says the thirsty rabbit Bram was searching for water because the sun had dried up every puddle.","points":1},{"id":"Q10","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What does the word \"discouraged\" mean as it is used in Part 1?","diagram":null,"options":["Feeling proud and happy","Wanting to run away quickly","Having lost hope after failing","Feeling thirsty and hot"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Bram sits down \"tired and discouraged\" after his tries to reach the water fail, so discouraged means having lost hope after failing.","points":1},{"id":"Q11","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What does Bram do to make the water rise to the top of the jug?","diagram":null,"options":["He drops pebbles into the jug one by one.","He waits for rain to fill the jug.","He drinks the water with a long straw.","He tips the jug over on its side."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Part 2 says Bram dropped pebbles into the jug one by one until the water crept up to the very top.","points":1},{"id":"Q12","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What does Bram try first, before he uses the pebbles?","diagram":null,"options":["He pushes his nose into the jug and tries to tip it.","He goes home to rest.","He drinks from a nearby puddle.","He flies up to the fence post."],"answer":0,"explanation":"In Part 1, Bram first pushes his nose into the jug and tries to tip it and knock it over, all before learning the pebble trick.","points":1},{"id":"Q13","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What is the lesson of this story?","diagram":null,"options":["It is dangerous to be thirsty in a meadow.","Crows are smarter than rabbits.","A hard problem can be solved a small piece at a time.","You should never drink from a jug."],"answer":2,"explanation":"The crow tells Bram that a hard problem can be solved a small piece at a time, which is the story''s lesson, shown by the pebbles.","points":1},{"id":"Q14","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What is one way the crow helps Bram?","diagram":null,"options":["The crow tips the heavy jug over for him.","The crow drops the pebbles into the jug for him.","The crow brings Bram water from another field.","The crow gives Bram a clue to look at the ground."],"answer":3,"explanation":"The crow tells Bram to watch the ground, not the jug, which is the clue that leads Bram to the pebbles. The crow says Bram did the work himself.","points":1},{"id":"Q15","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.9","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Use both parts of this text to answer this question. How does Bram change from the beginning to the end of the story?","diagram":null,"options":["He goes from friendly to angry.","He goes from thirsty and discouraged to satisfied and wiser.","He goes from helpful to selfish.","He goes from fast to slow."],"answer":1,"explanation":"At the start Bram is thirsty and discouraged, but by the end he has drunk his fill and learned a lesson, so he is satisfied and wiser.","points":1},{"id":"Q16","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What does the phrase \"the sun had baked the ground hard\" help the reader understand?","diagram":null,"options":["The ground was covered with bread.","The weather had been very hot and dry.","Someone was cooking food on the ground.","A fire had burned the meadow."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Saying the sun \"baked the ground hard\" is a way of showing the weather had been very hot and dry, which is why the puddles vanished.","points":1},{"id":"Q17","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P3","questionText":"According to Part 1, what sweet liquid do honeybees drink from flowers?","diagram":null,"options":["Water","Nectar","Wax","Honey"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 1 states that a honeybee drinks a sweet liquid called nectar from flower to flower.","points":1},{"id":"Q18","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What do the worker bees do right after the flying bee brings nectar back to the hive?","diagram":null,"options":["They fly out to find more flowers.","They seal the cells with wax.","They beat their wings to dry it out.","They take the nectar and chew it for a while."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Part 1 says the flying bee passes the nectar to other worker bees, who chew it for a while to begin changing it.","points":1},{"id":"Q19","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"cells\" as it is used in the text?","diagram":null,"options":["Sweet liquid from flowers","Tiny pouches inside a bee''s body","Fans that blow air","Small wax rooms where nectar is stored"],"answer":3,"explanation":"The text says the bees spread the nectar into small wax rooms called cells, so cells are small wax rooms.","points":1},{"id":"Q20","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"How do the bees turn the watery nectar into thick honey?","diagram":null,"options":["They add more water to it.","They beat their wings to blow air and dry it out.","They carry it back to the flowers.","They seal it in wax right away."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 2 explains the bees beat their wings like fans to blow air across the cells, drying out the extra water until the nectar becomes thick honey.","points":1},{"id":"Q21","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"How does the author connect the ideas in Part 1 and Part 2 of the text?","diagram":null,"options":["By describing the steps that turn nectar into honey, in order","By comparing two different kinds of bees","By telling a story about one beekeeper","By listing reasons people should fear bees"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Part 1 explains how bees gather and chew nectar, and Part 2 continues with drying and sealing it, giving the steps that make honey in order.","points":1},{"id":"Q22","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"According to the text, why do bees make far more honey than they need?","diagram":null,"options":["So they can build more cells","So the flowers will grow back","So beekeepers can sell it","So they will have food during the cold winter"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Part 2 says bees make extra honey so they will have plenty of food during the cold winter when no flowers bloom.","points":1},{"id":"Q23","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.2","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the main idea of the text?","diagram":null,"options":["Beekeepers take all of the honey from a hive.","Flowers cannot grow without bees.","Honeybees make honey through a series of steps that begin at a flower.","Honey tastes good on toast."],"answer":2,"explanation":"The whole text explains how honeybees make honey step by step, starting with nectar from a flower.","points":1},{"id":"Q24","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"Which statement from the text best supports the idea that beekeepers are careful not to harm the bees?","diagram":null,"options":["\"The honey can be stored this way for a long time.\"","\"It is made by honeybees, and the process begins far away in a field of flowers.\"","\"They beat their wings fast, like tiny fans...\"","\"Beekeepers gently take only the extra honey, leaving enough for the bees.\""],"answer":3,"explanation":"The line about beekeepers gently taking only the extra honey and leaving enough for the bees supports the idea that they are careful not to harm the bees.","points":1},{"id":"Q25","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P4","questionText":"According to Part 1, what did Wilma Rudolph have to wear for years as a child?","diagram":null,"options":["A gold medal","A heavy leg brace","A pair of running shoes","A team uniform"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 1 says Wilma wore a heavy brace for years and could not walk without help after her illness.","points":1},{"id":"Q26","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"What helped Wilma''s weak leg grow stronger?","diagram":null,"options":["Her family took turns rubbing her leg every day.","She rested in bed for years.","She wore the brace all the time.","A doctor gave her medicine."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Part 1 says her mother, brothers, and sisters took turns rubbing her weak leg every day to help it grow stronger.","points":1},{"id":"Q27","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"What does the word \"determined\" mean as it is used in Part 1?","diagram":null,"options":["Sick and weak","Set on reaching a goal and not giving up","Quiet and shy","Tired and sleepy"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Wilma practiced a little more each day until she could walk and run, so determined means being set on a goal and not giving up.","points":1},{"id":"Q28","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"What happened right after Wilma joined her school track team?","diagram":null,"options":["She traveled to Italy.","She grew very sick again.","She put her brace back on.","She soon began winning race after race."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Part 2 says once Wilma joined the track team, she soon was winning race after race.","points":1},{"id":"Q29","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"What is the main idea of the text?","diagram":null,"options":["Through hard work and courage, Wilma overcame illness to become a champion runner.","Track teams help children make new friends.","The Olympic Games take place in many countries.","Wilma Rudolph was born in Tennessee in 1940."],"answer":0,"explanation":"The text as a whole shows how Wilma overcame a serious illness through hard work and courage to win three gold medals, which is its main idea.","points":1},{"id":"Q30","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"How does the author connect the ideas in Part 1 and Part 2 of the text?","diagram":null,"options":["By describing the same race two times","By comparing two different runners","By showing how Wilma went from being unable to walk to becoming a champion","By listing rules of the Olympic Games"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 1 tells how Wilma could not walk, and Part 2 shows how she learned to run and won gold, connecting the two parts as a cause-and-effect change over time.","points":1},{"id":"Q31","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"Select the two facts the text gives about Wilma Rudolph''s Olympic success.","diagram":null,"options":["She won three gold medals.","She refused to wear running shoes.","She set a world record that still stands.","She raced in Rome, Italy, in 1960."],"answer":[0,3],"explanation":"The text states that Wilma raced in Rome, Italy, in 1960 and won three gold medals. The other choices are not in the text.","points":1},{"id":"Q32","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"Which word best describes Wilma Rudolph, based on the text?","diagram":null,"options":["Courageous","Fearful","Careless","Forgetful"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Wilma kept working through a hard illness and never gave up, which shows she was courageous.","points":1},{"id":"Q33","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P5","questionText":"According to Part 1, what has just happened at the start of the poem?","diagram":null,"options":["The rain has stopped and the clouds have cleared.","The sun has set for the night.","A storm is about to begin.","Snow has begun to fall."],"answer":0,"explanation":"The poem opens with \"The rain has gone, the clouds have cleared,\" showing the rain has just stopped.","points":1},{"id":"Q34","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"What does the poet mean by the phrase \"a tiny string of silver dream\" in Part 1?","diagram":null,"options":["Someone is dreaming about silver coins.","The spider has fallen asleep on the web.","The raindrops on the web shine and gleam like something magical.","A real string made of silver hangs on the gate."],"answer":2,"explanation":"The phrase describes the raindrops on the spider''s web catching the sun and gleaming, comparing them to a beautiful, dreamlike string of silver.","points":1},{"id":"Q35","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P5","questionText":"In Part 2, what does the poet mean when the flowers \"lift their drooping heads\"?","diagram":null,"options":["The flowers are falling to the ground.","The flowers are perking up after the rain.","The flowers are closing for the night.","The flowers are being picked."],"answer":1,"explanation":"After the rain, the flowers lift their drooping heads and stretch awake, which means they are perking up and reviving.","points":1},{"id":"Q36","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.5","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P5","questionText":"What does the robin do in Part 2 of the poem?","diagram":null,"options":["It builds a nest in the apple tree.","It hops across the lawn and pulls a worm from the ground.","It sings a song to wake the flowers.","It drinks raindrops from the spider''s web."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 2 says the robin hops across the lawn and pulls a worm up from the ground.","points":1},{"id":"Q37","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"What is the main message of the poem?","diagram":null,"options":["Rain helps the garden grow, and brightness returns after every cloudy day.","Rain is something to be afraid of.","Spiders make the best webs after a storm.","Robins are the most important garden animals."],"answer":0,"explanation":"The poem shows how the rain washes and wakens the garden, ending with the idea that the sun returns after every cloudy day, which is its main message.","points":1},{"id":"Q38","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"What does the line \"The whole world drank its morning cup\" help the reader picture?","diagram":null,"options":["The garden soaking up the rainwater to wake up fresh","A cup of water spilling on the flowers","People drinking tea in the garden","The robin drinking from a cup"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The line compares the rain-soaked garden to someone drinking a morning cup, picturing the garden taking in water and waking up fresh.","points":1},{"id":"Q39","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.5","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P5","questionText":"How is the poem mainly organized?","diagram":null,"options":["By describing the garden as it comes alive after the rain","By telling about the four seasons of the year","By comparing two different gardens","By giving steps for planting a garden"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The poem moves through the garden after the rain, describing the leaves, web, robin, and flowers as the garden wakens up.","points":1},{"id":"Q40","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"Both \"The Crow and the Pitcher''s Cousin\" and \"The Garden After Rain\" share which idea?","diagram":null,"options":["A person learns to run very fast.","A clever animal tricks another animal.","A long journey ends at someone''s table.","Water brings a good change to a dry or sleeping world."],"answer":3,"explanation":"In the fable, water saves the thirsty rabbit, and in the poem, rain wakens and refreshes the garden. Both show water bringing a good change. The other choices fit only one text or neither.","points":1}]}');
INSERT INTO "tests" ("id","grade","subject","test_type","title","time_limit_minutes","question_count","source","created_at","data") VALUES('g3-read-eog-6',3,'reading','eog','Grade 3 Reading — EOG Practice Test 6',120,40,'curated','2026-06-02T00:00:00.000Z','{"id":"g3-read-eog-6","grade":3,"subject":"reading","testType":"eog","title":"Grade 3 Reading — EOG Practice Test 6","instructions":"Read each selection carefully. Then answer the questions. Choose the one best answer for each question unless you are told to select more than one.","timeLimitMinutes":120,"calculatorAllowed":false,"source":"curated","passages":[{"id":"P1","title":"The Kindness Rocks","genre":"fiction","lexile":"570L","text":"Part 1\n\nMaya found the smooth gray rock half buried in the sand at the edge of the lake. Someone had painted a tiny yellow sun on it, and under the sun were two words: BE BRAVE. Maya turned the rock over and over in her hands. She did not know who had left it, but it made her smile on a morning when she had felt anything but brave.\n\nThat afternoon, Maya carried the rock home in her pocket. Her family had just moved to a new town, and tomorrow she would start at a new school where she knew no one. All week her stomach had felt like a jar full of buzzing bees. But every time she touched the little painted sun, the buzzing grew a bit quieter.\n\nThe next morning, Maya stood at the door of room 12. Her heart pounded. Then she slipped her hand into her pocket and felt the smooth rock there. BE BRAVE, it reminded her. She took a deep breath and walked inside.\n\nPart 2\n\nAfter school, Maya had an idea. If one painted rock could help her feel brave, maybe she could help someone else feel brave too. She gathered a basket of smooth stones from the yard, found her mother''s paints, and got to work.\n\nFor a week, Maya painted. She made rocks with rainbows, stars, hearts, and tiny suns. On each one she wrote a few kind words: YOU MATTER. KEEP GOING. YOU ARE NOT ALONE. Then she began leaving them in quiet places around town—on a park bench, beside the library steps, near the door of room 12.\n\nMaya never signed her name, and she never told anyone it was her. But on the playground she noticed a boy holding a rock painted with a star, grinning as if he had found treasure. A girl tucked a heart rock carefully into her backpack. Maya hugged her own rock and felt warm all the way through. She had learned that the kindness someone had given her was a gift she could pass along, one painted stone at a time."},{"id":"P2","title":"How Roadrunner Won the Race","genre":"fiction","lexile":"600L","text":"Part 1\n\nLong ago, when the desert was young and the animals could still boast and brag, Rabbit believed he was the fastest creature in all the land. \"No one can beat me,\" he announced from the top of a tall red rock. \"My legs are like springs, and my feet barely touch the ground!\"\n\nThe other animals were tired of Rabbit''s bragging. Quiet little Roadrunner, who spent her days darting between the cactus plants, stepped forward. \"I will race you,\" she said softly. Rabbit laughed so hard he nearly fell off his rock. \"You? Race me? This will be the easiest win of my life!\"\n\nThe animals marked a path from the dry riverbed to the old twisted juniper tree and back. \"Tomorrow at sunrise,\" said wise old Tortoise, who would be the judge.\n\nPart 2\n\nAt sunrise the next morning, every animal in the desert gathered to watch. Tortoise raised his foot and the race began. Rabbit shot ahead in a cloud of dust, so far in front that he could no longer even see Roadrunner behind him.\n\n\"This is too easy,\" Rabbit chuckled. \"I will rest in the shade and still win.\" He curled up beneath a cool mesquite tree and closed his eyes, certain he had plenty of time. But Roadrunner did not run in great leaps that wore her out. Instead, she ran with a steady patter, her feet whispering across the sand, never once stopping to rest.\n\nWhile Rabbit dozed, Roadrunner passed him quietly. By the time Rabbit yawned and stretched and remembered the race, Roadrunner was already crossing the finish line. The animals cheered until the canyon rang. From that day on, Rabbit did far less bragging, and Roadrunner became known across the desert not as the loudest, but as the one who kept going. And to this very day, you can still see Roadrunner racing across the sand, steady and quick, with no need to boast at all."},{"id":"P3","title":"From Egg to Frog","genre":"informational","lexile":"630L","text":"Part 1\n\nA frog does not begin its life looking like a frog at all. It begins as a tiny egg floating in a pond. A mother frog may lay hundreds of eggs at once, joined together in a soft, jellylike cluster. The clear jelly protects the eggs and keeps them from drying out while the young frogs grow inside.\n\nAfter about a week, the eggs hatch. But the creatures that wriggle out are not frogs—they are tadpoles. A tadpole looks more like a tiny fish. It has a long tail for swimming and gills on the sides of its body that let it breathe underwater. At this stage, a tadpole eats plants that grow in the pond.\n\nPart 2\n\nOver the next several weeks, the tadpole begins to change in an amazing way. First, two tiny back legs push out near its tail. A little later, two front legs appear. Slowly, the tadpole''s tail grows shorter and shorter as its body uses up the tail for energy.\n\nInside its body, even bigger changes are happening. The tadpole grows lungs to replace its gills, so that it can breathe air instead of water. Now the young frog can leave the pond and hop onto land for the first time. This whole change from one body shape into a very different one is called metamorphosis.\n\nThe grown frog will spend much of its life on land, catching insects with its long, sticky tongue. But when it is time to lay eggs of its own, the frog will return to the water where its life began. And there, in the quiet pond, the amazing journey from egg to frog will start all over again."},{"id":"P4","title":"Bessie Coleman: Reaching for the Sky","genre":"informational","lexile":"640L","text":"Part 1\n\nBessie Coleman was born in Texas in 1892, the tenth of thirteen children. Her family worked hard picking cotton, and there was little time or money for big dreams. But Bessie loved to read and learn, and she was determined to make something of her life. When she grew up, she moved to the city of Chicago, where she worked and listened to the stories of pilots returning from far away.\n\nBessie made up her mind: she would learn to fly an airplane. In those days, however, flight schools in the United States would not accept her because she was a woman and because she was Black. Most people would have given up. Bessie did something bold instead.\n\nPart 2\n\nBessie learned that flight schools in France would teach her, so she studied the French language at night after work. Then she sailed all the way across the ocean to France to chase her dream. There, in 1921, Bessie Coleman earned her pilot''s license. She became the first Black woman in the world to do so.\n\nWhen Bessie returned home, crowds gathered to watch her fly. She performed in air shows, looping and rolling her plane high above the cheering crowds. People called her \"Brave Bessie,\" and she became famous across the country.\n\nBut Bessie wanted to do more than thrill a crowd. She dreamed of opening a flying school so that other young Black students could learn to fly, just as she had longed to. She gave speeches and refused to perform anywhere that would not allow Black and white people to watch together. Bessie Coleman did not live to open her school, but her courage opened the skies for those who came after her, proving that a determined dream is stronger than any wall in its way."},{"id":"P5","title":"The Little Brook","genre":"poetry","lexile":"NP","text":"Part 1\n\nHigh on the hill where the cold springs start,\nA little brook begins its part.\nIt tumbles and trickles down mossy stone,\nSinging a song all its very own.\n\nIt does not hurry, it does not rest,\nIt simply does what it does best:\nIt slips past the roots of the old oak tree,\nAnd carries a leaf like a boat to sea.\n\nPart 2\n\nThe brook grows wider as it goes,\nGathering rain and melting snows.\nThe deer bend low to take a drink,\nThe minnows dart along its brink.\n\nIt turns the wheel of the mill in town,\nIt waters the fields of golden brown.\nThen on it rolls, both night and day,\nUntil it meets a river''s way.\n\nSo here is a lesson the small brook knows:\nKeep moving gently wherever it goes.\nA little water, steady and true,\nCan shape a valley before it is through."}],"questions":[{"id":"Q1","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P1","questionText":"According to Part 1, where does Maya find the painted rock?","diagram":null,"options":["On a park bench","Near the door of room 12","Half buried in the sand at the edge of the lake","Beside the library steps"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 1 says Maya found the smooth gray rock half buried in the sand at the edge of the lake.","points":1},{"id":"Q2","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What does the phrase \"her stomach had felt like a jar full of buzzing bees\" help the reader understand in Part 1?","diagram":null,"options":["Maya kept bees as pets.","Maya was hungry for breakfast.","Maya was excited about the lake.","Maya was feeling very nervous."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Comparing her stomach to a jar of buzzing bees shows that Maya felt nervous and uneasy about her new school.","points":1},{"id":"Q3","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Why was Maya nervous about the next morning?","diagram":null,"options":["She was going to give a speech.","She was starting at a new school where she knew no one.","She had to swim across the lake.","She had lost her painted rock."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 1 explains that Maya''s family had just moved and she would start at a new school the next day where she knew no one.","points":1},{"id":"Q4","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What does Maya do right after she has the idea to help someone else feel brave?","diagram":null,"options":["She walks into room 12.","She signs her name on a rock.","She gathers smooth stones and paints them.","She tells her mother her secret."],"answer":2,"explanation":"In Part 2, after getting the idea, Maya gathers a basket of smooth stones, finds her mother''s paints, and gets to work.","points":1},{"id":"Q5","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Use both parts of this text to answer this question. What is the main message of the story?","diagram":null,"options":["It is best to keep your good deeds a secret forever.","Kindness you receive can be passed along to help others.","Moving to a new town is always frightening.","Painting rocks is a good way to earn money."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Maya receives a kind painted rock that helps her, and then she passes that kindness along by making rocks for others, showing that kindness can be passed along.","points":1},{"id":"Q6","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Which word best describes Maya in the story?","diagram":null,"options":["Thoughtful","Lazy","Careless","Greedy"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Maya thinks about how the rock helped her and chooses to make rocks to help others, which shows she is thoughtful.","points":1},{"id":"Q7","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Which detail from the text best shows that Maya''s painted rocks made other people happy?","diagram":null,"options":["\"Her family had just moved to a new town.\"","\"...a boy holding a rock painted with a star, grinning as if he had found treasure.\"","\"All week her stomach had felt like a jar full of buzzing bees.\"","\"She did not know who had left it.\""],"answer":1,"explanation":"The boy grinning as if he had found treasure while holding one of the rocks shows that the rocks made others happy.","points":1},{"id":"Q8","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Select the two kind messages Maya writes on the rocks she makes in Part 2.","diagram":null,"options":["YOU MATTER","FOLLOW ME","BE BRAVE","KEEP GOING"],"answer":[0,3],"explanation":"In Part 2, Maya writes messages such as YOU MATTER, KEEP GOING, and YOU ARE NOT ALONE on her rocks. BE BRAVE was on the rock she found, not one she made.","points":1},{"id":"Q9","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P2","questionText":"According to Part 1, what does Rabbit believe about himself?","diagram":null,"options":["That he cannot run very far","That he is too tired to race","That he is the fastest creature in all the land","That he is the wisest animal in the desert"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 1 says Rabbit believed he was the fastest creature in all the land and that no one could beat him.","points":1},{"id":"Q10","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Why does Rabbit decide to rest under the mesquite tree during the race?","diagram":null,"options":["Roadrunner asks him to wait for her.","He is so far ahead that he thinks he has plenty of time to win.","He has hurt his foot.","Tortoise tells him to take a break."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Rabbit is so far ahead that he thinks the race is too easy and that he can rest in the shade and still win.","points":1},{"id":"Q11","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What does the phrase \"her feet whispering across the sand\" help the reader understand about Roadrunner in Part 2?","diagram":null,"options":["Roadrunner moved quietly and steadily.","Roadrunner was too tired to run.","Roadrunner was talking to the sand.","Roadrunner was afraid of the noise."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Saying her feet were \"whispering across the sand\" shows that Roadrunner ran quietly and steadily, without loud, tiring leaps.","points":1},{"id":"Q12","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What is the lesson of the story?","diagram":null,"options":["Bragging and resting can cause you to lose; steady effort wins.","Desert animals should not race one another.","It is best to run as fast as you can at the start.","Rabbits are always faster than roadrunners."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Rabbit brags and stops to rest and loses, while steady Roadrunner keeps going and wins, teaching that steady effort beats bragging.","points":1},{"id":"Q13","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"boast\" as it is used in this story?","diagram":null,"options":["To brag about yourself","To run very fast","To fall asleep","To feel afraid"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The story shows Rabbit announcing how fast he is and laughing at Roadrunner, so to \"boast\" means to brag about yourself.","points":1},{"id":"Q14","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Which word best describes Roadrunner in the story?","diagram":null,"options":["Unkind","Determined","Boastful","Fearful"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Roadrunner quietly accepts the challenge and never stops running until she wins, which shows she is determined.","points":1},{"id":"Q15","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.5","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"How does the author organize the events in Part 2 of the story?","diagram":null,"options":["By comparing the desert to the forest","By telling what happens in order, from the start of the race to the finish","By explaining why deserts are hot","By giving directions for running a race"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 2 tells the events of the race in order: the start, Rabbit racing ahead and resting, Roadrunner passing him, and crossing the finish line.","points":1},{"id":"Q16","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Who is chosen to be the judge of the race?","diagram":null,"options":["Roadrunner","The desert deer","Wise old Tortoise","Rabbit"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 1 states that wise old Tortoise would be the judge of the race.","points":1},{"id":"Q17","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P3","questionText":"According to Part 1, how does a frog''s life begin?","diagram":null,"options":["As a fish in the ocean","As a fully grown frog on land","As an insect in the grass","As a tiny egg floating in a pond"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Part 1 says a frog begins its life as a tiny egg floating in a pond.","points":1},{"id":"Q18","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What does a tadpole use to breathe underwater?","diagram":null,"options":["Its long tail","Its lungs","Its sticky tongue","Gills on the sides of its body"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Part 1 explains that a tadpole has gills on the sides of its body that let it breathe underwater.","points":1},{"id":"Q19","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"According to Part 2, which legs appear first as the tadpole changes?","diagram":null,"options":["The two front legs","All four legs at the same time","The tadpole never grows legs","The two back legs"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Part 2 says first two tiny back legs push out near its tail, and a little later the two front legs appear.","points":1},{"id":"Q20","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.4","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"metamorphosis\" as it is used in Part 2?","diagram":null,"options":["A long, sticky tongue","A change from one body shape into a very different one","A kind of pond plant","A cluster of frog eggs"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The text says the whole change from one body shape into a very different one is called metamorphosis.","points":1},{"id":"Q21","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"How does the author connect the ideas in Part 1 and Part 2 of the text?","diagram":null,"options":["By telling a made-up story about one frog","By listing reasons frogs are helpful to people","By describing the stages of a frog''s life in the order they happen","By comparing frogs with fish that live in the ocean"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 1 describes the egg and tadpole stages and Part 2 continues with the changes into a frog, presenting the stages of a frog''s life in order.","points":1},{"id":"Q22","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the connection between the tadpole growing lungs and the young frog being able to leave the pond?","diagram":null,"options":["Growing lungs lets the frog breathe air, so it can move onto land.","Growing lungs has nothing to do with leaving the pond.","Growing lungs makes the frog''s tail grow longer.","Growing lungs causes the frog to lay eggs."],"answer":0,"explanation":"The text shows cause and effect: the tadpole grows lungs to replace its gills so it can breathe air, which allows the young frog to leave the pond and hop onto land.","points":1},{"id":"Q23","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.2","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the main idea of the text?","diagram":null,"options":["Tadpoles look just like tiny fish.","Ponds are full of jellylike eggs.","Frogs eat insects with sticky tongues.","A frog changes through several stages as it grows from an egg into an adult."],"answer":3,"explanation":"The whole text explains how a frog grows and changes through stages, from egg to tadpole to adult frog.","points":1},{"id":"Q24","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"Select the two changes that happen to a tadpole as it becomes a frog.","diagram":null,"options":["Its body turns into an egg.","Its tail grows shorter.","It grows gills to breathe underwater.","It grows lungs to breathe air."],"answer":[1,3],"explanation":"Part 2 explains that the tadpole''s tail grows shorter and that it grows lungs to breathe air. It loses its gills rather than growing them, and it does not turn back into an egg.","points":1},{"id":"Q25","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P4","questionText":"According to Part 1, where was Bessie Coleman born?","diagram":null,"options":["In Texas","In an air show","In France","In Chicago"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Part 1 states that Bessie Coleman was born in Texas in 1892.","points":1},{"id":"Q26","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"Why did Bessie travel all the way to France?","diagram":null,"options":["To pick cotton with her family","To watch other pilots in air shows","To open a flying school for students","To learn to fly, because flight schools in the United States would not accept her"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Flight schools in the United States would not accept Bessie because she was a woman and Black, so she went to France, where a school would teach her.","points":1},{"id":"Q27","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"determined\" as it is used in Part 1?","diagram":null,"options":["Funny and playful","Worried and afraid","Set on doing something and not giving up","Tired and bored"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The text shows Bessie working hard to reach her goal, so \"determined\" means set on doing something and not giving up.","points":1},{"id":"Q28","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"What did Bessie do at night to prepare to go to France?","diagram":null,"options":["She performed in air shows.","She built her own airplane.","She gave speeches to crowds.","She studied the French language."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Part 2 says Bessie studied the French language at night after work so she could attend a flight school in France.","points":1},{"id":"Q29","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"How does the author connect the ideas in Part 1 about Bessie''s problem with the ideas in Part 2?","diagram":null,"options":["By listing the cities where Bessie performed","By presenting Bessie''s problem and then how she solved it","By comparing two different airplanes","By giving steps for flying a plane in order"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 1 presents the problem that U.S. flight schools would not accept Bessie, and Part 2 shows the solution: she learned French and went to France to earn her license.","points":1},{"id":"Q30","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"What is the main idea of the text?","diagram":null,"options":["Bessie Coleman had twelve brothers and sisters.","Air shows were popular long ago.","France was the only place to learn to fly.","Bessie Coleman overcame unfair barriers to become a pilot and inspire others."],"answer":3,"explanation":"The text as a whole shows how Bessie pushed past unfair barriers to become a pilot and how she wanted to help others fly, which is its main idea.","points":1},{"id":"Q31","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"Which statement from the text best supports the idea that Bessie wanted to help other people, not just herself?","diagram":null,"options":["\"She performed in air shows, looping and rolling her plane high above the cheering crowds.\"","\"She dreamed of opening a flying school so that other young Black students could learn to fly.\"","\"There, in 1921, Bessie Coleman earned her pilot''s license.\"","\"Bessie Coleman was born in Texas in 1892, the tenth of thirteen children.\""],"answer":1,"explanation":"Her dream of opening a flying school so other young Black students could learn to fly shows she wanted to help others, not just herself.","points":1},{"id":"Q32","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"Which word best describes Bessie Coleman, based on the text?","diagram":null,"options":["Selfish","Forgetful","Brave","Fearful"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Bessie crossed an ocean, refused to give up, and performed daring flights, and people even called her \"Brave Bessie,\" which shows she was brave.","points":1},{"id":"Q33","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P5","questionText":"According to Part 1, where does the little brook begin?","diagram":null,"options":["In a town near a mill","High on the hill where the cold springs start","At a river''s edge","In the fields of golden brown"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 1 says the little brook begins high on the hill where the cold springs start.","points":1},{"id":"Q34","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"What does the poet mean by the line \"And carries a leaf like a boat to sea\" in Part 1?","diagram":null,"options":["A floating leaf is carried along the moving water like a little boat.","Sailors row their boats down the brook.","The brook turns into a real boat.","The leaf sinks to the bottom of the brook."],"answer":0,"explanation":"The line compares a leaf floating on the moving water to a little boat being carried along, helping the reader picture the leaf drifting on the brook.","points":1},{"id":"Q35","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.5","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P5","questionText":"How is the poem mainly organized?","diagram":null,"options":["By following the brook''s journey from the hilltop to the river","By describing a single rainy day","By giving steps for building a mill","By comparing two different brooks"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The poem follows the brook from where it starts on the hill, growing wider as it travels, until it meets a river''s way.","points":1},{"id":"Q36","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"What is the main message, or theme, of the poem?","diagram":null,"options":["Water always moves too quickly to enjoy.","Mills are the most important buildings in a town.","Steady, gentle effort over time can make a big difference.","Brooks are dangerous and should be avoided."],"answer":2,"explanation":"The final stanza says a little water, steady and true, can shape a valley, teaching that steady, gentle effort over time makes a big difference.","points":1},{"id":"Q37","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P5","questionText":"According to Part 2, what useful work does the brook do in the town?","diagram":null,"options":["It paves the roads.","It puts out fires.","It turns the wheel of the mill.","It carries boats full of people."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 2 says the brook turns the wheel of the mill in town and waters the fields.","points":1},{"id":"Q38","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P5","questionText":"In Part 1, the poet writes that the brook is \"Singing a song all its very own.\" What does this line help the reader imagine?","diagram":null,"options":["The bubbling, trickling sound the water makes as it moves","Birds calling from the old oak tree","The silence of a frozen brook","A person standing beside the brook and singing"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Describing the brook as singing a song helps the reader imagine the bubbling, trickling sound the moving water makes.","points":1},{"id":"Q39","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.9","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"Both \"How Roadrunner Won the Race\" and \"The Little Brook\" share which idea?","diagram":null,"options":["Steady, gentle effort over time leads to success.","Deserts and brooks are dangerous places.","A clever trick is the best way to win.","Bragging helps you reach your goals."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Roadrunner wins by moving steadily without stopping, and the brook shapes a valley by moving steadily over time; both share the idea that steady, gentle effort leads to success.","points":1},{"id":"Q40","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.9","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"Both \"Bessie Coleman: Reaching for the Sky\" and \"From Egg to Frog\" describe a kind of change. How are the two changes different?","diagram":null,"options":["Both changes happen by accident with no effort.","Both changes are choices the subjects make on purpose.","A frog''s change is a choice, while Bessie''s just happened on its own.","Bessie''s change was a choice she worked toward, while a frog''s change happens naturally as it grows."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Bessie chose her goal and worked hard to become a pilot, while a frog''s change from egg to adult happens naturally as part of growing up, so the two kinds of change are different.","points":1}]}');
INSERT INTO "tests" ("id","grade","subject","test_type","title","time_limit_minutes","question_count","source","created_at","data") VALUES('g3-read-moy-1',3,'reading','moy','Grade 3 Reading — Middle of Year (MOY) Test 1',90,24,'curated','2026-06-02T00:00:00.000Z','{"id":"g3-read-moy-1","grade":3,"subject":"reading","testType":"moy","title":"Grade 3 Reading — Middle of Year (MOY) Test 1","instructions":"Read each selection carefully. Then answer the questions that follow. Some questions ask you to use both parts of the text. For each question, choose the best answer or answers based on what the selection states or suggests. You have 90 minutes.","timeLimitMinutes":90,"calculatorAllowed":false,"source":"curated","passages":[{"id":"P1","title":"The Quilt That Talked","genre":"fiction","lexile":"560L","text":"Part 1\n\nGrandma Pearl kept an old quilt folded at the foot of her bed. To Mia, it looked plain, just rows of faded cloth squares stitched together. \"Why do you keep this raggedy thing?\" Mia asked one rainy afternoon.\n\nGrandma Pearl smiled and spread the quilt across her lap. \"This quilt talks,\" she said. \"You only have to learn how to listen.\" Mia frowned, because quilts cannot talk. But she sat down beside her grandmother anyway.\n\nGrandma Pearl pointed to a blue square. \"This piece came from your grandfather''s work shirt. He wore it every day at the railroad.\" Then she touched a square covered in tiny yellow flowers. \"This was my Sunday dress when I was a girl your age. I wore it the day I learned to read.\"\n\nSquare by square, the quilt told its stories. A green patch was once a tablecloth from a family supper. A soft white square had been a baby blanket — Mia''s own, when she was small. Mia ran her fingers over the white cloth. It did not feel raggedy anymore. It felt warm, as if it remembered being wrapped around her.\n\nPart 2\n\n\"Now you try,\" Grandma Pearl said. \"Find a square and tell me what it says.\"\n\nMia looked closely. She chose a red square with a small tear near one corner. \"I don''t know this one,\" she admitted.\n\n\"That,\" said Grandma Pearl, \"is the most important square of all. It came from the apron I was wearing the day your mother was born. The tear is from when I caught it on the hospital door, running too fast to meet her.\"\n\nMia laughed and pressed the red square to her cheek. Suddenly the quilt did not look plain. Every square was a window into a day that had already happened, kept safe in thread.\n\nThat night, Grandma Pearl tucked the quilt around Mia''s shoulders. \"Listen,\" she whispered. And though the room was quiet, Mia was sure she could hear the squares humming the old, soft stories — railroad mornings, Sunday lessons, and the squeak of a hospital door swinging open. She fell asleep before the quilt was finished talking."},{"id":"P2","title":"How Honeybees Talk With a Dance","genre":"informational","lexile":"590L","text":"Part 1\n\nHoneybees cannot speak the way people do, yet they share important news every day. When a bee finds a patch of flowers full of sweet nectar, it must tell the other bees in the hive where to go. To do this, the bee does a special dance.\n\nThe most famous dance is called the waggle dance. The bee runs forward in a straight line while shaking, or waggling, its body from side to side. Then it loops back and runs the line again, tracing a path shaped like the number eight. This dance may look like wiggling, but it is really a set of directions.\n\nThe direction of the waggle run tells the other bees which way to fly. If the bee waggles straight up, the flowers are toward the sun. If it waggles to the left, the food is to the left of the sun. In this way, one small bee can point the whole hive in the right direction.\n\nPart 2\n\nThe dance also tells the bees how far to travel. A longer waggle run means the flowers are far away. A shorter run means they are close to the hive. Bees that watch the dance can learn both the direction and the distance without ever leaving home.\n\nWhy does this matter? A hive may hold thousands of bees. If every bee had to search alone, they would waste time and energy flying in circles. Because of the waggle dance, the bees can work together. One scout finds the food, returns to the hive, and shares the news. Soon many bees fly straight to the flowers and bring back nectar to make honey.\n\nScientists once thought the dancing was just an accident. Then they marked single bees with tiny dots of paint and followed them. They proved that bees who watched the dance flew to the exact spot the dancer described. The honeybee''s dance is one of the clearest examples of animals sharing directions, and it helps the whole hive survive."},{"id":"P3","title":"The Pony Express: Mail by Horse","genre":"informational","lexile":"610L","text":"Part 1\n\nLong before phones or email, getting a letter across the United States was slow and hard. In 1860, a message sent from Missouri to California could take weeks to arrive by wagon or boat. Some people felt this was far too slow for a growing country. They wanted a faster way to carry the mail across the wide land in the West.\n\nThree businessmen had an idea. They would use fast horses and brave riders to carry the mail in a relay, passing it from one rider to the next. They called their plan the Pony Express. The riders would race day and night across nearly two thousand miles, through deserts, mountains, and rivers.\n\nThe Pony Express built small stations along the trail. At each station, a tired horse was swapped for a fresh one in about two minutes. A rider would gallop fifty miles or more before handing the mail to the next rider, who carried it on. Because the horses were always fresh, the mail almost never stopped moving.\n\nPart 2\n\nThe riders faced great danger. They rode through blazing heat and freezing snow. Storms could hide the trail, and the work was lonely. To travel light and fast, riders carried little more than the mail and a small horn to signal the next station.\n\nThe Pony Express was a success at its main goal. It cut the delivery time from weeks to only about ten days. News that once crawled across the country now seemed to fly. People in California finally felt closer to the rest of the nation.\n\nYet the Pony Express did not last long. In late 1861, workers finished a telegraph line that could send messages across the country in seconds using electric signals over wires. A horse, no matter how fast, could not beat the speed of the telegraph. Just eighteen months after it began, the Pony Express closed for good. Even so, it is still remembered as a bold chapter in the story of how Americans worked to connect their country."}],"questions":[{"id":"Q1","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P1","questionText":"According to Part 1, where did the blue square in the quilt come from?","diagram":null,"options":["Grandfather''s work shirt","A tablecloth from a family supper","Mia''s baby blanket","Grandma Pearl''s Sunday dress"],"answer":0,"explanation":"In Part 1, Grandma Pearl points to a blue square and says, \"This piece came from your grandfather''s work shirt.\"","points":1},{"id":"Q2","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"raggedy\" as it is used in Part 1?","diagram":null,"options":["Large and heavy","Worn and shabby","Bright and new","Soft and warm"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Mia first sees the quilt as plain and \"raggedy,\" meaning old and worn. Later the white square \"did not feel raggedy anymore\" but \"felt warm,\" showing raggedy is the opposite of warm and new.","points":1},{"id":"Q3","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Which word BEST describes how Mia''s feelings change from the beginning to the end of the story?","diagram":null,"options":["From doubtful to delighted","From proud to ashamed","From cheerful to angry","From afraid to bored"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Mia begins by frowning and saying quilts cannot talk (doubtful), but by the end she laughs, presses a square to her cheek, and falls asleep happily listening to the stories (delighted).","points":1},{"id":"Q4","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"L.3.5.a","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Read this sentence from Part 2: \"Every square was a window into a day that had already happened.\" What is the meaning of the phrase \"a window into a day\"?","diagram":null,"options":["A piece of glass that breaks easily","A way to look back at a moment from the past","A spot that needs to be cleaned often","An opening that keeps out the cold air"],"answer":1,"explanation":"A window is something you look through to see. The phrase means each square lets Mia look back at and remember a day from the past, not a real glass window.","points":1},{"id":"Q5","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What is the main lesson, or theme, of this story?","diagram":null,"options":["Sewing is the most important skill to learn.","Children should not ask their grandparents questions.","Old quilts should be thrown away when they tear.","Ordinary objects can hold meaningful family memories."],"answer":3,"explanation":"The quilt looks plain, but each square holds a family memory, and Mia learns to value it. The theme is that ordinary objects can carry meaningful memories.","points":1},{"id":"Q6","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Which statement from the text BEST supports the idea that Mia''s feelings about the quilt have changed?","diagram":null,"options":["\"Grandma Pearl kept an old quilt folded at the foot of her bed.\"","\"Square by square, the quilt told its stories.\"","\"Mia frowned, because quilts cannot talk.\"","\"It did not feel raggedy anymore. It felt warm, as if it remembered being wrapped around her.\""],"answer":3,"explanation":"The quote showing the cloth no longer felt raggedy but warm directly shows Mia''s change in feeling. The other options describe the quilt or her early doubt, not her change.","points":1},{"id":"Q7","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Why does Grandma Pearl call the red square \"the most important square of all\"?","diagram":null,"options":["It is the brightest color in the whole quilt.","It is from the apron she wore the day Mia''s mother was born.","It came from the baby blanket that was once Mia''s.","It is the only square without a tear in it."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Grandma Pearl explains the red square came from the apron she wore the day Mia''s mother was born, and the tear is from rushing to meet her. That memory makes it the most important.","points":1},{"id":"Q8","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Select the TWO details from the text that show the quilt is connected to important days in the family''s life.","diagram":null,"options":["The white square had been Mia''s own baby blanket.","Grandma Pearl kept the quilt folded at the foot of her bed.","The yellow-flowered square was the dress Grandma Pearl wore the day she learned to read.","The room was quiet that night while Mia listened."],"answer":[0,2],"explanation":"The yellow square (the day she learned to read) and the white square (Mia''s baby blanket) both mark important days. Keeping the quilt folded and the quiet room are not tied to special family days.","points":1},{"id":"Q9","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.4","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"nectar\" as it is used in Part 1?","diagram":null,"options":["A small dot of paint","The home where bees live","A sweet liquid found in flowers","A type of dance bees perform"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The text says a bee finds \"a patch of flowers full of sweet nectar\" and that bees bring nectar back \"to make honey,\" showing nectar is a sweet liquid in flowers.","points":1},{"id":"Q10","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P2","questionText":"According to Part 1, what does the direction of the waggle run tell other bees?","diagram":null,"options":["Which way to fly to reach the flowers","How much honey is left in the hive","What color the flowers are","How many bees live in the hive"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Part 1 states, \"The direction of the waggle run tells the other bees which way to fly.\"","points":1},{"id":"Q11","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.2","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What is the main idea of this text?","diagram":null,"options":["Flowers grow best when the sun is shining.","Honeybees use a special dance to share where food is located.","Scientists like to paint dots on insects for fun.","Honeybees fly faster than any other insect."],"answer":1,"explanation":"The whole text explains how bees use the waggle dance to tell other bees the direction and distance of food. That is the main idea.","points":1},{"id":"Q12","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Based on the text, what does a LONGER waggle run tell the other bees?","diagram":null,"options":["The flowers are far away from the hive.","There is no food worth visiting.","The flowers are very close to the hive.","The flowers are directly toward the sun."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Part 2 states, \"A longer waggle run means the flowers are far away. A shorter run means they are close to the hive.\"","points":1},{"id":"Q13","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"How does the author connect the ideas in Part 1 and Part 2 of the text?","diagram":null,"options":["Part 1 describes bees, and Part 2 describes a different animal.","Part 1 lists problems, and Part 2 lists the same problems again.","Part 1 explains how the dance shows direction, and Part 2 explains how it also shows distance.","Part 1 tells a story, and Part 2 explains why the story is not true."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 1 explains how the waggle run shows direction; Part 2 adds how the same dance shows distance and why it helps the hive. The parts build on each other to fully explain the dance.","points":1},{"id":"Q14","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What is the connection between the information about scientists in the last paragraph and the rest of the text?","diagram":null,"options":["It describes a different way that bees make honey.","It shows that the dance is only a lucky guess the bees make.","It gives proof that the dance really does share directions, as the text explains.","It explains how scientists teach bees to dance."],"answer":2,"explanation":"The text explains the dance shares directions; the scientists'' experiment (marking bees and following them) proved the bees flew to the exact spot, which supports the rest of the text.","points":1},{"id":"Q15","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Which sentence from the text BEST supports the idea that the waggle dance helps the whole hive work together?","diagram":null,"options":["\"A longer waggle run means the flowers are far away.\"","\"Because of the waggle dance, the bees can work together.\"","\"The most famous dance is called the waggle dance.\"","\"Honeybees cannot speak the way people do.\""],"answer":1,"explanation":"The sentence stating the bees \"can work together\" because of the dance directly supports the idea of teamwork. The others define the dance or give facts that do not mention working together.","points":1},{"id":"Q16","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Use both parts of this text to answer this question. What must happen FIRST before many bees can fly straight to the flowers?","diagram":null,"options":["The flowers must move closer to the hive.","Scientists must mark the bees with paint.","The hive must grow to hold thousands of bees.","A scout bee finds the food and dances to share where it is."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Across both parts, the order is: a scout finds the food, returns, and dances; then the watching bees learn the direction and distance and fly straight to the flowers. The scout''s discovery and dance come first.","points":1},{"id":"Q17","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"relay\" as it is used in Part 1?","diagram":null,"options":["Passing something from one person to the next in turn","Resting for two minutes at a station","Sending a message by electric wire","Riding a horse in a large circle"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The text says riders would \"carry the mail in a relay, passing it from one rider to the next,\" which defines relay as passing along in turn.","points":1},{"id":"Q18","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P3","questionText":"According to Part 1, why was a fresh horse swapped in at each station?","diagram":null,"options":["So the horses could carry heavier loads","So the riders could rest for the night","So the mail would almost never stop moving","So the riders would not get lost in storms"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 1 explains that fresh horses were always ready, so \"the mail almost never stopped moving.\"","points":1},{"id":"Q19","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.2","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the main idea of this text?","diagram":null,"options":["Riders enjoyed the lonely life on the trail.","Horses are stronger than any machine ever built.","The Pony Express was a fast but short-lived way to carry mail across the country.","California was the hardest place to deliver mail."],"answer":2,"explanation":"The text describes how the Pony Express sped up mail delivery but lasted only about eighteen months before the telegraph replaced it. That is the main idea.","points":1},{"id":"Q20","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"Based on the text, what was one MAIN reason the Pony Express closed for good?","diagram":null,"options":["The riders no longer wanted to carry the mail.","The telegraph could send messages much faster than a horse.","California stopped sending and receiving letters.","The horses became too expensive to feed."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 2 states the telegraph could send messages \"in seconds,\" and \"a horse, no matter how fast, could not beat the speed of the telegraph,\" so the Pony Express closed.","points":1},{"id":"Q21","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"How does the author connect the ideas in the last paragraph of Part 2 to the rest of the text?","diagram":null,"options":["By telling a make-believe story about a horse.","By comparing two riders who carried the same letter.","By giving steps for how to build a station.","By showing cause and effect: a faster invention caused the Pony Express to end."],"answer":3,"explanation":"The earlier text shows the Pony Express was the fastest way to send mail; the last paragraph explains the telegraph arrived and was faster, which caused the Pony Express to close. This is a cause-and-effect connection.","points":1},{"id":"Q22","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"Which sentence from the text BEST supports the idea that the Pony Express reached its main goal?","diagram":null,"options":["\"The riders faced great danger.\"","\"Just eighteen months after it began, the Pony Express closed for good.\"","\"Storms could hide the trail, and the work was lonely.\"","\"It cut the delivery time from weeks to only about ten days.\""],"answer":3,"explanation":"The main goal was faster mail. The sentence about cutting delivery time from weeks to about ten days best supports that the goal was reached. The others describe danger or its ending.","points":1},{"id":"Q23","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"Select the TWO details from the text that show the Pony Express riders faced danger on the trail.","diagram":null,"options":["Storms could hide the trail.","A fresh horse was swapped in about two minutes.","The riders carried a small horn to signal the next station.","They rode through blazing heat and freezing snow."],"answer":[0,3],"explanation":"Riding through blazing heat and freezing snow, and storms hiding the trail, both show danger. Swapping horses and carrying a horn describe how the system worked, not danger.","points":1},{"id":"Q24","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.6","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"Use both parts of this text to answer this question. What does the author MOST want the reader to understand about the Pony Express?","diagram":null,"options":["It was a bold and useful idea, even though a newer invention soon replaced it.","It was slower than the wagons and boats it replaced.","It is still the main way mail is delivered today.","It was a failure that never delivered any mail at all."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Part 1 and Part 2 show the Pony Express was a bold idea that sped up mail (a success), yet it was soon replaced by the telegraph and is \"still remembered as a bold chapter.\" The author wants readers to see it as bold and useful even though it did not last.","points":1}]}');
INSERT INTO "tests" ("id","grade","subject","test_type","title","time_limit_minutes","question_count","source","created_at","data") VALUES('g3-read-moy-2',3,'reading','moy','Grade 3 Reading — Middle of Year (MOY) Test 2',90,24,'curated','2026-06-02T00:00:00.000Z','{"id":"g3-read-moy-2","grade":3,"subject":"reading","testType":"moy","title":"Grade 3 Reading — Middle of Year (MOY) Test 2","instructions":"Read each selection carefully. Some questions have two parts or ask you to use both parts of the text. Choose the best answer for each question.","timeLimitMinutes":90,"calculatorAllowed":false,"source":"curated","passages":[{"id":"P1","title":"The Mural on Oak Street","genre":"fiction","lexile":"560L","text":"Part 1\n\nThe brick wall at the end of Oak Street had been gray and plain for as long as Lena could remember. Every day she walked past it on her way to school, and every day it seemed a little more dull. One morning she stopped and stared at the empty wall. \"That wall could be beautiful,\" she said out loud.\n\nLena drew a picture of a giant garden full of bright flowers and painted birds. She carried her drawing to the community center and showed it to Ms. Park, who ran the neighborhood meetings. \"This is wonderful,\" Ms. Park said, \"but a wall this big needs many hands. One painter alone would take a whole year.\"\n\nLena did not give up. She made small flyers and taped them to mailboxes and shop windows up and down the street. The flyers asked neighbors to help paint a mural on the gray wall. At the first meeting, only two people came, and Lena felt a flutter of worry in her chest.\n\nPart 2\n\nThe next Saturday was different. Word had spread from neighbor to neighbor. When Lena arrived at the wall, she could not believe her eyes. Almost twenty people stood waiting with brushes, buckets, and old shirts. Mr. Diaz brought ladders from his shop. Two teachers brought leftover paint from the school.\n\nThe neighbors worked all weekend. Children painted the small flowers near the bottom, while taller helpers reached the birds near the top. By Sunday evening, the dull gray wall had turned into a garden that seemed to glow. People driving by slowed down to look and smile.\n\nLena stood back and felt proud, but she was even happier about something else. The mural had brought the whole street together. Neighbors who had never spoken now waved and laughed like old friends. \"A wall can do more than hold up a building,\" Lena thought. \"This one holds up our whole neighborhood.\""},{"id":"P2","title":"The Ant and the Grasshopper","genre":"fiction","lexile":"540L","text":"Part 1\n\nAll through the warm days of summer, a grasshopper hopped through the meadow, singing and playing his fiddle. The grass was green, the air was sweet, and food was easy to find. \"Why work,\" he chirped, \"when the sun is bright and the world is full of food?\"\n\nNearby, a small brown ant marched back and forth, carrying grains of wheat that were nearly as big as she was. Drop by drop, the sweat rolled off her, but she did not stop. She stored each grain deep inside her hill, building up a pile for later.\n\n\"Come and play with me!\" called the grasshopper. \"Summer will last forever.\" The ant shook her head. \"Winter is coming,\" she answered. \"I am gathering food now so that I will have enough when the snow falls.\" The grasshopper only laughed and hopped away to play another tune.\n\nPart 2\n\nThe golden days of summer slowly faded. The leaves turned brown and dropped from the trees. Then the cold winds blew, and snow covered the meadow in a thick white blanket. There was no green grass and no food to be found anywhere.\n\nThe grasshopper grew thin and hungry. He shivered in the icy wind, wishing he had something to eat. At last he crept to the ant''s warm hill and begged for a meal. The ant remembered the summer, but she was kind. She shared a little of her stored food so the grasshopper would not starve.\n\n\"Thank you,\" said the grasshopper, ashamed of how he had spent his summer. \"I see now that it is wise to prepare for hard times before they come.\" The ant nodded. From that day on, the grasshopper worked beside her, and he never laughed at hard work again."},{"id":"P3","title":"How Spiders Spin Their Webs","genre":"informational","lexile":"600L","text":"Part 1\n\nMany people are surprised to learn that spiders are not insects. Insects have six legs, but spiders have eight. Spiders also have a special talent that most insects do not have: they can make silk. This silk is one of the strongest materials in nature, and spiders use it to build webs that catch food.\n\nA spider makes silk inside its body using tiny organs called spinnerets. The silk starts as a liquid, but as the spider pulls it out, the silk turns into a solid thread. The thread is so thin that it is hard to see, yet it is stretchy and very strong. Some spider silk is stronger than a steel thread of the same size.\n\nTo begin a web, a spider must build a bridge. It releases a long thread of silk and lets the wind carry it across a gap. When the thread sticks to a branch or wall on the other side, the spider has its first line. From this single line, the whole web will grow.\n\nPart 2\n\nNext, the spider builds a frame and adds spokes that reach out from the center, like the lines on a wheel. These first threads are not sticky, so the spider can walk on them safely. They give the web its shape and hold everything in place.\n\nThen the spider spins a sticky spiral around the spokes, starting from the center and circling outward. This sticky silk is the part that traps insects. When a fly bumps into the web, it gets stuck, and the spider hurries out to catch its meal. Because the spider walks only on the dry threads, it does not get caught in its own trap.\n\nA web does not last forever. Wind, rain, and struggling insects can tear it apart. Many spiders build a fresh web each day. Instead of letting the old silk go to waste, some spiders eat it and use it to make new silk. In this way, a spider can spin a brand-new web again and again."}],"questions":[{"id":"Q1","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P1","questionText":"According to the text, why does Lena stop and stare at the brick wall one morning?","diagram":null,"options":["She is lost on her way to school.","She wants to climb over the wall.","She thinks the wall could be beautiful.","She is waiting for Ms. Park."],"answer":2,"explanation":"In Part 1, Lena stares at the empty wall and says out loud, \"That wall could be beautiful.\"","points":1},{"id":"Q2","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What did Lena do after Ms. Park said the wall needs many hands?","diagram":null,"options":["She painted a smaller wall instead.","She gave up on the mural.","She decided to paint the wall by herself.","She made flyers asking neighbors to help."],"answer":3,"explanation":"After Ms. Park said the wall needs many hands, Lena made flyers and taped them to mailboxes and shop windows to ask neighbors to help.","points":1},{"id":"Q3","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"L.3.5.a","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What is the meaning of the phrase \"a flutter of worry in her chest\" in paragraph 3 of Part 1?","diagram":null,"options":["Lena feels nervous because only two people came.","Lena is angry at her neighbors.","Lena is too tired to keep working.","Lena is excited that so many people came."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Only two people came to the first meeting, so \"a flutter of worry\" shows Lena feels nervous that not enough people will help.","points":1},{"id":"Q4","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P1","questionText":"According to Part 2, what did Mr. Diaz bring to help with the mural?","diagram":null,"options":["Brushes and old shirts","Ladders from his shop","Leftover paint from the school","Small flyers"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 2 states that Mr. Diaz brought ladders from his shop.","points":1},{"id":"Q5","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What is the main theme, or lesson, of this story?","diagram":null,"options":["Gray walls are always ugly.","Working together can make a community stronger.","Painting is the best way to spend a weekend.","It is hard to find good paint."],"answer":1,"explanation":"The story ends with the mural bringing the whole street together, showing that working together makes the community stronger.","points":1},{"id":"Q6","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Which word best describes Lena based on her actions in the story?","diagram":null,"options":["Fearful","Lazy","Determined","Selfish"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Even when only two people came, Lena did not give up and kept working to organize the mural, which shows she is determined.","points":1},{"id":"Q7","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Which sentence from the text best supports the idea that the mural did more than just decorate a wall?","diagram":null,"options":["\"Lena drew a picture of a giant garden full of bright flowers and painted birds.\"","\"Neighbors who had never spoken now waved and laughed like old friends.\"","\"Children painted the small flowers near the bottom.\"","\"The brick wall at the end of Oak Street had been gray and plain.\""],"answer":1,"explanation":"The sentence about neighbors who had never spoken now waving and laughing shows the mural brought people together, which is more than just decorating a wall.","points":1},{"id":"Q8","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.5","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Use both parts of this text to answer this question. How is the wall different at the end of the story compared to the beginning?","diagram":null,"options":["It is still gray and plain.","It changed from dull and gray to a bright, glowing garden.","It was torn down and rebuilt.","It is taller than it was before."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Part 1 describes the wall as gray, plain, and dull, while Part 2 says the neighbors turned it into a garden that seemed to glow.","points":1},{"id":"Q9","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P2","questionText":"According to Part 1, what does the grasshopper do all through the summer?","diagram":null,"options":["He builds a hill to store food.","He sleeps in the shade.","He gathers grains of wheat.","He sings and plays his fiddle."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Part 1 says the grasshopper hopped through the meadow singing and playing his fiddle all summer.","points":1},{"id":"Q10","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Why does the ant work so hard during the summer?","diagram":null,"options":["She wants to win a race against the grasshopper.","She is gathering food for the winter.","She is building a fiddle of her own.","She does not know how to play."],"answer":1,"explanation":"The ant tells the grasshopper she is gathering food now so she will have enough when the snow falls.","points":1},{"id":"Q11","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.4","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"faded\" in the sentence \"The golden days of summer slowly faded\" in Part 2?","diagram":null,"options":["Grew brighter","Became warmer","Stayed the same","Came to an end"],"answer":3,"explanation":"The days \"faded\" as the leaves turned brown and winter arrived, so \"faded\" means the summer slowly came to an end.","points":1},{"id":"Q12","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What happens to the grasshopper after the snow covers the meadow?","diagram":null,"options":["He flies south for the winter.","He finds plenty of food to eat.","He builds his own hill.","He grows thin and hungry."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Part 2 says the grasshopper grew thin and hungry and shivered in the icy wind with no food to find.","points":1},{"id":"Q13","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Which word best describes the ant in the story?","diagram":null,"options":["Hardworking","Careless","Greedy","Foolish"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The ant works without stopping all summer to store food, which shows she is hardworking.","points":1},{"id":"Q14","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What lesson does this fable mainly teach?","diagram":null,"options":["It is best to play all the time.","Singing is more important than working.","It is wise to prepare for hard times before they come.","Ants and grasshoppers cannot be friends."],"answer":2,"explanation":"The grasshopper learns it is wise to prepare for hard times before they come, which is the lesson of the fable.","points":1},{"id":"Q15","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Use both parts of this text to answer this question. Why is the grasshopper ashamed at the end of the story?","diagram":null,"options":["He could not find his fiddle in the snow.","He played all summer instead of storing food, and now he must beg.","He ate all of the ant''s food without asking.","He sang a song that the ant did not like."],"answer":1,"explanation":"In Part 1 the grasshopper played while the ant worked, and in Part 2 he must beg the ant for food, so he is ashamed of how he spent his summer.","points":1},{"id":"Q16","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"RL.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Select the two details from the story that show the ant was getting ready for winter.","diagram":null,"options":["She stored each grain deep inside her hill.","She played a tune on a fiddle.","She carried grains of wheat that were nearly as big as she was.","She hopped through the meadow singing."],"answer":[0,2],"explanation":"The ant carried grains of wheat and stored each one in her hill to prepare for winter. Playing the fiddle and hopping while singing are things the grasshopper did.","points":1},{"id":"Q17","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.2","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the main idea of this text?","diagram":null,"options":["Spider silk is weaker than steel.","Spiders are scary and dangerous animals.","Spiders use silk to build webs in careful steps.","All insects can make silk."],"answer":2,"explanation":"The whole text explains how spiders make silk and use it to build webs step by step.","points":1},{"id":"Q18","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P3","questionText":"According to the text, how many legs do spiders have?","diagram":null,"options":["Eight","Ten","Six","Four"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The text says insects have six legs, but spiders have eight.","points":1},{"id":"Q19","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"spinnerets\" in paragraph 2 of Part 1?","diagram":null,"options":["Tiny organs a spider uses to make silk","Insects that get caught in webs","Branches where webs are built","Sticky threads at the center of a web"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The text says a spider makes silk inside its body using tiny organs called spinnerets.","points":1},{"id":"Q20","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What step does a spider take first when building a web?","diagram":null,"options":["It builds a bridge by letting the wind carry a thread across a gap.","It adds spokes that reach out from the center.","It spins a sticky spiral around the spokes.","It eats its old web."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Part 1 explains that to begin a web, a spider first builds a bridge by releasing a thread that the wind carries across a gap.","points":1},{"id":"Q21","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"According to the text, why does the spider NOT get stuck in its own web?","diagram":null,"options":["Its legs are covered in water.","Its silk is too weak to hold the spider.","It walks only on the dry, non-sticky threads.","It never touches the web at all."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Part 2 says the spokes are not sticky and the spider walks only on the dry threads, so it does not get caught in its own trap.","points":1},{"id":"Q22","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"RI.3.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"Select the two facts the text gives about spider silk.","diagram":null,"options":["It is made by all insects.","It can never be torn apart.","It starts as a liquid inside the spider.","It can be stronger than a steel thread of the same size."],"answer":[2,3],"explanation":"The text states the silk starts as a liquid and that some spider silk is stronger than a steel thread of the same size. It also says webs can be torn by wind, rain, and insects, and that spiders, not insects, make silk.","points":1},{"id":"Q23","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"How does the author connect the ideas in the paragraph about the sticky spiral and the paragraph about webs not lasting forever in Part 2?","diagram":null,"options":["The author first explains how a finished web catches food, then explains why a spider must build a new web.","The author tells a made-up story about one spider''s day.","The author lists the colors of spider silk.","The author compares two different kinds of spiders."],"answer":0,"explanation":"The sticky-spiral paragraph explains how the finished web traps insects, and the next paragraph explains why webs wear out and must be rebuilt, connecting how a web works to why spiders make new ones.","points":1},{"id":"Q24","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.3.8","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"Use both parts of this text to answer this question. What is the connection between Part 1 and Part 2 of the article?","diagram":null,"options":["Both parts compare spiders to insects.","Part 1 describes a problem and Part 2 gives an opinion about it.","Part 2 happens before Part 1 in time.","Part 1 explains what silk is and how a web begins, and Part 2 gives the next steps to finish and rebuild the web."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Part 1 explains what spider silk is and how the spider starts a web with a bridge, and Part 2 continues with the frame, spokes, sticky spiral, and rebuilding, giving the steps in order.","points":1}]}');
INSERT INTO "tests" ("id","grade","subject","test_type","title","time_limit_minutes","question_count","source","created_at","data") VALUES('g3-read-sample-mpz0vonr',3,'reading','eog','Grade 3 Reading — BOG3/EOG Released Form',120,42,'sample','2026-06-04T04:56:47.754Z','{"id":"g3-read-sample-mpz0vonr","grade":3,"subject":"reading","testType":"eog","title":"Grade 3 Reading — BOG3/EOG Released Form","instructions":"Released-form sample. Choose the best answer for each question.","timeLimitMinutes":120,"calculatorAllowed":false,"source":"sample","createdAt":"2026-06-04T04:56:47.754Z","passages":[{"id":"P1","title":"Octopus","text":"The octopus is a sea animal. It has an interesting body. First, it has three hearts. The heart is often seen as a symbol of love. That’s a lot of love! An octopus also has eight limbs. Some people call them arms or tentacles. Eight arms could give a lot of hugs, but the octopus is a very shy animal. If an octopus is scared, it will squirt ink and swim away."},{"id":"P4","title":"The Adventures of Grandfather Frog","text":"Billy Mink ran around the edge of the Smiling Pool and turned down by the Laughing Brook. His eyes twinkled with mischief, and he hurried as only Billy can. As he passed Jerry Muskrat''s house, Jerry saw him.\n\n\"Hi, Billy Mink! Where are you going in such a hurry this fine morning?\" he called.\n\n\"To find Little Joe Otter. Have you seen him?\" replied Billy.\n\n\"No,\" said Jerry. \"He''s probably down to the Big River fishing. I heard him say last night that he was going.\"\n\n\"Thanks,\" said Billy Mink, and without waiting to say more he was off like a little brown flash.\n\nJerry watched him out of sight. \"Hump!\" exclaimed Jerry. \"Billy Mink is in a terrible hurry this morning. Now I wonder what he is so anxious to find Little Joe Otter for. When they get their heads together, it is usually for some mischief.\"\n\nJerry climbed to the top of his house and looked over the Smiling Pool in the direction from which Billy Mink had just come. Almost at once he saw Grandfather Frog fast asleep on his big green lily pad. The legs of a foolish green fly were sticking out of one corner of his big mouth. Jerry couldn''t help laughing, for Grandfather Frog certainly did look funny.\n\n\"He''s had a good breakfast this morning, and his full stomach has made him sleepy,\" thought Jerry. \"But he''s getting careless in his old age. He certainly is getting careless. The idea of going to sleep right out in plain sight like that!\"\n\nSuddenly a new thought popped into his head. \"Billy Mink saw him, and that is why he is so anxious to find Little Joe Otter. He is planning to play some trick on Grandfather Frog as sure as pollywogs have tails!\" exclaimed Jerry. Then his eyes began to twinkle as he added: \"I think I''ll have some fun myself.\"\n\nWithout another word Jerry slipped down into the water and swam over to the big green lily pad of Grandfather Frog. Then he pounded the water loudly with his tail. Grandfather Frog’s big goggly eyes flew open, and he was just about to make a frightened plunge into the Smiling Pool when he saw Jerry.\n\n“Have a nice nap?” inquired Jerry, with a broad grin.\n\n“I wasn’t asleep!” protested Grandfather Frog indignantly. “I was just thinking.”\n\n“Don’t you think it a rather dangerous plan to think so long with your eyes closed?” asked Jerry.\n\n“Well, maybe I did just doze off,” admitted Grandfather Frog sheepishly.\n\n“Maybe you did,” replied Jerry. “Now listen.” Then Jerry whispered in Grandfather Frog’s ear, and both chuckled as if they were enjoying some joke, for they are great friends, you know. Afterward Jerry swam back to his house, and Grandfather Frog closed his eyes so as to look just as he did when he was asleep.\n\nMeanwhile Billy Mink had hurried down the Laughing Brook. Halfway to the Big River he met Little Joe Otter bringing home a big fish, for you know Little Joe is a great fisherman. Billy Mink hastened to tell him how Grandfather Frog had fallen fast asleep on his big green lily pad.\n\n“It’s a splendid chance to have some fun with Grandfather Frog and give him a great scare,” concluded Billy.\n\nLittle Joe Otter put his fish down and grinned. He likes to play pranks almost as well as he likes to go fishing.\n\n“What can we do?” said he."},{"id":"P5","title":"Beavers at Home","text":"A beaver is a wild animal about three feet in length, and weighing forty or fifty pounds. It is covered with fine, glossy, grayish brown fur. Its tail is nearly a foot long, and has no hair at all, but only little scales, something like those of a fish. When the beaver is swimming about in the water it uses its tail as a kind of rudder.\n\nA beaver cannot bear to live alone. He is never as happy as when he has a large number of friends close at hand whom he can visit every day; for beavers are the best and kindest neighbors in the world, always ready to help one another in building new houses or in repairing old ones.\n\nOf course the first thing to be done when one is going to build a house or a village is to find a good place for it; and the spot which every beaver of sense thinks is best is either a large pond, or, if no pond is to be had, a low plain with a stream running through it. For on such a plain, a pond can be made by causing the water to cover it.\n\nIt must be a very, very long time since beavers first learned that the way to make a pond is to build a dam across a running stream. To begin with, they must know which way the stream runs, and in this they never make a mistake.\n\nThey first gather together a number of sticks and logs about five feet long, which they carry or roll into the stream. While some of the beavers are doing this—for the safety of the village lies in the strength of the foundation—others are gathering and piling up many green branches of trees. These branches, which they have cut from the trees with their teeth, are piled among the sticks and logs, and soon a dam is formed that reaches across the stream.\n\nWhen the foundation of the dam has been finished, the beavers pile stones and mud upon it until they have built a wall ten or twelve feet thick at the bottom and two or three feet thick at the top. After all this has been done, the older and wiser beavers go carefully over every part to see if the dam is of the right shape and is strong and safe; for beavers do not like poor work, and they know that a weak dam is easily washed away.\n\nWhen the dam has been finished and the pond made, the beavers begin to think about their houses. As they like to have their rooms dry, they raise the floors of their houses some distance above the water, so that when the stream rises during the rainy season they will not be flooded.\n\nBeavers are always quite clear in their minds as to what they want, and how to get it, and they like to keep things separate. When they are in the water, they are as happy as they can be; but when they are out of it, they like to be dry. It is sometimes two or three months before the village is finished. But the little round huts are to be used only for winter homes; for during the summer no beaver would think of sleeping indoors or, indeed, of staying very long in the same place.\n\nEverything that a beaver does is well done. The walls of his house are thick and strong, and when he has a large family or many friends to stay with him the house has several rooms in it. No beaver ever thinks of living alone. Sometimes he will have one companion, and sometimes a dozen or more. But however full the house may be, everything is kept in good order. Each beaver has his fixed place on the floor, which is covered with dry leaves and grass. A door is always kept open into the place where their food is kept, and so they never go hungry. There they stay all through the winter eating the bark and tender shoots of young trees which they have carefully stored away, sleeping through the cold stormy weather, and at last getting very fat.\n\nAt one time there were many beavers in the West and the South, but now there are very few to be found there. Many years ago a Frenchman who was traveling in Louisiana spent a good deal of time watching beavers and learning about their ways. He hid himself close to a dam which the little creatures had built, and in the night he cut a hole about a foot wide right through it.\n\nHe had made no noise while cutting through the dam, but the rush of the water awakened one beaver who was not sleeping as soundly as the others. This beaver left his hut quickly, and swam to the dam to see what was wrong. As soon as he saw the stream that had been dug, he struck four loud blows with his tail, and every beaver in the village left his bed and rushed out in answer to the call. When they reached the dam and saw the large hole in it, they held a meeting as to what they should do. Then the head beaver gave orders to the rest, and all went to the bank to get sticks and mud.\n\nWhen they had gathered together as much as they could carry, they formed in line and marched with their loads to the dam. The sticks were thrown into the hole and mud and stones were packed upon them. The beavers worked hard and wisely, and in a short time the dam was as good as ever. Then one of the older beavers struck two blows with his tail, and in a few minutes all were in bed and asleep again."}],"questions":[{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"What does shy mean in the text?","options":["A fearful","B harmful","C proud","D brave"],"diagram":null,"skill":"vocabulary","id":"Q1","points":1,"passageId":"P1","difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"Shy means feeling scared or nervous around others, so it makes sense that it relates to being fearful."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"How many hearts does an octopus have?","options":["A one","B three","C five","D eight"],"diagram":null,"skill":"comprehension","id":"Q2","points":1,"passageId":"P1","difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"An octopus has three hearts, which helps it pump blood, so saying it has five is incorrect because that''s too many!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"What is the meaning of pecked in paragraph 2?","options":["A poked","B ran from","C marched to","D tossed"],"diagram":null,"skill":"vocabulary","id":"Q3","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":3,"explanation":"Pecked means to poke at something, like a bird pecking at food, so tossing is not the right meaning here."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"What is the meaning of latch in paragraph 2?","options":["A side","B fence","C lock","D bottom"],"diagram":null,"skill":"vocabulary","id":"Q4","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"A latch is a type of lock that keeps things closed, just like how a door lock keeps a door shut."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"What did Rhode Island Red do after he got out of his cage?","options":["A He rode with the animals on the roller coaster.","B He put all of the animals in their cages.","C He chased the animals to the midway.","D He let the other animals out of their cages."],"diagram":null,"skill":"comprehension","id":"Q5","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"Rhode Island Red had fun riding the roller coaster with the other animals, which shows he was enjoying himself after getting out."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"How did the boy get all the animals back in their cages?","options":["A He chased after each one to get them to run into their cages.","B He shook a pail of oats while yelling at the animals to get back in their cages.","C He dropped a trail of oats behind him so the animals would follow him to their cages.","D He grabbed Rhode Island Red first and then scared all the other animals to their cages."],"diagram":null,"skill":"comprehension","id":"Q6","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":3,"explanation":"He grabbed Rhode Island Red first because that helped him scare the other animals back into their cages, showing he was clever in his plan."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Why is Rhode Island Red so pleased with himself at the end of the text?","options":["A He gets the boy to feed all the animals and let them out of their cages.","B He gets all the animals back into their cages without anyone else’s help.","C He is happy to be in his cage with a long drink and some food.","D He is happy that he let the animals out of their cages so they could have some fun."],"diagram":null,"skill":"Character feelings","id":"Q7","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":3,"explanation":"Rhode Island Red felt proud because he let the other animals have fun, and that made him happy to see them enjoying themselves."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Which word describes the boy in the text?","options":["A clever","B scared","C unusual","D useless"],"diagram":null,"skill":"character analysis","id":"Q8","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"The boy is clever because he comes up with smart ideas to lead and manage the animals, showing he thinks well on his feet."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"What is one way that Rhode Island Red and the boy are alike?","options":["A They both lead the animals.","B They both chase the animals.","C They both feed the animals.","D They both catch the animals."],"diagram":null,"skill":"Compare characters","id":"Q9","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"Rhode Island Red and the boy are alike because they both know how to lead the animals, which shows teamwork."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Which statement from the text shows that Rhode Island Red is proud?","options":["A “And in the middle of the poultry tent sat Rhode Island Red, the rooster.”","B “One morning, Red pecked at the latch on his cage.”","C “Rhode Island Red headed straight for the goose tent.”","D “But Rhode Island Red just drank a long drink, fluffed up his feathers, and crowed, ‘R-r-r-r-roooo!’ ”"],"diagram":null,"skill":"Character traits","id":"Q10","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":3,"explanation":"Rhode Island Red is proud when he fluffs up his feathers and crows, showing he feels good about himself and what he did."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"What is the meaning of inspired in paragraph 4?","options":["A changed","B started","C finished","D used"],"diagram":null,"skill":"Vocabulary","id":"Q11","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"The word ''inspired'' means to start something new, like when you get a great idea and want to create something special."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"According to the text, what is often difficult for the author?","options":["A drawing pictures","B creating a title","C getting started","D reading a book"],"diagram":null,"skill":"Author''s challenges","id":"Q12","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"The author finds it hard to get started because beginning a new project can be tricky, just like starting a puzzle can be tough until you find the first piece."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"What is the meaning of portrait in paragraph 6?","options":["A lesson","B picture","C report","D story"],"diagram":null,"skill":"Vocabulary","id":"Q13","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"A ''portrait'' is a picture of someone, usually showing their face, which helps us remember what they look like."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"According to the text, why does the cat have a bell on its collar?","options":["A The bell warns the birds.","B The bell makes a nice sound.","C The bell is pretty.","D The bell is interesting."],"diagram":null,"skill":"Details","id":"Q14","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"The bell on the cat''s collar is there to warn the birds, so they can fly away before the cat gets too close."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"How does the author connect the writing steps in paragraphs 10 and 11?","options":["A by contrasting two different styles for writing books","B by giving a step-by-step process for publishing a book","C by comparing the writing steps for two kinds of books","D by giving a chronological order for beginning a book"],"diagram":null,"skill":"Text structure","id":"Q15","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":3,"explanation":"The author connects the writing steps by showing the order in which you should do things when starting to write a book, like following a recipe."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"How does the author connect the ideas in paragraphs 12 and 13?","options":["A by listing important events that have occurred in the author’s life","B by explaining the different parts of the book that have to be made","C by describing how the author gets ideas when they just will not come","D by comparing the rhythm of the text when read aloud to how it looks on paper"],"diagram":null,"skill":"Text structure","id":"Q16","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"The author connects the ideas by explaining the different parts of a book that need to be created, which helps us understand how a book is made."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"What is the meaning of the phrase “right under your nose” in paragraph 16?","options":["A inside a person","B on a person’s face","C read by a person","D in front of a person"],"diagram":null,"skill":"Idioms","id":"Q17","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":3,"explanation":"The phrase ''right under your nose'' means something is in front of you, like when you can''t find your glasses because they''re on your head!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Which statement by the author supports the main idea?","options":["A \"The books I made needed text, so I began writing words to go with my art.\"","B \"Getting a good idea for a book is the hardest thing for me, but also the most fun.\"","C \"I like to write out rough story ideas for my books, then make thumbnail sketches.\"","D \"I like to read the text out loud and listen to the rhythm of the words.\""],"diagram":null,"skill":"main idea","id":"Q18","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"This statement shows that getting a good idea is really important and can be hard, which is a big part of writing a book and supports the main idea."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Why was Billy in a hurry?","options":["A He was looking for Grandfather Frog.","B He was getting careless in his old age.","C He was going to eat breakfast.","D He was looking for Little Joe Otter."],"diagram":null,"skill":"character motivation","id":"Q19","points":1,"passageId":"P4","difficulty":"medium","answer":3,"explanation":"Billy was in a hurry because he was looking for Little Joe Otter, which means he wanted to find his friend quickly!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Why was Grandfather Frog sleeping?","options":["A He was hot.","B He is old.","C He had just eaten.","D He had been sick."],"diagram":null,"skill":"cause and effect","id":"Q20","points":1,"passageId":"P4","difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"Grandfather Frog was sleeping because he had just eaten, and sometimes after a big meal, we feel sleepy too."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Why does Jerry laugh when he sees Grandfather Frog?","options":["A Grandfather Frog is jumping on the lily pads.","B Grandfather Frog has part of a fly sticking out of his mouth.","C Grandfather Frog has singing lessons after breakfast with his friends.","D Grandfather Frog is dancing because he is happy to see Jerry."],"diagram":null,"skill":"character reaction","id":"Q21","points":1,"passageId":"P4","difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"Jerry laughs because he sees Grandfather Frog with part of a fly in his mouth, which is funny and surprising!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word slipped in paragraph 10?","options":["A crashed","B floated","C attacked","D entered"],"diagram":null,"skill":"vocabulary","id":"Q22","points":1,"passageId":"P4","difficulty":"medium","answer":3,"explanation":"In this paragraph, ''slipped'' means to enter, like when someone quietly goes into a room without being noticed."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Why did Grandfather Frog close his eyes to look just as he did when he was asleep?","options":["A to play a joke on Billy","B to get back to his nap","C to be a friend to Jerry","D to finish eating the fly"],"diagram":null,"skill":"comprehension","id":"Q23","points":1,"passageId":"P4","difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"Grandfather Frog closes his eyes to play a joke on Billy, making it seem like he is asleep when he really isn''t!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"What is the meaning of splendid in paragraph 17?","options":["A fast","B great","C safe","D usual"],"diagram":null,"skill":"vocabulary","id":"Q24","points":1,"passageId":"P4","difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"The word ''splendid'' means great, which shows something is really wonderful or impressive!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Which detail from the text supports that Grandfather Frog was scared when Jerry pounded the water with his tail?","options":["A “The idea of going to sleep right out in plain sight like that!”","B “He was just about to make a frightened plunge into the Smiling Pool when he saw Jerry.”","C “I wasn’t asleep!’ protested Grandfather Frog indignantly.”","D “Don’t you think it a rather dangerous plan to think so long with your eyes closed?’ asked Jerry.”"],"diagram":null,"skill":"text evidence","id":"Q25","points":1,"passageId":"P4","difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"This detail shows that Grandfather Frog was scared because he was about to jump into the water quickly when he saw Jerry, which means he was startled!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"How does Jerry’s climb to the top of his house contribute to the rest of the text?","options":["A He realizes that he wants to take a nap.","B He knows that he wants to go fishing.","C He knows where to find Longlegs the Blue Heron.","D He realizes why Billy Mink is in such a hurry."],"diagram":null,"skill":"text structure","id":"Q26","points":1,"passageId":"P4","difficulty":"medium","answer":3,"explanation":"Jerry''s climb helps him understand why Billy Mink is in a hurry, showing how climbing gives him a better view of what''s happening!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"According to the text, which choice describes a beaver’s tail?","options":["A It is three feet long and weighs forty or fifty pounds.","B It has small scales similar to those of a fish.","C It is covered with shiny, brown fur.","D It looks like a hairy rudder on a boat."],"diagram":null,"skill":"comprehension","id":"Q27","points":1,"passageId":"P5","difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"A beaver''s tail has small scales like a fish, which makes it different from other animal tails and helps it in the water!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word bear in paragraph 2?","options":["A accept","B carry","C uncover","D earn"],"diagram":null,"skill":"vocabulary","id":"Q28","points":1,"passageId":"P5","difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"In this paragraph, ''bear'' means to accept something, like when you take on a responsibility or deal with a situation."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"According to the text, what step follows finishing the foundation when building a beaver dam?","options":["gathering sticks and logs","piling stones and mud on top","watching which way the stream runs","checking to see if it is strong and safe"],"diagram":null,"skill":"sequence of events","id":"Q29","points":1,"passageId":"P5","difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"After finishing the foundation of a beaver dam, the next step is piling stones and mud on top to make it strong and sturdy!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"What is the connection between paragraphs 5 and 6?","options":["They present a problem and offer a solution.","They explain a cause-effect relationship.","They present a sequence for building.","They compare habits of wise beavers."],"diagram":null,"skill":"text structure","id":"Q30","points":1,"passageId":"P5","difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"Paragraphs 5 and 6 show a sequence for building, explaining the steps that come one after the other in the process of making a dam."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Why do beavers carefully inspect a dam after building it?","options":["Beavers need to build a bridge to get across the stream.","Beavers know that water will wash away a weak dam.","Beavers want to find the best place to build a house or village.","Beavers make the walls of their houses with big sticks."],"diagram":null,"skill":"cause and effect","id":"Q31","points":1,"passageId":"P5","difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"Beavers check their dam because they want to make sure it''s strong enough to hold the water. If it''s weak, the water can wash it away, so they inspect it carefully to keep their home safe."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"What does the word companion mean in paragraph 9?","options":["sister","enemy","worker","friend"],"diagram":null,"skill":"vocabulary","id":"Q32","points":1,"passageId":"P5","difficulty":"medium","answer":3,"explanation":"The word companion means friend because it describes someone who is close to you and shares fun times, just like a good friend does."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"How are paragraphs 10 and 11 connected?","options":["Both compare the two ways that beavers build dams.","Both describe the differences between a dam and a pond.","Paragraph 10 presents a problem, and paragraph 11 describes a solution.","Paragraph 10 shows a result of the unusual situation in paragraph 11."],"diagram":null,"skill":"text structure","id":"Q33","points":1,"passageId":"P5","difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"Paragraph 10 talks about a problem that the beavers face, and then paragraph 11 gives a solution to that problem, showing how they work together to fix things."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Which detail from the text supports the main idea?","options":["“A beaver is a wild animal about three feet in length.”","“They first gather together a number of sticks and logs.”","“No beaver ever thinks of living alone.”","“Each beaver has his fixed place on the floor.”"],"diagram":null,"skill":"main idea and details","id":"Q34","points":1,"passageId":"P5","difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"The detail about gathering sticks and logs shows the main idea of how beavers build their homes, which is important to understand their behavior."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"What is the meaning of experienced in paragraph 2?","options":["eager","important","practiced","expected"],"diagram":null,"skill":"vocabulary","id":"Q35","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"Experienced means practiced because it describes someone who has done something many times and knows how to do it well."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Why did the rock climbers end their climb early?","options":["The weather was bad.","The group was bored.","The dog was tired.","The dog was sick."],"diagram":null,"skill":"cause and effect","id":"Q36","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"The climbers ended their climb early because the weather was bad, which can make climbing unsafe and uncomfortable."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"According to the text, what caused the climbers to fall down the mountain?","options":["They were very tired.","The mountain was rocky.","It was getting dark.","The mountain was slippery."],"diagram":null,"skill":"cause and effect","id":"Q37","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":3,"explanation":"The climbers fell because the mountain was slippery, which means it was hard to keep their balance and stay safe while climbing."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"How does the author connect the point that the climb was very dangerous in paragraphs 5 and 6?","options":["A The information in paragraph 6 is a result of the action in paragraph 5.","B The ideas in paragraphs 5 and 6 compare the different climbers.","C Paragraphs 5 and 6 describe the path the climbers took.","D Paragraph 5 lists the steps needed for paragraph 6."],"diagram":null,"skill":"text analysis","id":"Q38","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"The author connects the danger of the climb by showing that what happens in paragraph 6 is a result of the actions described in paragraph 5, making it clear how risky the situation was."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"What is the meaning of “face the fact” in paragraph 8?","options":["A to look at an idea one believes in","B to admit that something is true","C to escape from danger","D to learn something new"],"diagram":null,"skill":"vocabulary","id":"Q39","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"To"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"According to the text, what is the relationship between the climbers petting Velvet’s fur and Velvet licking them?","options":["A Both dried the climbers.","B Both scared the climbers.","C Both calmed the climbers.","D Both warmed the climbers."],"diagram":null,"skill":"text analysis","id":"Q40","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"face the fact"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"What is the main idea of the text?","options":["A Mount Hood can be a dangerous place.","B Mount Hood is popular for rock climbing.","C A dog helps a group of rock climbers.","D A group of teachers goes rock climbing."],"diagram":null,"skill":"main idea","id":"Q41","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"The main idea is about how a dog named Velvet helped the rock climbers. This is important because it shows how the dog played a big role in their adventure and safety."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Which statement from the text supports the main idea?","options":["A “They had no idea a German shepherd named Velvet would help save their lives.”","B “On Sunday, the weather took a turn for the worse.”","C “They hiked for miles to try to make it down the mountainside.”","D “The rescue team found the climbers with Velvet in White River Canyon at about 7,400 feet.”"],"diagram":null,"skill":"supporting details","id":"Q42","points":1,"passageId":null,"difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"This statement tells us that the climbers were surprised that a dog could be so helpful in a dangerous situation. It directly connects to the main idea of the dog helping them."}]}');
INSERT INTO "tests" ("id","grade","subject","test_type","title","time_limit_minutes","question_count","source","created_at","data") VALUES('g3-read-sample-mpz0x6eb',3,'reading','eog','Grade 3 ELA — Released Practice',120,15,'sample','2026-06-04T04:57:43.706Z','{"id":"g3-read-sample-mpz0x6eb","grade":3,"subject":"reading","testType":"eog","title":"Grade 3 ELA — Released Practice","instructions":"Released-form sample. Choose the best answer for each question.","timeLimitMinutes":120,"calculatorAllowed":false,"source":"sample","createdAt":"2026-06-04T04:57:43.706Z","passages":[{"id":"P1","title":"Balloons Over Broadway","text":"From the time he was a little boy, Tony Sarg loved to figure out how to make things move. He once said he became a marionette man when he was only six years old.\n\nHis father had asked him to feed their chickens at six-thirty in the morning—every day. Tony had an idea—what if he could feed the chickens without leaving his bed?\n\nHe rigged up some pulleys and ran rope from the chicken coop door to his bedroom window. That night, he spread chicken feed outside the chicken coop door.\n\nThe next morning . . . Tony pulled on the rope, and the door to the chicken coop opened! The chickens ate their breakfast, Tony stayed snug in his bed, and his dad, so impressed, never made Tony do another chore.\n\nWhen Tony grew up he moved to London, where he discovered that no one was making marionettes for kids anymore. So out of wood, cloth, and strings, Tony began to make puppets. He figured out ways to make his marionettes’ movement so lifelike that they performed as if they were real actors. Word soon spread about Tony’s amazing marionettes. When Tony moved to New York City, the Tony Sarg Marionettes began performing on Broadway.\n\nIn the heart of New York City, in Herald Square, was “the biggest store on earth”: R. H. Macy’s department store. Macy’s had heard about Tony’s puppets and asked him to design a “puppet parade” for the store’s holiday windows. So Tony made new puppets based on storybook characters, then attached them to gears and pulleys to make them move.\n\nIn Macy’s “Wondertown” windows, Tony’s mechanical marionettes danced across the stage as if by magic. All day long they performed to shoppers jostling for a better look.\n\nBut Macy’s had an even bigger job in store for Tony.\n\nMany of the people working at Macy’s were immigrants, and as the holidays approached, they missed their own holiday traditions. . . . Macy’s agreed to put on a parade for their employees, and they hired Tony to help.\n\nTony too was an immigrant. . . . He loved the idea of creating a parade based on street carnivals from all over the world. He made costumes and built horse-drawn floats, and Macy’s even arranged to bring in bears, elephants, and camels from the Central Park Zoo.\n\nThe animals joined hundreds of Macy’s employees on Thanksgiving Day, 1924, winding their way from Harlem to Herald Square. It was a dazzling parade!\n\nIn fact, Macy’s first parade was such a success that they decided to have one every year on Thanksgiving Day—to celebrate America’s own holiday.\n\nEach year the parade grew. But when Macy’s brought in lions and tigers—in addition to the bears, elephants, and camels—the animals roared and growled and frightened the children.\n\nMacy’s asked Tony to replace the animals.\n\nTony hoped to replace the animals with some kind of puppets, but his marionettes were less than three feet tall. He would have to make much larger puppets in order for them to be seen in the parade. And how could he make them strong enough to hold up in bad weather yet light enough to move up and down the streets?\n\nTony knew of a company in Ohio that made blimps* out of rubber—the perfect material for any weather. When he called the company and showed them his sketches, they agreed to make what Tony wanted.\n\nStill, how would Tony make his big puppets move?\n\nThen Tony had an idea—from an Indonesian rod puppet in his toy collection.\n\nOn Thanksgiving Day, Tony’s creatures, some as high as sixteen feet, spilled into the streets, and the crowds cheered wildly.\n\nPart puppet, part balloon, the air-filled rubber bags wobbled down the avenues, propped up by wooden sticks.\n\nBut now the sidewalks were so packed with people that only those in the first few rows could really see the parade. Tony realized his puppets would have to be even bigger and higher off the ground. And though the sticks helped to steer the puppets, they were stiff and heavy. Tony wanted his balloons to articulate—to move and gesture—more like puppets. But how?\n\nWith a marionette, the controls are above and the puppet hangs down . . .\n\nBut what if the controls were below and the puppet could rise up?\n\nDuring the next year, Tony set his new idea into motion.\n\nThis time, he asked the company in Ohio to make balloons out of rubberized silk—as strong as rubber but lighter than rubber alone.\n\nMost important, Tony ordered the balloons to be filled not just with air but with helium too. Since helium is lighter than air, it would make the balloons rise.\n\nOnce the puppets were completed, they were deflated and shipped back to Tony in New York.\n\nTony did not know if everything would go as planned . . .\n\nIt was still dark on Thanksgiving morning when Tony filled the balloons with helium, tethering them down with sandbags.\n\nBy one p.m. the sidewalks were packed with people ready for the parade. Then, one by one, Tony cut the lines to the sandbags . . .\n\nLET’S have a PARADE!"},{"id":"P2","title":"Penguins and My Father''s Feet","text":"Penguins\nby Melvin and Gilda Berger\n\n1 Penguins live on the ice of the Antarctic. They have wings—yet they can’t fly! But the penguins are terrific swimmers and divers. They plunge into the icy ocean to catch their meals of fish, squid, and krill. Some can stay underwater for up to six minutes.\n\n2 After a long dive, penguins shoot up out of the water. They look like rockets being launched. The birds gulp a quick breath of air. Then they splash back down into the water.\n\n3 Sometimes the penguins leap onto the ice. Once there, penguins are slow and clumsy walkers. But they have a way to move quickly. They drop onto their bellies and push themselves forward with feet and flippers. ZOOM! Away they go, sliding across the ice!\n\n4 The biggest penguins of all are the emperor penguins. They are about as tall and heavy as third graders! Like other penguins, they spend most of their time diving for food. When it is time to nest, they jump out of the water and plop on the ice.\n\n5 Each female lays a single egg on the ice. Then she heads back to the water. Her mate rolls the egg onto his feet and covers it with a flap of skin. Then he joins other males in a large circle. They huddle together to keep warm.\n\n6 The males keep the eggs on their feet for a couple of months. During that time they do not eat. They lose about half their weight. Finally, the eggs hatch and the chicks are born.\n\n7 By now, the females are back. They take over the care of the chicks. The males march off to the ocean. There, they fill their empty stomachs with food.\n\n8 In a few weeks, the males return with food. Now both parents feed and protect their chicks. Six months later, the offspring are fully grown. Off they go. They’re big enough to care for themselves.\n\nMy Father’s Feet\n\nTo keep myself up off the ice,\nI find my father’s feet are nice.\nI snuggle in his belly fluff,\nAnd that’s how I stay warm enough.\n\n5 But when my father takes a walk,\nMy cozy world begins to rock.\nHe shuffles left, I hold on tight.\n\nOh no! He’s wobbling to the right.\nNot left again! Oops, here he goes.\n\n10 Do you suppose my father knows\nI’m hanging on to his warm toes?\n\n—Judy Sierra"}],"questions":[{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Based on the passage, why was Tony interested in marionettes?","options":["He liked to watch big parades.","He wanted to take care of animals.","He was curious about how things moved.","He was interested in writing puppet shows."],"diagram":null,"skill":"reading comprehension","id":"Q1","points":1,"passageId":"P1","difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"Tony was curious about how things moved, which is why he found marionettes interesting. They are puppets that move in a special way, and that made him want to learn more!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Based on paragraphs 2–4, what does the diagram mainly show?","options":["how the invention was like a puppet","why feeding chickens was a hard chore","how the invention was supposed to work","why feeding chickens was done in the morning"],"diagram":null,"skill":"reading comprehension","id":"Q2","points":1,"passageId":"P1","difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"The diagram mainly shows how the invention was supposed to work, helping us understand its purpose and how it functions. This is important because it explains the idea behind the invention clearly."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Read the sentence from paragraph 5 in the box below.\n\nWord soon spread about Tony’s amazing marionettes.\n\nWhat does the sentence suggest about Tony’s marionettes?","options":["They became very popular.","They became very expensive.","They were changed over the years.","They were copied by other people."],"diagram":null,"skill":"reading comprehension","id":"Q3","points":1,"passageId":"P1","difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"The sentence suggests that Tony’s marionettes became very popular because word spread about them, meaning many people wanted to see and talk about them!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Based on the passage, why did Macy’s decide to use puppets instead of live animals in the parade?","options":["Live animals bored some people.","Live animals scared some people.","Live animals cost too much to use.","Live animals became too tired to walk."],"diagram":null,"skill":"reading comprehension","id":"Q4","points":1,"passageId":"P1","difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"Macy’s decided to use puppets instead of live animals because some people were scared of the animals, making the parade more fun and safe for everyone."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Based on paragraph 21, why did Tony think the puppets needed to be bigger and fly higher?","options":["so that the puppets would look more real","so that people could see the puppets better","so that people could stand under the puppets","so that the puppets would look more beautiful"],"diagram":null,"skill":"reading comprehension","id":"Q5","points":1,"passageId":"P1","difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"Tony thought the puppets needed to be bigger and fly higher so that people could see them better from far away. This way, everyone could enjoy the show!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"What does the question in paragraph 23 mainly show?","options":["what Tony wrote","that Tony was upset","what Tony wondered","that Tony was confused"],"diagram":null,"skill":"reading comprehension","id":"Q6","points":1,"passageId":"P1","difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"The question in paragraph 23 mainly shows what Tony wondered about, which means he was thinking and curious about something important to him."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"In paragraph 28, how did Tony most likely feel?","options":["lonely","nervous","grumpy","disappointed"],"diagram":null,"skill":"reading comprehension","id":"Q7","points":1,"passageId":"P1","difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"In paragraph 28, Tony most likely felt nervous because he was probably anxious about how the parade would go and if everything would be okay."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Read the sentence from paragraph 30 in the box below.\n\nThen, one by one, Tony cut the lines to the sandbags . . .\n\nBased on the passage, what did Tony’s action show?","options":["The parade was late.","Tony was going home.","The parade was beginning.","Tony was popping the balloons."],"diagram":null,"skill":"reading comprehension","id":"Q8","points":1,"passageId":"P1","difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"When Tony cut the lines to the sandbags, it showed that the parade was beginning because that action was part of getting everything ready for the big event!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"In paragraph 7, what does “danced across the stage as if by magic” suggest about the marionettes?","options":["They seemed tired.","They seemed alive.","They moved loudly.","They moved quickly."],"diagram":null,"skill":"reading comprehension","id":"Q9","points":1,"passageId":"P1","difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"The phrase ''danced across the stage as if by magic'' suggests that the marionettes seemed alive because they moved in a way that looked magical and lively, capturing everyone’s attention!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Read paragraph 12 in the box below.\n\nIn fact, Macy’s first parade was such a success that they decided to have one every year on Thanksgiving Day—to celebrate America’s own holiday.\n\nIn the paragraph, which of the following words is a noun?","options":["such","decided","every","holiday"],"diagram":null,"skill":"grammar","id":"Q10","points":1,"passageId":"P1","difficulty":"medium","answer":3,"explanation":"In the paragraph, the word ''holiday'' is a noun because it names a special day, while the other words are not nouns. Nouns are names of people, places, or things, and ''holiday'' fits that description perfectly!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Based on paragraph 2 of the article, why do penguins “shoot up out of the water”?","options":["to hide","to hunt","to breathe","to exercise"],"diagram":null,"skill":"Reading comprehension","id":"Q11","points":1,"passageId":"P2","difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"Penguins shoot up out of the water to breathe because they need air after swimming underwater. Just like we come up for air when we swim, penguins do the same!"},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Based on the article, which would be the best heading for paragraphs 1–3?","options":["Big Birds","On the Move","On Their Own","A Meal Fit for a King"],"diagram":null,"skill":"Identifying main idea","id":"Q12","points":1,"passageId":"P2","difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"The best heading for paragraphs 1–3 is ''On the Move'' because those paragraphs talk about how penguins travel and move around, especially when they are swimming or walking."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Based on the article, which of the following happens last?","options":["The female penguin lays an egg.","The male penguin goes to the ocean to eat.","The male penguin protects the egg with his feet.","The female penguin comes back from the ocean."],"diagram":null,"skill":"Sequence of events","id":"Q13","points":1,"passageId":"P2","difficulty":"medium","answer":1,"explanation":"The last thing that happens is the male penguin goes to the ocean to eat. This happens after the female lays the egg and after he has been protecting it, so it comes last in the order of events."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Based on the article and the poem, why do male penguins put their eggs and chicks on their feet?","options":["The ice is very cold.","The sun is very bright.","The young penguins are shy.","The other penguins are dangerous."],"diagram":null,"skill":"Understanding details","id":"Q14","points":1,"passageId":"P2","difficulty":"medium","answer":0,"explanation":"Male penguins put their eggs and chicks on their feet because the ice is very cold. This helps keep the eggs and chicks warm and safe from the freezing temperatures."},{"itemType":"single_choice","questionText":"Read the sentence from paragraph 1 of the article in the box below.\n\n\"They plunge into the icy ocean to catch their meals of fish, squid, and krill.\"\n\nBased on the article, which word could be used instead of plunge?","options":["fly","turn","dive","look"],"diagram":null,"skill":"Vocabulary context","id":"Q15","points":1,"passageId":"P2","difficulty":"medium","answer":2,"explanation":"The word ''dive'' can be used instead of ''plunge'' because both words mean to jump into the water quickly. When penguins dive, they go underwater to catch their food."}]}');
INSERT INTO "tests" ("id","grade","subject","test_type","title","time_limit_minutes","question_count","source","created_at","data") VALUES('g5-math-eog-1',5,'math','eog','Grade 5 Math — EOG Practice Test 1',120,40,'curated','2026-06-02T00:00:00.000Z','{"id":"g5-math-eog-1","grade":5,"subject":"math","testType":"eog","title":"Grade 5 Math — EOG Practice Test 1","instructions":"Read each question carefully. For multiple-choice questions, choose the one best answer. For ''select all that apply'' questions, choose every correct answer. For numeric-entry questions, write your answer as a number. For fill-in-the-blank equations, write the number that makes the equation true. Calculators are NOT allowed. You have 120 minutes.","timeLimitMinutes":120,"calculatorAllowed":false,"source":"curated","passages":[],"questions":[{"id":"Q1","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"NF.5.1 add fractions unlike denominators","difficulty":"easy","questionText":"What is the value of 1/2 + 1/3?","diagram":{"type":"fraction_bar","params":{"bars":[{"parts":2,"shaded":1,"label":"1/2"},{"parts":3,"shaded":1,"label":"1/3"}]}},"options":["2/5","5/6","2/6","1/6"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Common denominator 6: 1/2 = 3/6 and 1/3 = 2/6. 3/6 + 2/6 = 5/6. The distractor 2/5 incorrectly adds numerators and denominators.","points":1},{"id":"Q2","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"NF.5.1 subtract fractions unlike denominators","difficulty":"medium","questionText":"What is the value of 5/6 − 1/4?","diagram":null,"options":["4/2","4/12","7/12","1/2"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Common denominator 12: 5/6 = 10/12 and 1/4 = 3/12. 10/12 − 3/12 = 7/12. The distractor 4/2 subtracts numerators and denominators separately.","points":1},{"id":"Q3","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"NF.5.2 add mixed numbers word problem","difficulty":"hard","questionText":"A recipe uses 2 1/3 cups of flour for bread and 1 1/2 cups for muffins. How many cups of flour are used in all?","diagram":null,"options":["3 1/6 cups","4 5/6 cups","3 5/6 cups","3 2/5 cups"],"answer":2,"explanation":"2 1/3 + 1 1/2. Common denominator 6: 1/3 = 2/6 and 1/2 = 3/6, so 2/6 + 3/6 = 5/6. Whole numbers 2 + 1 = 3. Total = 3 5/6 cups. The distractor 3 2/5 adds numerators and denominators.","points":1},{"id":"Q4","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"NF.5.1 subtract mixed numbers with regrouping","difficulty":"hard","questionText":"Maria has 4 1/4 yards of ribbon. She uses 1 2/3 yards. How many yards of ribbon are left? Enter your answer as a decimal rounded to the nearest hundredth.","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":2.58,"explanation":"4 1/4 − 1 2/3. Common denominator 12: 4 3/12 − 1 8/12. Since 3/12 < 8/12, regroup: 4 3/12 = 3 15/12. Then 3 15/12 − 1 8/12 = 2 7/12. As a decimal, 7/12 = 0.5833..., so 2 7/12 ≈ 2.58 yards.","points":1},{"id":"Q5","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"NF.5.4 multiply fraction by fraction","difficulty":"medium","questionText":"What is the value of 2/3 × 3/4?","diagram":{"type":"rectangle","params":{"width":4,"height":3,"unit":"unit","showGrid":true,"label":"2/3 of 3/4 shaded"}},"options":["5/7","5/12","6/7","1/2"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Multiply numerators and denominators: (2×3)/(3×4) = 6/12 = 1/2. The distractor 6/7 adds instead of multiplying.","points":1},{"id":"Q6","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"NF.5.4 multiply fraction by whole number","difficulty":"easy","questionText":"What is the value of 3/5 × 10?","diagram":{"type":"fraction_bar","params":{"parts":5,"shaded":3}},"options":["6","13/5","3/50","30"],"answer":0,"explanation":"3/5 × 10 = 30/5 = 6. The distractor 30 multiplies only the numerator by 10 without dividing.","points":1},{"id":"Q7","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"NF.5.4 multiply mixed number, area","difficulty":"hard","questionText":"A rectangular garden is 4 1/2 feet long and 2/3 foot wide. What is the area of the garden in square feet?","diagram":{"type":"rectangle","params":{"width":9,"height":2,"unit":"ft","showGrid":false,"label":"4 1/2 ft by 2/3 ft"}},"options":["5 1/6 sq ft","9 sq ft","3 sq ft","6 sq ft"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Area = length × width = 4 1/2 × 2/3 = 9/2 × 2/3 = 18/6 = 3 square feet. The distractor 5 1/6 adds the two dimensions.","points":1},{"id":"Q8","itemType":"equation","skill":"NF.5.1 add fractions unlike denominators","difficulty":"medium","questionText":"Fill in the blank to make the equation true. Write your answer as a fraction.","template":"3/4 + ▢ = 5/4","answer":"1/2","options":[],"explanation":"5/4 − 3/4 = 2/4 = 1/2. So ▢ = 1/2 (equivalent to 2/4).","points":1},{"id":"Q9","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"NF.5.7 divide fractions reasoning","difficulty":"hard","questionText":"Select ALL expressions that have a value of 1/12.","diagram":{"type":"fraction_bar","params":{"parts":12,"shaded":1}},"options":["1/4 ÷ 3","1/3 ÷ 4","1/6 ÷ 2","1/2 ÷ 6"],"answer":[0,1,2,3],"explanation":"1/4 ÷ 3 = 1/12 ✓. 1/3 ÷ 4 = 1/12 ✓. 1/2 ÷ 6 = 1/12 ✓. 1/6 ÷ 2 = 1/12 ✓. Each divides a unit fraction so the denominator becomes 12.","points":1},{"id":"Q10","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"NF.5.7 divide whole number by unit fraction","difficulty":"hard","questionText":"Tom has 5 cups of trail mix. He puts 1/3 cup into each small bag. How many small bags can he fill?","diagram":null,"options":["8 bags","15 bags","5/3 bags","1 2/3 bags"],"answer":1,"explanation":"5 ÷ 1/3 = 5 × 3 = 15 bags. Each cup makes 3 bags, and 5 cups make 15 bags. The distractor 5/3 multiplies by 1/3 instead of dividing.","points":1},{"id":"Q11","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"NF.5.7 divide unit fraction reasoning","difficulty":"hard","questionText":"A piece of rope is 1/2 meter long. It is cut into pieces that are each 1/8 meter long. How many pieces are made? Enter your answer as a whole number.","diagram":{"type":"number_line","params":{"min":0,"max":1,"step":0.125,"point":0.5}},"options":[],"answer":4,"explanation":"1/2 ÷ 1/8 = 1/2 × 8/1 = 8/2 = 4 pieces. On a number line, 1/2 = 4/8, so there are four 1/8 segments.","points":1},{"id":"Q12","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"NF.5.1 equivalent sums","difficulty":"hard","questionText":"Select ALL expressions that have a value equal to 3/4.","diagram":null,"options":["2/3 + 1/12","1/4 + 1/4 + 1/4","1/2 + 1/4","1/2 + 1/3"],"answer":[0,1,2],"explanation":"1/4 + 1/4 + 1/4 = 3/4 ✓. 1/2 + 1/4 = 2/4 + 1/4 = 3/4 ✓. 2/3 + 1/12 = 8/12 + 1/12 = 9/12 = 3/4 ✓. 1/2 + 1/3 = 3/6 + 2/6 = 5/6 ≠ 3/4 ✗.","points":1},{"id":"Q13","itemType":"equation","skill":"NF.5.4 multiply fraction by whole number","difficulty":"medium","questionText":"Fill in the blank to make the equation true. Write your answer as a whole number.","template":"2/3 × ▢ = 8","answer":12,"options":[],"explanation":"2/3 × ▢ = 8 means ▢ = 8 ÷ (2/3) = 8 × 3/2 = 24/2 = 12. Check: 2/3 × 12 = 24/3 = 8.","points":1},{"id":"Q14","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"NF.5.1 subtract fractions","difficulty":"easy","questionText":"What is the value of 7/10 − 2/5?","diagram":{"type":"fraction_bar","params":{"bars":[{"parts":10,"shaded":7,"label":"7/10"},{"parts":5,"shaded":2,"label":"2/5"}]}},"options":["5/5","1/2","9/10","3/10"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Common denominator 10: 2/5 = 4/10, so 7/10 − 4/10 = 3/10. The distractor 5/5 subtracts numerators and denominators (7−2 over 10−5).","points":1},{"id":"Q15","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"NF.5.4 fraction of a set","difficulty":"medium","questionText":"A class has 24 students. 3/8 of the students walk to school. How many students walk to school? Enter your answer as a whole number.","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":9,"explanation":"3/8 × 24 = (3 × 24)/8 = 72/8 = 9 students.","points":1},{"id":"Q16","itemType":"equation","skill":"NF.5.6 multiply mixed number","difficulty":"hard","questionText":"Fill in the blank to make the equation true. Write your answer as a whole number.","template":"▢ × 1/2 = 3 1/2","answer":7,"options":[],"explanation":"▢ × 1/2 = 3 1/2 = 7/2. So ▢ = (7/2) ÷ (1/2) = 7/2 × 2 = 7. Check: 7 × 1/2 = 7/2 = 3 1/2.","points":1},{"id":"Q17","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"NBT.5.1 place value to thousandths","difficulty":"easy","questionText":"In the number 4.736, what is the value of the digit 3?","diagram":null,"options":["3 hundredths","3 ones","3 tenths","3 thousandths"],"answer":0,"explanation":"In 4.736, the digit 3 is in the hundredths place, so its value is 3 hundredths (0.03). The 7 is tenths and 6 is thousandths.","points":1},{"id":"Q18","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"NBT.5.2 powers of 10","difficulty":"medium","questionText":"What is the value of 3.5 × 10³?","diagram":null,"options":["35,000","35","350","3,500"],"answer":3,"explanation":"10³ = 1,000, so 3.5 × 1,000 = 3,500. The decimal point moves 3 places to the right. The distractor 35 moves only one place.","points":1},{"id":"Q19","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"NBT.5.7 add decimals","difficulty":"easy","questionText":"What is the value of 2.45 + 1.7?","diagram":null,"options":["2.62","4.15","3.52","16.2"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Align decimals: 2.45 + 1.70 = 4.15. The distractor 2.62 misaligns (2.45 + 0.17).","points":1},{"id":"Q20","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"NBT.5.7 multiply decimals","difficulty":"hard","questionText":"What is the value of 0.6 × 0.4?","diagram":null,"options":["0.24","2.4","1.0","0.024"],"answer":0,"explanation":"6 × 4 = 24, and there are two decimal places total (one in each factor), so 0.6 × 0.4 = 0.24. The distractor 2.4 misplaces the decimal by one position.","points":1},{"id":"Q21","itemType":"equation","skill":"NBT.5.7 multiply decimals","difficulty":"medium","questionText":"Fill in the blank to make the equation true.","template":"▢ × 0.6 = 4.8","answer":8,"options":[],"explanation":"▢ = 4.8 ÷ 0.6 = 8. Check: 8 × 0.6 = 4.8.","points":1},{"id":"Q22","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"NBT.5.7 divide decimals","difficulty":"medium","questionText":"What is the value of 4.5 ÷ 9?","diagram":null,"options":["5","50","0.5","0.05"],"answer":2,"explanation":"4.5 ÷ 9 = 0.5. Check: 0.5 × 9 = 4.5. The distractor 5 ignores the decimal.","points":1},{"id":"Q23","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"NBT.5.6 divide 4-digit by 2-digit","difficulty":"hard","questionText":"A factory packs 1,288 markers into boxes of 23 markers each. How many full boxes can be packed? Enter your answer as a whole number.","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":56,"explanation":"1,288 ÷ 23 = 56 exactly (23 × 56 = 1,288). So 56 full boxes can be packed.","points":1},{"id":"Q24","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"NBT.5.4 round decimals","difficulty":"medium","questionText":"What is 7.165 rounded to the nearest hundredth?","diagram":null,"options":["7.20","7.1","7.16","7.17"],"answer":3,"explanation":"The thousandths digit is 5, so round the hundredths digit up: 7.165 → 7.17. The distractor 7.16 incorrectly rounds down.","points":1},{"id":"Q25","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"NBT.5.1 place value relationships","difficulty":"hard","questionText":"Select ALL statements that are TRUE.","diagram":null,"options":["In 22, the left 2 is 100 times the right 2.","In 0.77, the 7 in the hundredths place is 1/10 of the 7 in the tenths place.","In 4.4, the 4 in the ones place is 10 times the 4 in the tenths place.","In 55.5, the 5 in the tens place is 10 times the 5 in the ones place."],"answer":[1,2,3],"explanation":"Each place is 10 times the place to its right and 1/10 of the place to its left. Tens is 10× ones ✓; hundredths is 1/10 of tenths ✓; ones is 10× tenths ✓. In 22, the left 2 is 10 times (not 100 times) the right 2 ✗.","points":1},{"id":"Q26","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"NBT.5.7 multi-step decimals","difficulty":"hard","questionText":"A runner buys 3 energy bars at $1.25 each and a bottle of water for $0.95. What is the total cost in dollars? Enter your answer as a decimal.","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":4.7,"explanation":"3 × $1.25 = $3.75. Then $3.75 + $0.95 = $4.70.","points":1},{"id":"Q27","itemType":"equation","skill":"NBT.5.6 division base ten","difficulty":"easy","questionText":"Fill in the blank to make the equation true.","template":"▢ ÷ 12 = 8","answer":96,"options":[],"explanation":"▢ = 8 × 12 = 96. Check: 96 ÷ 12 = 8.","points":1},{"id":"Q28","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"MD.5.5 volume of rectangular prism","difficulty":"easy","questionText":"A rectangular box has a length of 5 cm, a width of 3 cm, and a height of 4 cm. What is the volume of the box?","diagram":{"type":"rectangle","params":{"width":5,"height":3,"unit":"cm","showGrid":true,"label":"base 5 cm by 3 cm, height 4 cm"}},"options":["47 cubic cm","60 cubic cm","12 cubic cm","23 cubic cm"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Volume = length × width × height = 5 × 3 × 4 = 60 cubic cm. The distractor 47 comes from a surface-area mix-up.","points":1},{"id":"Q29","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"MD.5.5 volume word problem","difficulty":"hard","questionText":"A storage bin is 8 inches long, 5 inches wide, and 6 inches tall. A second bin has the same length and width but is only 2 inches tall. How much GREATER is the volume of the first bin than the second, in cubic inches?","diagram":null,"options":["80 cubic inches","320 cubic inches","160 cubic inches","240 cubic inches"],"answer":2,"explanation":"First bin: 8×5×6 = 240. Second bin: 8×5×2 = 80. Difference: 240 − 80 = 160 cubic inches. (Or 8×5×4 = 160.) The distractor 240 is the first bin''s volume.","points":1},{"id":"Q30","itemType":"numeric_entry","skill":"MD.5.5 volume with missing dimension","difficulty":"hard","questionText":"A rectangular fish tank has a volume of 144 cubic inches. Its base is 6 inches long and 4 inches wide. What is the height of the tank, in inches? Enter your answer as a whole number.","diagram":null,"options":[],"answer":6,"explanation":"Volume = L × W × H, so 144 = 6 × 4 × H = 24 × H. Therefore H = 144 ÷ 24 = 6 inches.","points":1},{"id":"Q31","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"MD.5.1 multi-step unit conversion","difficulty":"hard","questionText":"A jug holds 2 liters of juice. Mia pours the juice into glasses that each hold 250 milliliters. How many glasses can she completely fill? (1 liter = 1,000 milliliters)","diagram":null,"options":["4 glasses","20 glasses","8 glasses","5 glasses"],"answer":2,"explanation":"2 liters = 2,000 milliliters. 2,000 ÷ 250 = 8 glasses. The distractor 4 forgets to convert and does 1,000 ÷ 250.","points":1},{"id":"Q32","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"MD.5.2 line plot with fractions","difficulty":"hard","questionText":"The data table represents a line plot of ribbon lengths measured to the nearest quarter inch. What is the TOTAL length of all the ribbons combined?","diagram":{"type":"data_table","params":{"headers":["Length (inches)","Number of ribbons"],"rows":[["1/4","2"],["1/2","3"],["3/4","1"]]}},"options":["2 3/4 inches","6 inches","1 1/2 inches","3 inches"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Total = 2×(1/4) + 3×(1/2) + 1×(3/4) = 2/4 + 6/4 + 3/4 = 11/4 = 2 3/4 inches. The distractor 1 1/2 just counts ribbons above 1/4.","points":1},{"id":"Q33","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"MD.5.2 line plot interpretation","difficulty":"medium","questionText":"Use the line-plot data table to answer. Select ALL statements that are TRUE.","diagram":{"type":"data_table","params":{"headers":["Length (inches)","Number of ribbons"],"rows":[["1/4","2"],["1/2","3"],["3/4","1"]]}},"options":["The most common length is 1/2 inch.","More ribbons are 3/4 inch long than 1/4 inch long.","There are 6 ribbons in all.","There are twice as many 1/4-inch ribbons as 3/4-inch ribbons."],"answer":[0,2,3],"explanation":"Total ribbons: 2 + 3 + 1 = 6 ✓. The 1/2-inch length has the most (3) ✓. There are 2 ribbons of 1/4 inch and 1 of 3/4 inch, so 2 = 2×1, twice as many ✓; and 3/4 inch has FEWER, not more, than 1/4 inch ✗.","points":1},{"id":"Q34","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"MD.5.1 unit conversion","difficulty":"medium","questionText":"A rope is 3.5 meters long. How many centimeters long is the rope? (1 meter = 100 centimeters)","diagram":null,"options":["0.035 cm","3,500 cm","35 cm","350 cm"],"answer":3,"explanation":"3.5 meters × 100 = 350 centimeters. The distractor 35 multiplies by 10 instead of 100.","points":1},{"id":"Q35","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"G.5.1 coordinate plane ordered pairs","difficulty":"medium","questionText":"On a coordinate grid, a point is located 4 units to the right of the origin and 2 units up. Which ordered pair names this point?","diagram":{"type":"data_table","params":{"headers":["Direction","Units"],"rows":[["Right (x)","4"],["Up (y)","2"]]}},"options":["(0, 6)","(4, 2)","(2, 4)","(6, 0)"],"answer":1,"explanation":"An ordered pair is (x, y): x is horizontal, y is vertical. Right 4 and up 2 gives (4, 2). The distractor (2, 4) reverses the coordinates.","points":1},{"id":"Q36","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"G.5.3 classify 2-D figures hierarchy","difficulty":"hard","questionText":"Which statement is ALWAYS true?","diagram":null,"options":["Every rhombus is a rectangle.","Every square is a rectangle.","Every trapezoid is a parallelogram.","Every rectangle is a square."],"answer":1,"explanation":"A square has four right angles and opposite sides parallel and equal, so every square fits the definition of a rectangle. Not every rectangle is a square, and a rhombus need not have right angles.","points":1},{"id":"Q37","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"OA.5.1 order of operations","difficulty":"hard","questionText":"What is the value of 3 + 4 × (6 − 2)?","diagram":null,"options":["19","21","25","28"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Parentheses first: 6 − 2 = 4. Then 4 × 4 = 16. Then 3 + 16 = 19. The distractor 28 comes from adding before multiplying: (3+4)×4.","points":1},{"id":"Q38","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"OA.5.2 write/interpret expressions","difficulty":"medium","questionText":"Which expression means ''add 8 and 5, then multiply the result by 3''?","diagram":null,"options":["3 × (8 + 5)","8 + (5 × 3)","8 + 5 × 3","(3 × 8) + 5"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Adding 8 and 5 first requires parentheses, then multiplying by 3: 3 × (8 + 5). The distractor 8 + 5 × 3 multiplies 5 by 3 first because of order of operations.","points":1},{"id":"Q39","itemType":"equation","skill":"OA.5.1 order of operations","difficulty":"hard","questionText":"Fill in the blank to make the equation true.","template":"2 × (5 + ▢) = 24","answer":7,"options":[],"explanation":"2 × (5 + ▢) = 24 means 5 + ▢ = 12, so ▢ = 7. Check: 2 × (5 + 7) = 2 × 12 = 24.","points":1},{"id":"Q40","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"OA.5.3 generate and compare patterns","difficulty":"hard","questionText":"Pattern A starts at 0 and adds 3 each time: 0, 3, 6, 9, ... Pattern B starts at 0 and adds 6 each time: 0, 6, 12, 18, ... Select ALL statements that are TRUE about the patterns.","diagram":{"type":"data_table","params":{"headers":["Term","Pattern A (+3)","Pattern B (+6)"],"rows":[["1st","0","0"],["2nd","3","6"],["3rd","6","12"],["4th","9","18"]]}},"options":["Both patterns will always have the same value at each term.","The ordered pair (9, 18) shows the 4th terms of Pattern A and Pattern B.","Each term in Pattern B is twice the matching term in Pattern A.","Each term in Pattern A is twice the matching term in Pattern B."],"answer":[1,2],"explanation":"Each Pattern B term is twice the matching Pattern A term: 6=2×3, 12=2×6, 18=2×9 ✓. Pattern A is half (not twice) Pattern B ✗. The 4th terms are A=9, B=18 → (9, 18) ✓. They are equal only at the first term ✗.","points":1}]}');
INSERT INTO "tests" ("id","grade","subject","test_type","title","time_limit_minutes","question_count","source","created_at","data") VALUES('g5-read-eog-1',5,'reading','eog','Grade 5 Reading — EOG Practice Test 1',120,40,'curated','2026-06-02T00:00:00.000Z','{"id":"g5-read-eog-1","grade":5,"subject":"reading","testType":"eog","title":"Grade 5 Reading — EOG Practice Test 1","instructions":"Read each selection carefully. Then answer the questions that follow. For each question, choose the best answer based on what the selection states or implies. Some questions may ask you to select two answers. You have 120 minutes to complete this test.","timeLimitMinutes":120,"calculatorAllowed":false,"source":"curated","passages":[{"id":"P1","title":"The Last Tomato","genre":"realistic fiction","lexile":"820L","text":"Maya had checked the garden every single morning for three weeks, and every single morning the tomato vine offered her the same answer: not yet. The plant her grandmother had given her in May was tall now, taller than Maya herself, and it leaned against the wooden stake like a tired old man. Green tomatoes hung from it like little hard fists. Maya wanted, more than anything, to bring her grandmother one perfect red tomato before she moved away at the end of the summer.\n\n\"You can''t rush a tomato,\" Grandma Rosa always said, laughing, her hands deep in the soil. \"A tomato ripens when it is ready, not when you are ready.\" But Maya was not good at waiting. She measured the tomatoes with her fingers. She whispered to them. Once, when no one was watching, she even tried painting a green tomato red with a marker, until Grandma Rosa caught her and laughed so hard she had to sit down on the back steps.\n\nThen came the storm. It arrived on a Thursday afternoon with no warning, slamming the screen door and bending the trees sideways. Maya watched from the kitchen window, her stomach twisting, as the wind shoved her tomato plant back and forth. When the rain finally stopped, she ran outside in her socks. The stake had snapped. The vine lay flat in the mud, and most of the tomatoes had been knocked loose and split open on the ground.\n\nBut one tomato remained. It hung at the very top of the broken vine, and as Maya knelt in the wet dirt, she saw that it had turned, overnight, a deep and glowing red. It was not a perfect tomato. One side was a little flat, and there was a small scar near the stem where a branch had scratched it. Maya cupped it in both hands as if it were made of glass.\n\nThat evening she carried it inside on a white plate and set it in front of her grandmother. Grandma Rosa looked at the lopsided, scarred tomato for a long moment. Then she looked at Maya, and her eyes were shining. \"This,\" she said quietly, \"is the most beautiful tomato I have ever seen.\" Maya started to explain about the storm, about how it wasn''t perfect, but her grandmother shook her head. \"The waiting is part of it,\" she said. \"And so is the storm. That is how you know it is real.\"\n\nMaya did not fully understand what her grandmother meant, not that night. But years later, long after Grandma Rosa had moved away and the garden had been planted with new things, Maya would stand at her own kitchen window during a storm, watching the wind move through a vine she had grown herself, and she would finally understand."},{"id":"P2","title":"How the Coyote Brought Fire","genre":"legend","lexile":"850L","text":"Long ago, the people of the valley had no fire. In the cold months they shivered in their homes, eating their food uncooked, watching their breath rise like smoke that gave no warmth. They knew that fire existed, for far away on the top of the great mountain lived three Fire Beings who guarded it jealously. The Fire Beings never slept all at once. One of them always kept watch over the flames, and they shrieked with anger whenever any creature came near.\n\nCoyote, who was clever and curious and a little bit foolish, grew tired of watching the people suffer. \"I will bring you fire,\" he announced, though no one had asked him to. The wise old woman of the village only shook her head. \"Many have tried,\" she said. \"None have returned.\" But Coyote had a plan, and Coyote''s plans were always either very good or very bad, and sometimes both at once.\n\nHe climbed the great mountain and watched the Fire Beings for three days, hidden among the rocks. He noticed something the others had missed: at dawn, when the watch changed from one Fire Being to the next, there was a single moment when both were awake but neither was truly watching the fire. It was the smallest of openings. Coyote also knew he could not carry the fire alone, so he visited the other animals and asked each one to wait along the mountainside, ready to run.\n\nWhen the gray light of dawn came, Coyote darted forward, seized a glowing branch in his teeth, and ran. The Fire Beings screamed and gave chase, their cries shaking loose stones from the mountain. Coyote ran until his legs burned, then flung the branch to Squirrel, who caught it on her back. The fire scorched her so badly that her tail curled up over her body, the way a squirrel''s tail still curls today. Squirrel ran and passed the fire to Chipmunk, who was scratched by a Fire Being''s claw, leaving three pale stripes down her back that her children wear to this day.\n\nOn and on the fire traveled, from animal to animal, each one carrying it a little farther and each one marked forever by the journey. At last Frog took the fire, but the Fire Beings were close, and they grabbed his tail. Frog gave a mighty leap and escaped, but his tail stayed behind in their hands, which is why frogs have no tails. Frog spat the fire into a tree, and the fire sank deep into the wood and hid there.\n\nThe Fire Beings searched and searched, but they could not pull the fire out of the tree, and at last they returned to their mountain in defeat. Then Coyote showed the people how to rub two dry sticks of that tree together until the hidden fire woke and leaped out. From that day on, the people had fire to warm their homes and cook their food. And though Coyote never asked for thanks, the people remembered, and they tell his story still."},{"id":"P3","title":"The Hidden World of Soil","genre":"informational","lexile":"910L","text":"When you walk across a field or a forest floor, you are stepping on one of the most crowded places on Earth. A single handful of healthy soil can contain more living organisms than there are people on the entire planet. Most of these living things are far too small to see, yet without them, life as we know it could not exist.\n\nSoil is not simply dirt. It is a complex mixture of broken-down rock, water, air, and living and dead material. It forms slowly, over hundreds or even thousands of years, as rock is worn down by wind, water, and the roots of plants. Dead leaves, insects, and animals are mixed in and broken apart. The result is a living system that feeds the plants we depend on for food.\n\nThe most important workers in the soil are also some of the smallest. Bacteria and fungi break down dead plants and animals into nutrients that growing plants can absorb through their roots. Without these tiny decomposers, dead material would pile up endlessly, and the nutrients trapped inside it would never be returned to the soil. In this way, the smallest creatures make the largest forests possible.\n\nEarthworms play a different but equally important role. As an earthworm tunnels through the ground, it swallows soil, digests the bits of dead material inside, and leaves behind waste that is rich in nutrients. Its tunnels also loosen the soil, allowing air and water to reach plant roots more easily. A single earthworm may seem unimportant, but a healthy field can contain a million earthworms in a single acre, and together they can move tons of soil each year.\n\nUnfortunately, soil is in danger. When forests are cleared or farmland is left bare, rain and wind can carry away the rich top layer of soil, called topsoil. This process is known as erosion. Topsoil that took a thousand years to form can be washed away in a single season. Around the world, soil is being lost far faster than nature can replace it, and scientists warn that this loss threatens our ability to grow enough food.\n\nThe good news is that people are learning to protect the soil. Farmers can plant cover crops that hold the soil in place between growing seasons. They can plow less often, leaving the soil undisturbed and full of life. They can plant trees whose roots anchor the ground against wind and water. Protecting soil is not only about saving dirt. It is about protecting the hidden, crowded, living world beneath our feet, the world that quietly makes all other life possible."},{"id":"P4","title":"The Girl Who Mapped the Stars","genre":"biography","lexile":"870L","text":"In the late 1800s, the doors of science were closed to most women. Few were allowed to attend universities, and even fewer were given the chance to do real scientific work. Yet at the Harvard College Observatory, a remarkable group of women spent their days studying the stars, and one of them, Henrietta Swan Leavitt, would change the way humans measure the universe.\n\nLeavitt was born in 1868 and loved astronomy from a young age. After college, she began working at the observatory, where she was hired as a \"computer.\" This did not mean she worked with machines. In those days, a computer was a person who performed careful, repeated calculations by hand. Leavitt''s job was to study photographs of the night sky and measure the brightness of thousands upon thousands of stars. It was slow, demanding work, and she was paid only a few cents an hour.\n\nLeavitt became especially interested in a type of star that does not shine steadily but instead grows brighter and dimmer over a regular cycle. These stars are called variable stars. By comparing photographs taken on different nights, Leavitt patiently tracked how the brightness of each star changed over time. She measured more than a thousand of these variable stars, far more than anyone before her.\n\nThen Leavitt noticed something that no one else had seen. Among a certain group of variable stars, the ones that were brighter took longer to complete their cycle of dimming and brightening. The dimmer stars cycled quickly; the brighter stars cycled slowly. The relationship was steady and predictable. This meant that if astronomers measured how long a star''s cycle lasted, they could figure out how bright the star truly was, and from that, they could calculate how far away it was.\n\nThis discovery, known today as Leavitt''s Law, gave astronomers their first reliable way to measure great distances in space. Before Leavitt, no one could say with confidence how far away the distant stars were. After her, astronomers had a kind of cosmic measuring stick. A few years later, a scientist named Edwin Hubble used Leavitt''s discovery to prove that the universe is far larger than anyone had imagined, containing countless galaxies beyond our own.\n\nHenrietta Leavitt did not live to receive the honors she deserved. She died in 1921, and much of the credit for the discoveries her work made possible went to the men who came after her. Yet today, scientists recognize that the modern understanding of the universe rests, in part, on the patient work of a woman who counted the changing light of the stars, one photograph at a time."},{"id":"P5","title":"The Old Oak","genre":"poetry","lexile":"780L","text":"I have stood here a hundred years,\nmy roots like fingers gripping stone,\nand I have watched the seasons turn\nwhile children grew and then were grown.\n\nIn spring I wear a coat of green,\nin summer, shade for those below—\nthe farmer resting in my arms,\nthe lovers carving names I know.\n\nThe autumn sets my leaves on fire,\na thousand torches, gold and red,\nthat one by one let go their hold\nand make a blanket for my bed.\n\nThen winter strips me to my bones.\nI stand alone against the sky,\nbut I am not afraid of cold—\nI know that spring is drawing nigh.\n\nThe lightning split my oldest branch;\nthe storms have bent me, year by year.\nAnd yet I am not made of fear—\nI am made of standing here.\n\nSo when the small ones ask me how\na tree can live so long, so tall,\nI tell them: bend, but do not break,\nand answer green to winter''s call."}],"questions":[{"id":"Q1","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.5.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"What is a theme of \"The Last Tomato\"?","diagram":null,"options":["Grandparents know more about gardening than children do.","Storms always destroy the things we work hardest to grow.","True value comes from waiting through hardship, not from perfection.","It is foolish to grow tomatoes in a place that has storms."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Grandma Rosa says the waiting and the storm are ''how you know it is real,'' and Maya later understands this, showing the theme that worth comes from patience and struggle rather than perfection. The scarred tomato being called ''the most beautiful'' supports this.","points":1},{"id":"Q2","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.5.6","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"From whose point of view is the story told?","diagram":null,"options":["The tomato plant''s, in the first person","Grandma Rosa''s, in the first person","A neighbor who watches Maya''s garden","Maya''s, through a narrator outside the story"],"answer":3,"explanation":"The story is told by a third-person narrator who follows Maya''s thoughts and feelings (''her stomach twisting,'' ''Maya did not fully understand''), so events are seen mainly through Maya''s perspective but not in her own voice.","points":1},{"id":"Q3","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.5.4","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Read this sentence from the passage: \"Green tomatoes hung from it like little hard fists.\" What does this comparison suggest about the tomatoes?","diagram":null,"options":["They were still tight, unripe, and not ready.","They were angry at Maya for rushing them.","They were soft and ready to be picked.","They were so heavy they pulled the vine down."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Comparing the green tomatoes to ''little hard fists'' emphasizes that they are closed up, hard, and unripe — matching the plant''s repeated answer of ''not yet.''","points":1},{"id":"Q4","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.5.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Which detail best supports the idea that Maya was impatient?","diagram":null,"options":["She carried the tomato inside on a white plate.","She watched the storm from the kitchen window.","She tried painting a green tomato red with a marker.","She checked the garden every morning for three weeks."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Trying to paint a green tomato red shows Maya could not wait for it to ripen naturally, directly supporting that she was impatient. Checking daily shows interest, but painting it red shows impatience most clearly.","points":1},{"id":"Q5","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.5.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P1","questionText":"How does Maya change from the beginning of the story to the end?","diagram":null,"options":["She moves from fearing storms to causing them.","She moves from rushing things to understanding the value of waiting.","She moves from enjoying gardening to disliking it.","She moves from loving her grandmother to forgetting her."],"answer":1,"explanation":"At the start Maya rushes the tomatoes and cannot wait; by the end she ''finally understands'' what her grandmother meant about waiting and storms, showing her growth.","points":1},{"id":"Q6","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.5.4","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Read this sentence: \"Maya cupped it in both hands as if it were made of glass.\" What does the phrase \"as if it were made of glass\" suggest about how Maya felt about the tomato?","diagram":null,"options":["She treated the tomato as precious and fragile.","She thought the tomato was cold and smooth.","She believed the tomato was fake.","She was afraid the tomato would cut her."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Holding something ''as if it were made of glass'' means handling it gently and carefully because it is precious and breakable — showing how much the tomato meant to Maya.","points":1},{"id":"Q7","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.5.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Why does Grandma Rosa call the scarred, lopsided tomato \"the most beautiful tomato I have ever seen\"?","diagram":null,"options":["She is teasing Maya for bringing an imperfect tomato.","She cannot see the tomato''s flaws clearly.","She has never seen a red tomato before.","She values the love and struggle behind it more than its looks."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Grandma Rosa explains that ''the waiting is part of it'' and ''so is the storm,'' showing she values the effort and meaning behind the tomato, not its appearance.","points":1},{"id":"Q8","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"RL.5.3","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"Select two details that show the storm was an important turning point in the story.","diagram":null,"options":["Grandma Rosa gave Maya the plant in May.","Maya measured the tomatoes with her fingers.","The stake snapped and the vine lay flat in the mud.","The one remaining tomato had turned deep red overnight.","Maya whispered to the tomatoes when no one watched."],"answer":[2,3],"explanation":"The storm breaks the vine (option 1) and yet leaves one tomato that has finally ripened red (option 3) — together these mark the turning point that gives Maya her gift. The other options describe events before the storm.","points":1},{"id":"Q9","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.5.2","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"What is a theme of \"How the Coyote Brought Fire\"?","diagram":null,"options":["Animals should never trust one another.","It is dangerous to climb tall mountains.","Helping others often requires sacrifice and working together.","Cleverness alone is enough to solve any problem."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Coyote cannot bring fire alone; many animals carry it and are each marked or hurt in the effort. The story''s theme centers on sacrifice and cooperation to help the people.","points":1},{"id":"Q10","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.5.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"How does Coyote''s plan differ from the attempts of those who tried before him?","diagram":null,"options":["He waits for the brief moment at dawn and gets help from other animals.","He climbs the mountain at night while the Fire Beings sleep.","He fights the Fire Beings instead of running from them.","He asks the wise old woman to steal the fire for him."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Coyote notices the single moment at dawn when neither Fire Being is truly watching, and he arranges for other animals to relay the fire — strategies the failed attempts lacked.","points":1},{"id":"Q11","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.5.2","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P2","questionText":"This legend mainly explains —","diagram":null,"options":["how the valley people learned to farm","why coyotes live near mountains","why the Fire Beings never sleep","how certain animals got their physical features and how people got fire"],"answer":3,"explanation":"The story explains the squirrel''s curled tail, the chipmunk''s stripes, the frog''s missing tail, and how people gained fire — classic features of an origin legend.","points":1},{"id":"Q12","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.5.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"Read this sentence from the passage: \"It was the smallest of openings.\" What does the word \"openings\" mean as it is used here?","diagram":null,"options":["a hole in the mountainside","a chance or opportunity to act","a doorway into the Fire Beings'' home","the beginning of a story"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Here ''opening'' is used figuratively to mean a brief chance or opportunity — the moment when neither Fire Being is watching the fire.","points":1},{"id":"Q13","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.5.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P2","questionText":"According to the legend, why do frogs have no tails?","diagram":null,"options":["Coyote took Frog''s tail as payment for the fire.","A Fire Being grabbed Frog''s tail, and it stayed behind when Frog leaped away.","Frog burned his tail off carrying the fire.","Frog traded his tail to the tree for safety."],"answer":1,"explanation":"The text states that the Fire Beings grabbed Frog''s tail, and when Frog leaped away ''his tail stayed behind in their hands, which is why frogs have no tails.''","points":1},{"id":"Q14","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.5.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"The narrator says Coyote''s plans \"were always either very good or very bad, and sometimes both at once.\" What does this statement help the reader understand about Coyote?","diagram":null,"options":["Coyote does not care whether the people get fire.","Coyote usually fails at whatever he tries.","Coyote is unpredictable and takes risks that can succeed or backfire.","Coyote is too cautious to ever take action."],"answer":2,"explanation":"Describing his plans as both very good and very bad shows Coyote is a risk-taker whose bold ideas can succeed or go wrong — fitting his clever-but-foolish nature.","points":1},{"id":"Q15","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.5.6","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P2","questionText":"How might the story be different if it were told from the point of view of one of the Fire Beings?","diagram":null,"options":["Squirrel would be the hero of the story.","The animals would not receive any markings.","The people would never get fire.","Coyote would be shown as a thief who steals what they guard."],"answer":3,"explanation":"From the Fire Beings'' point of view, Coyote — the hero in this version — would appear as a thief taking the fire they jealously guard, reversing the reader''s sympathy.","points":1},{"id":"Q16","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.5.2","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the main idea of \"The Hidden World of Soil\"?","diagram":null,"options":["Farmers are responsible for destroying the world''s soil.","Soil takes a thousand years to form and cannot be saved.","Earthworms are the only living things found in soil.","Soil is a living system full of organisms that supports life and must be protected."],"answer":3,"explanation":"The passage explains that soil is full of living organisms, supports the plants we depend on, is threatened by erosion, and can be protected — making this the central idea.","points":1},{"id":"Q17","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.5.5","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P3","questionText":"How are the fifth and sixth paragraphs (about erosion and about protecting soil) organized?","diagram":null,"options":["They compare two different kinds of soil.","They present a problem and then offer solutions.","They describe a process in numbered steps.","They list events in the order they happened in history."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Paragraph five describes the problem (soil erosion and loss), and paragraph six describes solutions (cover crops, less plowing, planting trees) — a problem-and-solution structure.","points":1},{"id":"Q18","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.5.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"Based on the passage, what is the relationship between bacteria and the growth of large forests?","diagram":null,"options":["Bacteria are eaten by earthworms, which then feed the trees.","Bacteria block water from reaching the roots of trees.","Bacteria compete with trees for nutrients, slowing forest growth.","Bacteria break down dead material into nutrients that plants need to grow."],"answer":3,"explanation":"The text states bacteria and fungi break down dead plants and animals into nutrients plants absorb, so ''the smallest creatures make the largest forests possible.''","points":1},{"id":"Q19","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.5.4","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P3","questionText":"What is the meaning of the word \"decomposers\" as it is used in the third paragraph?","diagram":null,"options":["plants that grow in poor soil","tools that farmers use to dig","living things that break down dead material","animals that eat living plants"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The paragraph calls bacteria and fungi ''tiny decomposers'' right after explaining that they ''break down dead plants and animals,'' giving the meaning in context.","points":1},{"id":"Q20","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.5.1","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P3","questionText":"According to the passage, what is topsoil?","diagram":null,"options":["a kind of cover crop planted by farmers","the rich top layer of soil that can be carried away by erosion","the waste left behind by earthworms","the deepest layer of rock beneath the soil"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The passage defines topsoil as ''the rich top layer of soil'' that rain and wind can carry away during erosion.","points":1},{"id":"Q21","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.5.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"Read this sentence: \"In this way, the smallest creatures make the largest forests possible.\" Why does the author contrast \"smallest\" and \"largest\" in this sentence?","diagram":null,"options":["to emphasize how tiny organisms have an enormous effect","to show that forests are shrinking over time","to explain why bacteria grow into large plants","to argue that small creatures are more important than trees"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Contrasting ''smallest'' with ''largest'' highlights the surprising idea that microscopic organisms make huge forests possible — emphasizing their outsized importance.","points":1},{"id":"Q22","itemType":"multi_select","skill":"RI.5.1","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"Select two ways earthworms help the soil, according to the passage.","diagram":null,"options":["They leave behind waste that is rich in nutrients.","They eat bacteria and fungi to control them.","They plant cover crops between growing seasons.","They dig up topsoil so wind can carry it away.","Their tunnels loosen the soil so air and water reach roots."],"answer":[0,4],"explanation":"The text says earthworm waste is ''rich in nutrients'' (option 1) and that their tunnels ''loosen the soil, allowing air and water to reach plant roots'' (option 3). The other options are not supported.","points":1},{"id":"Q23","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.5.2","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"Which sentence from the passage best supports the idea that soil is fragile and in danger?","diagram":null,"options":["\"Soil is not simply dirt.\"","\"A single earthworm may seem unimportant.\"","\"Soil is a complex mixture of broken-down rock, water, air, and living and dead material.\"","\"Topsoil that took a thousand years to form can be washed away in a single season.\""],"answer":3,"explanation":"The contrast between a thousand years to form and a single season to be washed away most directly shows soil is fragile and threatened.","points":1},{"id":"Q24","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.5.2","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"What is the main idea of \"The Girl Who Mapped the Stars\"?","diagram":null,"options":["Variable stars grow brighter and dimmer over a regular cycle.","Henrietta Leavitt''s patient work gave astronomers a way to measure distances in space.","Women in the 1800s were not allowed to attend universities.","Edwin Hubble discovered that the universe is full of galaxies."],"answer":1,"explanation":"The passage centers on how Leavitt''s careful study of variable stars produced Leavitt''s Law, giving astronomers their first reliable way to measure great distances.","points":1},{"id":"Q25","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.5.4","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"In the second paragraph, the author explains that a \"computer\" was a person, not a machine. Why does the author include this explanation?","diagram":null,"options":["to explain why Leavitt was paid so little","to prove that machines were better than people at math","to prevent readers from misunderstanding the word''s older meaning","to show that Leavitt invented the first computer"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Because readers today think of a machine, the author clarifies that in that era a ''computer'' was a person doing calculations by hand, preventing confusion.","points":1},{"id":"Q26","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.5.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"What was the key relationship Leavitt discovered among the variable stars?","diagram":null,"options":["All variable stars cycled at exactly the same speed.","Stars that cycled quickly were always the largest.","Closer stars were always dimmer than distant stars.","Brighter stars took longer to complete their cycle than dimmer stars."],"answer":3,"explanation":"Leavitt noticed that brighter variable stars ''took longer to complete their cycle,'' while dimmer ones cycled quickly — a steady, predictable relationship.","points":1},{"id":"Q27","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.5.5","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"How is the passage as a whole organized?","diagram":null,"options":["by describing the same event from several points of view","in time order, following Leavitt''s life and discovery","by listing problems with the Harvard Observatory","by comparing Leavitt to Edwin Hubble throughout"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The passage moves chronologically from Leavitt''s birth and early love of astronomy, through her work and discovery, to her death and lasting legacy.","points":1},{"id":"Q28","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.5.1","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P4","questionText":"Which detail best supports the idea that Leavitt did not receive the recognition she deserved?","diagram":null,"options":["She loved astronomy from a young age.","Much of the credit for her discoveries went to the men who came after her.","She was hired at the Harvard College Observatory as a computer.","She measured more than a thousand variable stars."],"answer":1,"explanation":"The statement that credit ''went to the men who came after her'' directly supports the idea that Leavitt did not get the recognition she earned.","points":1},{"id":"Q29","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.5.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"The passage describes Leavitt''s discovery as \"a kind of cosmic measuring stick.\" What does this phrase mean?","diagram":null,"options":["a real ruler used to measure telescopes","a method for measuring enormous distances in space","a tool astronomers built out of metal","a stick used to point at stars in photographs"],"answer":1,"explanation":"A ''cosmic measuring stick'' is a figurative phrase meaning Leavitt''s law gave astronomers a reliable way to measure great distances in space.","points":1},{"id":"Q30","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.5.3","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P4","questionText":"What was the relationship between Leavitt''s discovery and Edwin Hubble''s work?","diagram":null,"options":["Hubble used Leavitt''s discovery to show the universe contains countless galaxies.","Hubble''s work proved that Leavitt''s discovery was wrong.","Hubble trained Leavitt to study variable stars.","Leavitt and Hubble made the same discovery at the same time."],"answer":0,"explanation":"The text states that Hubble ''used Leavitt''s discovery to prove that the universe is far larger than anyone had imagined, containing countless galaxies.''","points":1},{"id":"Q31","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.5.2","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"What is a theme of the poem \"The Old Oak\"?","diagram":null,"options":["Winter is the most dangerous season for living things.","Trees are stronger than any storm or lightning.","Children should not carve their names into trees.","Endurance comes from being flexible and patient through hard times."],"answer":3,"explanation":"The oak survives storms and lightning by enduring and trusting that spring will return, and it advises the young to ''bend, but do not break'' — a theme of patient endurance.","points":1},{"id":"Q32","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.5.6","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P5","questionText":"From whose point of view is the poem told?","diagram":null,"options":["a narrator watching the seasons change","a farmer resting beneath the tree","the oak tree itself","a child asking the tree questions"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The poem is spoken in the first person by the oak tree (''I have stood here a hundred years,'' ''my roots''), giving the tree its own voice.","points":1},{"id":"Q33","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.5.4","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P5","questionText":"Read these lines: \"The autumn sets my leaves on fire, / a thousand torches, gold and red.\" What do these lines mean?","diagram":null,"options":["The leaves turn bright gold and red colors in the fall.","Someone lit torches in the tree''s branches.","The tree gives off heat and light in autumn.","The tree was actually burned in a fire during autumn."],"answer":0,"explanation":"This is figurative language: comparing the autumn leaves to fire and torches describes their bright gold and red colors, not a real fire.","points":1},{"id":"Q34","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.5.4","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"Read this line: \"I am made of standing here.\" What does this line suggest about the oak?","diagram":null,"options":["The tree''s strength and identity come from enduring in one place over time.","The tree wishes it could stand somewhere else.","The tree cannot move because its roots are stuck.","The tree is made of wood that came from this place."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Saying it is ''made of standing here'' rather than ''made of fear'' means the oak''s character and strength come from having endured in one place through everything.","points":1},{"id":"Q35","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.5.5","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P5","questionText":"How does the structure of the poem, moving through spring, summer, autumn, and winter, help convey its message?","diagram":null,"options":["It shows the tree enduring through a full cycle of change and still standing.","It shows that winter is the only season that matters.","It shows that the tree changes into a different tree each season.","It lists the seasons in the order the speaker likes them."],"answer":0,"explanation":"By moving through all four seasons, the poem shows the oak surviving constant change and remaining standing, reinforcing its message of endurance.","points":1},{"id":"Q36","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RL.5.4","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P5","questionText":"In the line \"my roots like fingers gripping stone,\" the oak''s roots are compared to fingers. What does this comparison suggest?","diagram":null,"options":["The roots hold tightly and firmly to the ground.","The roots are soft and weak.","The roots are reaching up toward the sky.","The roots are shaped exactly like human hands."],"answer":0,"explanation":"Comparing roots to fingers ''gripping stone'' suggests they hold firmly and tightly to the earth, emphasizing the tree''s stability.","points":1},{"id":"Q37","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"RI.5.9","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P5","questionText":"Both \"The Old Oak\" and \"The Last Tomato\" deal with surviving storms. How do the two texts present storms differently?","diagram":null,"options":["In the poem the storm destroys the oak, while in the story the storm saves Maya''s whole garden.","Both texts treat the storm as a small, unimportant event.","In the poem storms shape the oak over many years, while in the story one storm brings a single turning point.","In the poem the storm is avoided, while in the story it never arrives."],"answer":2,"explanation":"In the poem, repeated storms over years bend and shape the oak (''the storms have bent me, year by year''); in the story, a single sudden storm is the turning point that ripens the one tomato. This is the key difference.","points":1},{"id":"Q38","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"L.5.4","difficulty":"medium","passageId":"P3","questionText":"The word \"erosion\" contains a root meaning \"to wear away.\" Based on this and the passage, what does \"erosion\" most nearly mean?","diagram":null,"options":["the wearing away and carrying off of soil by wind and water","the planting of trees to protect the land","the slow forming of new soil over time","the digging of tunnels by earthworms"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Using the root ''to wear away'' plus the passage''s description of rain and wind carrying away topsoil, erosion means the wearing away and loss of soil.","points":1},{"id":"Q39","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"L.5.4","difficulty":"easy","passageId":"P4","questionText":"In the passage, the word \"variable\" is used to describe stars that grow brighter and dimmer. The prefix and root of \"variable\" relate to \"change.\" What does \"variable\" most nearly mean?","diagram":null,"options":["located far away","extremely bright","able to change or vary","very large in size"],"answer":2,"explanation":"''Variable'' shares its root with ''vary,'' meaning to change; the passage confirms variable stars change in brightness over a cycle.","points":1},{"id":"Q40","itemType":"single_choice","skill":"L.5.5.a","difficulty":"hard","passageId":"P1","questionText":"In the first paragraph, the tomato vine \"leaned against the wooden stake like a tired old man.\" What does this figurative comparison suggest?","diagram":null,"options":["The vine was angry and ready to fall over on purpose.","The vine was heavy and drooping, needing support to stay up.","The vine belonged to an old man in the neighborhood.","The vine was actually as old as an elderly person."],"answer":1,"explanation":"Comparing the vine to ''a tired old man'' leaning on the stake suggests it was heavy and weary, needing the stake''s support to stay upright.","points":1}]}');
